<HEAD>Dukakis Says Reagan Administration Deserted American Dream</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, His speech, to UPDATE with speech
delivered; new grafs 6-9 to UPDATE with new material from news
conference</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic presidential candidate <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said Thursday the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has `` walked away from the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> dream'' with policies to help the rich at the expense of working people. `` I'm running for president because during the past seven years I've seen too many people thrown out into the streets after decades on the job. ... I've talked to too many local leaders who've seen their communities become ghost towns of boarded up hopes and foreclosed dreams,'' the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor said. His speech at Serb Hall, a traditional rallying spot for presidential hopefuls in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, came with polls suggesting <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is in a virtual dead heat with <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> heading into Tuesday's primary. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has been making a strong pitch in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> to blue-collar workers, asking them to support him as he supported striking meatpackers and paperworkers as well as <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> autoworkers about to lose their jobs because of a plant closing. While hitting hard at the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> refrained from criticizing other Democratic candidates. One day earlier, he had spoken in general terms of his differences with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and then had criticized <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> for demanding he be more specific. At a news conference after the speech, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, responding to questions, said he felt he was better qualified than <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> to be president because of his experience as a governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. But he stopped well short of criticizing <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> also called for the resignation of Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <P