<HEAD>Kenyan Ex-President's Nephew Fined $5,000 In Pot Importation
Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nephew of <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s founding president has been fined $ 5,000 and credited for time served for his role in a 1,900-pound marijuana importation conspiracy. `` For your greed, you ... have failed your government and certainly your family,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolin </PERSON> said Wednesday in sentencing <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Muigai </PERSON>, 36, nephew of <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s first president <PERSON> Jomo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON>. <PERSON> Muigai </PERSON> walked away a free man after paying the fine and serving more than five months in jail since his arrest in October on charges of conspiring to import the marijuana. Three co-defendants were sentenced to prison. <PERSON> Muigai </PERSON> pleaded guilty to conspiring to import an unspecified quantity of the drug, which carries a maximum term of five years in prison. <PERSON> Wolin </PERSON>, who sentenced two Kenyan co-defendants to six years in prison and a third to nine years for their guilty pleas, found that <PERSON> Muigai </PERSON> played a `` truly passive'' role `` limited to greed,'' in the scheme. A fifth Kenyan, millionaire arms dealer and land developer <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Mwangi </PERSON>, 49, was found innocent after a trial earlier this month. A Ugandan defendant, <PERSON> Mpigi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kabasha </PERSON> <PERSON> Mbogo </PERSON>, 39, is to be sentenced Monday. The six men were arrested after they traveled to <LOCATION> Gloucester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, where the pot had just arrived aboard a ship. They were to be paid $ 1 million in the deal, negotiated through undercover agents in telephone calls to <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>. Though <PERSON> Muigai </PERSON>'s crime was an `` affront to the people of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Wolin </PERSON> said he was satisfied <PERSON> Muigai </PERSON> was remorseful and had learned a `` bitter lesson.'' He also took note that <PERSON> Muigai </PERSON> was the first to plead guilty. <PERSON> Muigai </PERSON>, dressed in a gray pin-stripped suit and white loafers, apologized for his involvement in what he called an `` unfortunate incident.'' `` I would like to assure you, sir, that I do n't intend and I do n't think I will ever stand in another court of law for charges of any sort of criminal activity,'' he told the judge. <PERSON> Muiga </PERSON>'s his attorneys argued that <PERSON> Muigai </PERSON>'s co-defendants invited him to meet with wealthy <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businessmen interested in developing some of his property. Even after learning the discussions with the `` businessmen,'' who turned out to be federal agents, concerned marijuana, <PERSON> Muigai </PERSON> went along, hoping still to discuss the land deal, the court papers said. The stiffest sentence, nine years, went to <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Thuku </PERSON>, who <PERSON> Wolin </PERSON> determined was the principal in the deal for making the contacts with the sources of the marijuana and the other defendants. <PERSON> Wolin </PERSON> found that <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tumbo </PERSON>, 45, and <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Githegi </PERSON>, 36, had less culpability and gave them six-year prison terms. They pleaded guilty to conspiring to import more than 110 pounds of marijuana, a charge carrying a 20-year maximum penalty.
