<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There are at least four men in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> prisons who have something in common with a new inmate, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON>: They all killed somebody in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> on Aug. 26, 1986. But the similarities end there. Unlike the killer of <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, they are serving their time in obscurity. No camera-wielding mobs hounded them when they surrendered, no tabloids splashed their names in headlines. All four cases were in the impoverished <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION>, uptown from the grassy spot in Central Park where the former prep school student killed Miss <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, from the bar on <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s East Side patronized by Chambers, Miss <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> and other affluent young people. `` It is n't fair,'' said <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Traverso </PERSON>, 16, a neighbor of one of the victims, <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON> <PERSON> Dueno </PERSON>, 44. `` They make such a big deal out of <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>'s death and <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON>'s death means nothing.'' Chambers, 21, started a five - to 15-year sentence Saturday for killing Miss <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, 18, during what he initially called an episode of `` rough sex. The day before, while a jury deliberated murder charges against him, he pleaded guilty to first-degree manslaughter. Chambers and the other defendants all killed people they knew, and they were arrested quickly. Three of the four <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> killers pleaded guilty after bargaining with prosecutors, as <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> did. But none went through the protracted litigation that <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> did, and all but one are serving longer sentences. The one who received a lighter term was Ms. <PERSON> Dueno </PERSON>'s killer, <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON>. He had a history of beating Ms. <PERSON> Dueno </PERSON>, who was his girlfriend, and on Aug. 26, 1986, he stabbed her to death. He was never charged with murder. He pleaded guilty to second-degree manslaughter and was sentenced May 19 to two-and-a-third to seven years in prison. In a city that averages about five homicides a day, the deaths of Ms. <PERSON> Dueno </PERSON> and the others were largely unnoticed. The disposition of the cases went unnoticed as well: _ <ORGANIZATION> Santos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cuello </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION>, charged with second-degree murder for shooting <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON> to death, pleaded guilty last May 14 to first-degree manslaughter. Justice <PERSON> Elbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinkson </PERSON> sentenced him on June 26 to seven to 21 years in prison. _ A grand jury charged <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinones </PERSON> with second-degree murder in the stabbing of <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON> <PERSON> Pajooh </PERSON>, 48. She allegedly had shot at him once when he tried to rob her and had reported him to police. After a non-jury trial, Justice <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> convicted <PERSON> Quinones </PERSON> of first-degree manslaughter and sentenced him on Oct. 7, 1987, to 12 -LCB- to 25 years in prison. _ <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON>, indicted on a charge of second-degree murder after he smashed his father's head with a sledgehammer, pleaded guilty to first-degree manslaughter and was sentenced by Justice <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON> on Oct. 13 to six to 18 years in prison. There is no indication as to whether the families of the victims were consulted when the guilty pleas were negotiated; prosecutors gave the <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> family the right to veto their agreement with Chambers. And no news conferences were called when the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> cases were wrapped up. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> district attorney's office, said the assistant district attorneys who prosecuted the cases were not available to discuss them, or to compare them with the more celebrated case in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> `` It's apples and oranges,'' he said. `` What happened there, happened there. What happens here, happens here.''
