<HEAD>Feast for the Body Follows One for the Mind</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY MacVEAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For $ 2 or so, you can hungrily cradle a barrel of popcorn while watching characters in `` Babette's Feast'' ravish blini with black caviar, quail stuffed with foie gras and other magnificent morsels in what has to be one of the most inspiring meals ever shown on the screen. For $ 88 more, you can follow this feast for the eyes with one for the body. `` One thing will happen after you see this movie: You will be starving,'' said <PERSON> Dro </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Proudian </PERSON>, general manager at <ORGANIZATION> Petrossian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, whose restaurant is one of several around the the country serving the seven-course feast during the run of the movie, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s entry for an Academy Award as best foreign film. `` When you see the film, how complicated the meal is, how expensive, all the marketing,'' there will be a greater understanding of the art of preparing a great meal, said <PERSON> Yannick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cam </PERSON>, chef and owner at <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pavillion </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, which begins serving the feast in April. The movie, based on a story by <PERSON> Isak </PERSON> <PERSON> Dinesen </PERSON>, tells of two unmarried and pious sisters who take a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> political refugee, <PERSON> Babette </PERSON>, into their home on the bleak coast of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, in return for housekeeping. Fourteen years later, when <PERSON> Babette </PERSON> wins 10,000 francs in the lottery, she repays them with a feast so strange to them that one sister, in anticipation, compares it to a witch's sabbath But <PERSON> Babette </PERSON> fills the hearts, as well as the bellies, of her 12 guests, mostly members of the sisters' religious community. `` It was a whole experience, that's why we did it,'' said <PERSON> Stella </PERSON> <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <