see the truffles, not just a speck here, a slice there. When you put your knife into the quail, you have to feel the foie gras.'' `` It was extraordinarily difficult, because we had to recreate a visual image on a plate,'' he said. <PERSON> Petrossian </PERSON>'s chef, <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Attali </PERSON>, said he encountered one problem. In the film, the quail is served sitting in its pastry nest with the head on. Believing that would not be acceptable here, <PERSON> Attali </PERSON> fashioned pastry `` heads'' for the tiny game birds. But no matter how faithful, diners will not experience the same mood as in the film, <PERSON> Cam </PERSON> said: `` First the house in the film, and it was a little religious dinner. I do n't think we can reproduce that.'' Still, <PERSON> Proudian </PERSON> said, `` The star of the movie is the food. So if you are in this business, it's nice to see all of this dignity and respect given to the preparation of food.''
