<TEXT>
 It looks more and more as though President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will leave office without achieving his stated goal of making <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> say `` Uncle.'' In the view of many Latin American experts, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s policy of keeping the pressure on <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>'s Nicaraguan government to bring about peace and democracy has failed. `` You have peace, but you do n't have freedom,'' says <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickett </PERSON>, an expert on national and international security affairs at the <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>. `` They're about to leave office, and they've got a Contra program that's falling apart on them,'' says <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, Latin American adviser to <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>. As <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON>, senior associate specializing in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> affairs at the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, sees it, the stated goal of the policy has kept shifting. `` The first one was simply to interdict Nicaraguan arms to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> said. `` Then it was rather strongly implied that the idea was to bring down the regime. And now the idea is that if they -LRB- <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leaders -RRB- will change, everything will be all right.'' <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, the president's chief spokesman, says the administration's goal remains the same: `` The situation is that we need aid to the Contras in the worst way.'' But questions remain whether Wednesday's <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote to continue non-lethal aid and leave the door open for military aid, and the expected <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote today, will help further <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s objectives. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has said his goal is to keep pressure on the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> so they will live up to the promises of democratic reform that they made when they took over from dictator <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> in 1979. At a news conference Feb. 21, 1985, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was asked whether he was advocating the overthrow of the Nicaraguan government. His reply was: `` Not if the present government would turn around and ... say, ` Uncle. All right, come back into the revolutionary government, and let's straighten this out and institute the goals.''' Now that the two sides have agreed on a cease-fire, will <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Marxist-led Sandinista government reform? And if it does n't, can the Contra rebels the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has backed survive as an effective force? Many think not. `` I think it would be awfully difficult to reorganize them,'' said <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON>. `` I doubt if they would be particularly interested in that. I do n't think they would want to go through the convolutions of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy again.'' King added that `` it's over for the time being unless the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> back up on what they say they are going to do, and have done, and the Contras change their orientation from where they are, which is: let's get some kind of political opening going.'' <PERSON> Pickett </PERSON>, too, sees `` the end of the resistance'' in the latest developments, `` barring some miracle or barring some violation before the truce is signed.'' `` If the Sandinistas do something stupid before that, the Contras can be saved,'' he said. King, the adviser to <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, said: `` The objective of the whole exercise in the beginning was to protect <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> security concerns in the region. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> security concerns in the region are removal of the Soviet and the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> advisers, guarantees of no bases, reduction of Soviet weapons and guarantees of no border crossing. `` Now they are at a point where they do n't have any of those things arranged, they're about to leave office, and they've got a Contra program that's falling apart on them,'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said. `` I think the whole thing is a disaster, frankly.'' The less partisan sources are not calling it a disaster, but they are n't proclaiming it a success either.
</TEXT>
