<HEAD>GAO Cites Weaknesses in Military Purchasing Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Congressional investigators say the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Logistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> should tighten controls over its `` fast-pay'' program to avoid paying for supplies that are never delivered. According to a <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> report released today, one <ORGANIZATION> DLA </ORGANIZATION> purchasing office failed to take action to ensure collection of more than $ 7 million in overpayments. `` I'm appalled that <ORGANIZATION> DLA </ORGANIZATION> is paying money for supplies that it never received,'' said Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, who, along with Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, R-Calif., released the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report `` We need sound business management at <ORGANIZATION> DLA </ORGANIZATION>.'' The agency purchases food, clothing, fuel oil and other supplies for the armed services. Under the fast-pay program, the agency pays vendors based on shipping invoices instead of verifying receipt of the supplies. The procedure is designed to expedite payments for small purchases. `` Internal controls established by the <ORGANIZATION> DLA </ORGANIZATION> purchasing offices do not prevent possible fast-pay program abuse,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` Potential missing depot shipments are not always detected for timely follow-up and resolution.'' The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said that in 52 fast-pay shipments valued at $ 71,267 to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, the center could not document the receipt of 16 shipments valued at $ 18,618. In addition, the center failed to notify some of the vendors of the missing shipments within 90 days. It also said action had not been taken as of last May to collect more than $ 7 million in previously identified overpayments owed the Defense Personnel Support Center in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> also said that vendors with performance problems on previous contracts have continued to receive fast-pay awards and that controls have not been established to ensure the receipt of supplies sent directly from vendors to overseas locations. In 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> issued instructions to limit the use of fast pay, saying it should not be used to replace stocks in depots or when timely payment can be made. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> DLA </ORGANIZATION> believes it is not required to follow the requirements until they are incorporated into the Federal Acquisition Regulations. However, <ORGANIZATION> DLA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said the agency plans to be in compliance with the <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> requirements by the end of the year even though it is expected to cost an additional $ 2.5 million to process the extra paperwork.
