<HEAD>House Votes To Rehire Some Controllers Fired In 1981</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislation calling for the rehiring of 1,000 air traffic controllers fired nearly seven years ago has won strong approval in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, although the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has yet to consider a similar bill. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has steadfastly refused to rehire any of the 11,400 controllers who were fired after they walked off their jobs in 1981. The <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has urged that such legislation be vetoed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> if it clears <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The 234-180 <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote Wednesday calling for some of the fired controllers to return to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> came two years after similar legislation was defeated by a 193-226 margin. Supporters of the legislation argued that there are too few controllers to handle air traffic needs, especially at some of the busiest towers and traffic control centers, and that the former controllers could become fully trained more quickly than trainees off the street. Rep. <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Molinari </PERSON>, sponsor of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> resolution, said a selected number of fired controllers should be rehired by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> `` for the sake of safety and the convenience of the flying public.'' `` Today it's clearer than ever that the air traffic control system is still severely strained,'' <PERSON> Molinari </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, said during floor debate. The legislation calls for selectively hiring 500 of the fired controllers this year and another 500 next fiscal year. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, has estimated that as many as 6,000 of the 11,400 former controllers still have an interest in returning to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>. Under the legislation the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> would be free to select the controllers it wants to rehire. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has steadily been increasing its controller workforce and now has 14,450 controllers at various experience levels, compared with 16,375 before the 1981 strike. The <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> plans to hire another 1,350 over the next 1 -LCB- years. While support for rehiring at least some of the fired controllers was widespread, some congressmen continued to have deep concerns about such a move. `` Putting the strikers and their replacements in the same control tower is sure to create animosity between the two factions,'' suggested Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammerschmidt </PERSON>, R-Ark. Rep. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, said the legislastion is `` sending the wrong message'' to government workers and their unions. `` The right to fire illegal strikers must not be compromised,'' <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> declared.
