 Audiences seem to know what he means, but Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> does n't always get the words out exactly right as he campaigned this week in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. During an appearance at <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Univeristy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Appleton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, the Republican presidential candidate told his audience, `` I want to be the education president.'' `` There is a need for help at the federal level ... so you can afford to send your college to children,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> declared. At another time in the same speech, he meant to talk about the `` high cost of college,'' but it came out: `` the high cost of courage.'' Speaking to a rally in a <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> suburb, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> appeared to invent a new federal tax on farmers, declaring he favored a lower `` capital grains tax.'' No doubt, he was referring to the capital gains tax. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has urged a partial repeal of the part of the 1987 tax overhaul law that taxes capital gains _ such as from the sale of a house, stocks or business assets _ at the same level as other income. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s verbal tongue-twisting seems to be catching. Introducing the vice president at another Milwaukee-area function, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> asserted: `` As the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presidency ends, it's time for the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> pregnancy to begin.''
