<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 At an aviation musuem in <LOCATION> Oshkosh </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was presented with a brown leather aviator's jacket and he climbed readily into the cockpit of a 1949 Bearcat fighter. The plane was billed as similar to one he had flown as a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> pilot during World War II, a past his campaign strategists would like to have remembered as often as possible. Well, it was n't exactly like the kind of planes he used to fly, `` but it has the same engine,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. Then <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who frequently has posed on and in various kinds of heavy equipment during his campaign, held his right arm over his head and flashed a `` V'' sign for photographers. `` Is this the Red Baron look?'' he asked. Then <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was led to a full-scale replica of the Voyager, the lightweight plane that set a record for flying non-stop around the world. `` I'm anxious to learn about this,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` This looks like it may be a little tough.'' He elaborated further. `` There's the inevitable question,'' he said. `` How does one go to the bathroom?''
