<HEAD>Presidential Yacht, Rescued from Oblivion, on National Tour</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The restored presidential yacht USS Sequoia is making a national tour before being returned once again to the president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> after an 11-year hiatus. The Sequoia, which was sold in 1977 by President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> as part of an austerity move, has been repaired by a private group. It was launched Wednesday on a 100-city, 22-state tour that will enable thousands to see the vessel before it is officially returned to the White House Nov. 15. `` What we have here is a Fourth of July celebration every weekend in cities throughout the country,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> McGehee </PERSON>, a member of the group that raised money to repair the 105-foot yacht. `` We're taking a piece of American history to the American people.'' Private and corporate funding paid for the Sequoia's restoration, and <PERSON> Josh </PERSON> <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON>, who chairs the nine-member <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yacht </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION>'s board of trustees, hopes the tour will raise money for an endowment to pay for the ship's upkeep `` This tour is a little like running a campaign,'' he joked. `` We have a good candidate, no opposition, and we're confident she wo n't screw up on the evening news.'' The Sequoia was built in 1925 and sold to the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in 1931. In 1933, after President <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> wintered on it in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, the Sequoia was acquired by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and became the president's official yacht. Over the next 44 years, the Sequoia served eight presidents. It was the site of talks on nuclear controls during the <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> administration, the venue of gala celebrations by President <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and the place where President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> told his family in 1974 that he would resign the presidency. In 1977, as part of a widespread retrenchment program, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> directed that the vessel be sold. It was purchased for $ 286,000 by a group of private investors. Over the next four years, the craft changed hands three times and began to deteriorate. In 1981, a private trust was established to purchase and restore the boat. After reading news accounts in 1983 about the boat's dilapidated condition, <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON>, a former aide to Sen. <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Talmadge </PERSON>, D-Ga., joined the effort to refurbish the craft `` I remember thinking it was a crying shame that this boat had fallen on such bad times, because I remember how it was used in the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> administrations,'' he said. Minor repairs were made, and a little-publicized, 16-state tour during the summer of 1984 drew surprisingly large crowds. `` Everyone told us it was a mistake for the federal government to have sold the Sequoia,'' <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON> said. `` We then started raising money for a full restoration, with the intention of returning the vessel to the office of the president.'' In June 1986, a six-month, $ 3.5 million restoration was completed, and the Sequoia sailed to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for the Statue of Liberty centennial celebration. Since then, the Sequoia has been moored in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and used for government functions. The Sequoia's tour will include ports in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> in April, and to <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> cities in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> in May. It then will sail up the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in June and July, stopping at ports in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. After visiting Great Lakes ports in August, the Sequoia will stop at cities between <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> in September. The tour will end Oct. 30 in <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>.
