<FIRST>r w PM-Retirees'Taxes Bjt   03-31 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retirees' Taxes, Bjt,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retirees Spared Pension Tax Underpayment Penalties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retirees do n't have to worry any more about being penalized for underpayment of estimated taxes on their 1987 pensions. The <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> announced Wednesday that it will waive penalties that otherwise would hit retirees who failed to pay sufficient tax in advance on their pensions. `` The idea is to have equity between retired people and wage earners,'' said <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Johnell </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>. `` Retired people will now have the same benefits as wage earners.'' The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> announced last year that it would not impose penalties on taxpayers who had too little withheld from their 1987 wages. That announcement was made because of widespread taxpayer confusion about the numerous tax-law revisions enacted in 1986 and a complex new W-4 withholding form. Even with these two waivers, taxpayers with large amounts of interest, dividends and other investment income still might be penalized if they have to pay too much tax when they file their returns. But the penalty would not apply to wage or pension portions of income. As a rule, at least 90 percent of 1987 tax liability must have been paid in advance through withholding or estimated quarterly payments. Withholding is not required on pensions, although most recipients opt to have tax taken out from each check. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> said most retirees will be automatically covered by the waiver without having to take any additional action. Those who have already filed a return and paid the estimated-tax penalty will have any overpayment refunded. A taxpayer who receives a penalty notice dated before May 2, 1988, and has not responded should call the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> toll-free line for assistance, the agency said. That number is 800-424-1040. The waiver applies to any retirement income that must be reported on Line 16b of Form 1040, including <ORGANIZATION> Individual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retirement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounts </ORGANIZATION> and profit-sharing distributions, employee savings plans, pensions and annuities. In another decision affecting retirees, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> said owners of multiple IRAs who passed the age of 70 -LCB- in 1987 will be allowed more discretion in choosing from which <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> to take a distribution. Such <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> owners are required to take money from an <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> by April 1. A recent change in the law required those with multiple <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> accounts to divide the minimum required distribution among those accounts. Under the change announced Wednesday a past-70 -LCB- <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> owner still will have to calculate a required distribution from each account but may then choose to take the entire payout from any one or more accounts. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> announcement said taxpayers who already have received payouts from their IRAs and want to take advantage of the new rule may be able to return the distribution to one or more accounts under existing `` rollover'' provisions. In general, an <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> owner has a 60-day period each year during which an account may be rolled over into another. This change could benefit, for example, a retiree who has some high-earning IRAs and some that are earning less. The retiree might find it beneficial to take the required minimum distribution from the less lucrative <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> and keep the high earner intact.
</TEXT>
