<HEAD>Woman Undergoes Abortion Before Appeals Court Issues Restraining
Order</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with official saying woman
underwent abortion before receiving restraining order. CORRECTS
spelling of lawyer's name to Dolowitz sted Dorowitz. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KIRK MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An 18-year-old woman, whose quest to end her pregnancy was upheld by a district court but blocked an hour later by the <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, obtained an abortion between the two rulings Wednesday, a court spokeswoman said. The appellate court had scheduled a Monday hearing to consider 25-year-old <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>' appeal of 3rd District Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>'s decision to vacate an earlier restraining order, which banned <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>' estranged wife, <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON>, from ending her pregnancy, in its eighth weeks. The higher court's ruling was issued within an hour of <PERSON> Young </PERSON>'s decision, but <PERSON> Mrs. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>, who did not attend the court proceedings, had an abortion before she was served with the appellate court order, said <PERSON> Rosemary </PERSON> <PERSON> Gacnik </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the state court system `` She did have the abortion before she was served with the papers, which would've prevented her from doing so,'' <PERSON> Gacnik </PERSON> said. `` It was during that time lapse between when the ban was lifted and when the <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> issued its own restraining order.'' <PERSON> Gacnik </PERSON> said Monday's hearing was now `` a moot issue,'' although Mrs. <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>' attorneys had not filed a motion to vacate the appellate court's order as of the close of court offices late Wednesday. `` I would n't be surprised if her attorney filed a motion to vacate the hearing, but that remains to be seen,'' <PERSON> Gacnik </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, who last week ruled that Mrs. <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> could not have an abortion pending resolution of a divorce-related custody dispute involving both a 10-month-old infant and the unborn child, accepted arguments by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> attorneys Wednesday that the woman has a constitutional right to end her pregnancy. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said while <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> may have the right to be consulted about any abortion involving Mrs. <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>, she had the ultimate authority over whether to carry the fetus to term. Following the hearing, defense attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dolowitz </PERSON> said he believed his client would `` secure an abortion'' as soon as possible. <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>' attorney, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> <PERSON> Barker </PERSON>, said Monday's hearing might be pointless if the fetus had been aborted. `` If the abortion has taken place, we're going to have to make some serious evaluation ... there's a pretty good argument that would make it moot,'' he said. <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> is one of four states with laws requiring wives to notify husbands of abortion decisions. During arguments before <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dolrowitz </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> wanted the court to order Mrs. <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> to `` do what he -LRB- Reynolds -RRB- wants to do with her body.'' Young's earlier restraining order was in effect `` telling my client that she must use her body to carry his baby,'' <PERSON> Dolowitz </PERSON> added. Co-counsel <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled in <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> that husbands have no veto power over their wives' abortion decisions The high court ruled that when a husband and wife disagree over an abortion, `` the view of only one of the two marriage partners can prevail. Inasmuch as it is the woman who physically bears the child and who is the more directly and immediately affected by the pregnancy ... the balance weighs in her favor,'' <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> said.
