<HEAD>Woman Believed World's Oldest Person Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOSHEN, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ulysses </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> was in the White House and Gen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Custer </PERSON> was one year away from making his last stand when <PERSON> Orpha </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> was born Aug. 13, 1875. Mrs. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>, believed by the <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> to be the world's oldest person, died Wednesday at age 112. She had pneumonia recently, but an official cause of death was not released, said <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Hostetler </PERSON>, director of nursing at <LOCATION> Fountainview </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nursing </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Home </LOCATION>, where Mrs. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> lived. `` Her condition worsened during the weekend,'' Miss <PERSON> Hostetler </PERSON> said. `` She could n't do anything for herself anymore,'' said a stepdaughter-in-law, <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>. `` You ca n't do anything for a person who does n't want to live anymore.'' <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> said she was saddened by the death, but said Mrs. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> had lived a good life. Last month, <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> officials said they believed she was the oldest person alive. Mrs. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> was honored at a special ceremony in January when officials placed the <LOCATION> Goshen </LOCATION> city seal on census documents indicating she was born in 1875 on the family farm near <LOCATION> Middlebury </LOCATION> about 10 miles away. She spent most of her life in <LOCATION> Middlebury </LOCATION> until moving to the nursing home in 1982. <PERSON> Florence </PERSON> <PERSON> Knapp </PERSON>, who lived in a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> suburb, had been recognized as the world's oldest person until her death Jan. 11. She was 114 years and 94 days old. Guinness restricts recognition to those who can provide birth records and other documentation. There had been some confusion whether Mrs. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> would be 112 or 113 last Aug. 13. For years she had maintained she was a year older than she actually was. But a document found in the public library in this northern <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> city last September showed that the former <PERSON> Orpha </PERSON> <PERSON> Ulery </PERSON> was 4 years old when she was counted in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Census of 1880, making her 112. Mrs. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> attributed her longevity to her strict obedience to a biblical command, <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> said. `` She honored her father and mother. That's it,'' she said. For many years Mrs. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> taught Sunday school in the <LOCATION> Elkhart </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Goshen </LOCATION> areas. When she was 93, she resumed writing poetry, a hobby she had stopped in the 1920s. Mrs. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> married <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mischler </PERSON>, a minister, in 1897. After his death, she married <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> in 1947. He died in 1959.
