<FIRST>r w PM-ContraAidChronology     03-31 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contra Aid Chronology,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Contra Aid Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Since President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> took office in 1981, his policy of financing the Contra rebels in their war against <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Sandinista government has been one of the most divisive foreign-policy questions facing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the nation. Here is a chronology of the ups and downs of that policy: 1981 _ <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, late in the year, approves $ 19 million in covert military aid to the rebels. The money, to be managed by the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>, is part of a classified intelligence bill. 1982 _ A second infusion of $ 19 million, again part of a classified bill, is approved. This time, restrictive provisions are added that prevent any of the money from being used to overthrow the Sandinista government. There are reports, as well, that the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> has used an additional $ 10 million from its contingency fund. 1983 _ The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> votes to end Contra aid, but a later compromise results in the appropriation of $ 24 million for the rebels. This time, the money is appropriated openly, and the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> is barred from using any money from its contingency fund to supplement the new aid. 1984 _ In April, reports surface that the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> has supervised the mining of three Nicaraguan ports, and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> votes to cut off aid to the rebels. But at the end of the year, lawmakers vote to set aside $ 14 million for the rebels, to be released after Feb. 28, 1985, if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approves in a separate vote at that time. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adds new restrictions, saying the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> may not use the money to support paramilitary operations in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> unless specifically authorized by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. 1985 _ In April the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> votes to release the $ 14 million, but the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> votes against the resolution, denying the money to the rebels. That summer, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approves $ 27 million for the Contras but restricts its use to food, clothing, medicine and other `` humanitarian'' aid. The money is directed to be used by the administration as leverage to promote peace negotiations, and the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> are barred from any role in distributing the money. 1986 _ In the fall, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approves $ 100 million _ its largest single appropriation for the rebels _ the bulk of it for military aid. Restrictions on the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>'s role are lifted, except that the agency remains barred from using its contingency fund. 1987 _ In March, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passes a moratorium on Contra aid in an effort to hold up the final $ 40 million of the aid bill approved in 1986, but the measure dies in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. At the end of the fiscal year, on Sept. 30, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> begins a series of stopgap funding measures that include money for `` non-lethal'' aid for the rebels totaling another $ 20 million. 1988 _ Under procedures laid out in late 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Feb. 3 kills President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s request for $ 36 million in rebel aid, including $ 3.6 million in military aid. A month later, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> also rejects a Democratic alternative that would have provided $ 30 million in solely humanitarian aid. The rebels reach a negotiated truce with the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> on March 23, and a new $ 48 million proposal is drafted in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> with bipartisan support.
</TEXT>
