<HEAD>Senate Panel Passes Budget Plan Following Reagan's Priorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A big boost for the space program along with cuts in aid to local and state governments are contained in the $ 1.1 trillion fiscal 1989 budget approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The plan, closer to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s priorities than the budget passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> earlier this month, was approved 18-3 on Wednesday and sent to the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for consideration. Committee chairman <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., and Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the panel's senior Republican, drafted the bipartisan compromise and it sailed through the committee in a single day There's even an outside chance <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will meet its April 15 deadline for final budget action, although the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> does n't plan to vote on the resolution until after next week's holiday recess. But opponents and supporters complained that while they were living up to the terms of last fall's deficit reduction agreement with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, the result was to put off much-needed fiscal reforms until next year. `` We need to get this out and then start showing what the problems are going to be,'' said <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>. Sen. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, R-Colo., said it was mostly a plan to `` get past the November election. `` There's an old saying, ` No guts, no glory,''' said <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>. `` And this is a no-glory budget.'' <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> and Sens. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Symms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.D. </LOCATION>, voted against the plan. Total deficit reduction in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budget proposal would be $ 7.2 billion, accomplished in part by holding spending on most programs short of the full inflation increases they would normally get. More than half the saving would come from selling off government assets. It would meet the $ 136 billion deficit-reduction target of the Gramm-Rudman budget balancing law only because the committee decided to use optimistic White House economic projections. The non-partisan <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> predicts a deficit more than $ 30 billion higher. Last fall's pact with the president set overall spending limits of $ 294 billion, $ 16.1 billion for foreign aid and $ 169.2 billion for domestic spending other than Social Security and entitlement programs. The agreement also included $ 14 billion in new taxes that were enacted last year and will be in effect for fiscal 1989, which begins Oct. 1. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budget envisions spending $ 13 billion of the domestic allocation on space and science in the year beginning Oct. 1, about the same amount <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> requested and nearly $ 1 billion more than the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved. In addition to the 27 percent increase for the space program, that money would boost <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> programs by 11 percent and move ahead the proposed construction of a giant physics project known as the superconducting super collider. Like the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee declined to kill any programs, relying instead on across-the-board spending restraint to reach deficit-reduction targets without making those tough choices in an election year. But while most programs would get at least a partial inflation boost, community and regional development would be cut $ 100 million from last year's $ 5.8 billion last year. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION>, said aid to localities has been cut too deeply already during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years. `` The priorities of this thing are out of whack,'' he said of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan. A Republican amendment to carry out some of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s plan to eliminate those development programs was withdrawn, and <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> was defeated when he tried to require selling off two federally owned oil tracts, and said that, `` Sooner or later, we're going to have to get rid of some programs.'' But it was, <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> said, still a `` a fair, balanced budget.'' The proposal would, like the administration and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> budgets, call for big increases in spending on AIDS research, air traffic safety and education. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan assumes that if legislation providing catastrophic health insurance for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> recipients is approved, there will be an accompanying increase in premiums to cover the cost. An additional $ 500 million would be provided to continue supplying cheese and other surplus commodities to the needy. Like the president's budget, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan would grant 4.3 percent pay raises for the military and 2 percent for civilian federal workers. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> adopted a 3 percent across-the-board pay hike.
