<HEAD>Teamsters Win Right To Try To Organize Coors Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> has eliminated a rival in trying to unionize the once bitterly anti-union <ORGANIZATION> Adolph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> after organizing <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION>'s newest brewery just two weeks ago. The <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday awarded sole organizing rights to the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION>' lead brewery at <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, less than 50 miles away from the new <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> facility at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Collins </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo </LOCATION><LOCATION> . </LOCATION> The labor federation ordered one of its veteran affiliates, the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, to withdraw from its campaign to organize the same 3,200 <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> workers, saying the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> had a much better chance of succeeding. The decision was an outgrowth of the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>' decision last October to reaffiliate their 1.6 million members with the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>. The union was expelled from the federation 30 years earlier on charges of corruption. A major factor in the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to readmit the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> was ending the expensive fights and membership raids that the two organizations constantly waged against each other. Many employers often were able to avoid collective bargaining altogether by playing one union against the other. The <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> last September had awarded the sole organizing rights at <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> to the Machinists. The Teamsters had challenged that ruling as soon as they were re-admitted to the federation last Nov. 1. <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION>, in the face of an intensive organizing effort by the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> since early 1986, last August signed an agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> ending a 10-year-old nationwide boycott of its beer by the labor movement. In exchange, the company agreed to forgo erecting the usual legal hurdles available to employers in opposing unions and allow an <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> affiliate an unfettered attempt to organize its Golden work force. However, that was before the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> were back in the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>. And Teamsters officials admitted they now have concerns now about how the Coors-AFL-CIO pact will hold up in the face of Wednesday's action `` We're elated,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Klare </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>' 100,000-member brewery and soft drinks division `` But there's a lot to be found out yet. We've got to meet with Coors and determine if they accept the fact that the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> picked us.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> had argued before an arbitrator picked by <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> that the Teamsters should give up the <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> effort based on last September's decision. The <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> countered they had an ongoing organizing campaign at <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> a year before the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> entered the picture and had gotten signatures on Teamster union cards from more than 30 percent of the workers at Golden. <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> agreed with the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>, according to witnesses at the arbitration proceedings. `` It was a black-and-white case,'' said <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> <PERSON> Saporta </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>' director of organizing. `` We were there first and they did n't have a single card signed. We're also the predominant union in the industry. We have contracts at all 12 <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> breweries covering some 9,000 workers.'' Ms. <PERSON> Saporta </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> have another tactical advantage in that it also has union contracts representing employees of more than 180 local distributors of Coors' products nationwide. The <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> just last week ratified a new contract with <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> raising the base pay for brewery production workers from its current $ 16.50 an hour to $ 17.25 over the next three years. Just a week earlier, the union won a an organizing effort at <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION>'s newest facility at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Collins </LOCATION> to represent its current work force of about 340 people, which is expected to grow to 550 by next January. `` That was one of the factors the arbitrator took into consideration,'' <PERSON> Klare </PERSON> said. `` Coors workers are averaging about $ 3.50 to $ 4 an hour less than our members. Seeing how fellow workers down the road are doing gives them a big incentive to come in.''
