<HEAD>Jackson Says He's A Leader, Even If He Hasn't Held Office</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: May be topped with morning events</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CUDAHY, Wisc. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, answering critics who say he lacks the government experience to be president, says `` Some leaders do n't hold office.'' The Democratic presidential candidate also accused fellow hopeful <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of personal attacks on him, a day after <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> lacked the qualifications for the presidency. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> returned to a site of his activism last year to emphasize Wednesday that his personal style of leadership has been in the streets, not in the government halls. `` Leadership stands with the people in the time of crisis,'' he told about a 1,000 people at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Frederick </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> here late Wednesday. `` I stood with the people ... I stood with the P-40 workers in <PERSON> Cudahy </PERSON>.'' Almost exactly a year ago _ on <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> Sunday 1987 _ <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> marched in the streets of this <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> suburb to protest management's actions in the strike of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> local at the <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cudahy </PERSON> meatpacking plant here. Workers went on strike on Jan. 4, 1987, and are still out. Replacement workers have been hired, but the company, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Smithfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION>, is trying to reoganize under the backruptcy laws. `` In your time of crisis, you called out to me and I responded,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told the crowd. `` In the time of this nation's crisis, I want to be your president and I need your help. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> began a three-day <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> campaign swing Wednesday after a day of private meetings in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> with key leaders of the party's <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> establishment and with campaign aides. He planned a full day of campaigning across the state both today and Saturday. `` Some officeholders are leaders. Some leaders do n't hold office,'' he said. `` But leaders stand with the people in the hour of hardship and challenge.'' On Tuesday, fellow <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> attacked <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> for lacking the requisite experience to be president, and criticized his foreign policy views. On Wednesday, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said he viewed <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s comments as `` attacks, which were more personal than principled.'' The two were to meet, but it fell through. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, told of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s remark, asked: `` Is there supposed to be some unwritten rule why <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> can not be criticized, why his positions have to be just sacrosanct and nobody can say anything about them for fear somebody will just misinterpret what you're saying? <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> did not refer to <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> directly in his speech, but he did tell reporters that he will lay his differences with the other candidates as appropriate. `` If there are distinctions, I will discuss them,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. He emphasized that he wanted to keep his message positive and pledged not to engage in personal attacks. But <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s campaign manager, told reporters on the plane that <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> `` is the Democratic bully'' who has attacked other candidates before. <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> derided <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> for saying complimentary things about <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in a Monday debate and then criticizing <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> the next day. `` <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> does n't deserve your attention or ours until he starts winning some votes _ or at least breaks into double digits,'' <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s recently poor showing in primaries. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s speech at the Cudahy church laid out more specifically than before his definition of leadership. `` I have learned to lead in the gap ... the leadership gap in the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the Executive Office building,'' he said. `` When the drugs flow into our country, Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> just says no. Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> just says nothing. Mr. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> does nothing. `` I led the drive to ban drugs and to ban guns,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> listed a variety of his previous actions as demonstrations of leadership. He mentioned his `` standing with the auto workers at <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION>'' <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> closed a plant shortly after promising to keep it open for several more years. He talked of standing with family farmers at foreclosure sales. He talked of his leadership in the fight against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and in personally asking Soviet leaders to improve human rights in that nation. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> refered to his campaign as featuring `` a clear message and an authentic leader who speaks directly to the people.''
