<HEAD>Dollar Dips, Stocks Lose Ground in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar dropped nearly one yen against the Japanese currency in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> trading Thursday, while stock prices declined slightly after three days of substantial gains. The dollar opened at 125.15 yen and slumped to 124.50 yen at the close, down 0.93 yen from Wednesday's close of 125.43 yen. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, which rose 366.89 points on Wednesday to a post-crash high, slipped 59.81 points, closing at 26,260.26 points. `` Fiscal year-end demand for dollars, which supported the dollar in early trading, has come to an end,'' said an official of a major commercial bank in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The Japanese fiscal year ends Thursday. On the stock exchange, traders said the market has come to a rest after three days of sharp gains. The Nikkei Stock Average surged more than 1,000 points in the previous three sessions. Wednesday's close of the stock market's key barometer was 26,319.98 points, the first close above 26,000 since last October's market crash
