<HEAD>Iran Boosts Fuel Imports As Tanker War Takes Its Toll</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Iraqi air raids on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s refineries and tankers in recent weeks appear to be taking an increasing toll on <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s vital oil industry as the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war escalates sharply. Shipping analysts believe the Iraqis will intensify air strikes aimed at throttling <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s oil exports while hammering <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and other cities in a drive to pressure <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to the negotiating table. `` We ca n't see an end to the tanker war,'' <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramheim </PERSON> of the Oslo-based <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tanker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Owners </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We had hoped the tanker war was coming to an end after a recent lull, but the situation is worse now than it's been for a long time. You think it's reached a peak, and then it just gets worse,'' he said in a phone interview. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, one of the world's major oil producers, is having to import record amounts of refined petroleum products, such as kerosene and jet fuel, the Middle East Economic Survey reported this week. `` This unprecedented sudden import of gas oil could be due to damage inflicted on Iranian refineries because of the war,'' the respected oil industry newsletter noted. But it noted as well that <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> may also be `` taking precautionary measures and stocking up these products in anticipation of a further escalation in the war.'' The sudden surge in refined imports has strategic implications in the 7 -LCB- - year-old war It coincides with an unprecedented Iraqi missile bombardment of <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and other key cities over the last month. The Iranians may fear their battered refineries could be knocked out altogether. The Economic Survey, a weekly published in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, said the Iranians have chartered a 200,000-ton tanker from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s Marimpex trading company to deliver a full load of gas oil _ more than 2 million barrels _ from <LOCATION> Rotterdam </LOCATION> next month The Iranians have already taken delivery of nearly 3 million 42-gallon barrels of gas oil in recent weeks, industry sources noted. That is a massive increase over the 300,000 barrels a day it has been importing for the last 18 months. Recent Iraqi air raids have reduced <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s domestic refining capacity by as much as one-third. A large formation of Iraqi fighter-bombers attacked <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s big <LOCATION> Kharg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> oil terminal in the northern end of the gulf on March 19, badly damaging two of the estimated 25 tankers that shuttle oil to makeshift terminals farther south for transshipment to delivery tankers. The 316,379-ton Avaj and the 249,829-ton <LOCATION> Sanandaj </LOCATION> were left in flames with 50 crewmen killed. Shipping sources said both vessels were so badly hit they will likely be scrapped. The loading facilities on <LOCATION> Kharg </LOCATION>, heavily defended by anti-aircraft missile batteries, also were damaged, the economic survey said. The main systems on the west of the island were knocked out in the bombing, forcing the Iranians to switch loading to a smaller jetty, slowing down exports that are <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s main source of revenue for its war effort. Several other shuttle tankers, either owned by the state-run <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iranian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tanker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, or chartered by it, are believed to have been put out of action in recent <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> air strikes. `` The Iraqis are the key,'' stressed <PERSON> Ramheim </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tanker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Owners </ORGANIZATION>. `` Now they're attacking again, we think the situation's going to get worse because <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> always retaliates.'' Because <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s gulf ports have been closed since the early days of the war, the Iranians have to take revenge by attacking neutral ships. After <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> reported three air strikes on Iranian tankers, Iranian gunboats on Monday attacked a Danish supertanker and a Norwegian-operated tanker, setting both ablaze. London-based <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION> says 4.7 million tons of shipping has been sunk or written off since December because of the tanker war. That includes the 280,000-ton Iranian tanker Susangird, which went down after it was set on fire by Iraqi Exocet missiles, killing 21 crewmen. Altogether, about 15 million tons of shipping has been lost since 1981, <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> and other agencies reported. That's more than half the 24 million tons of merchant shipping sunk in World War II. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> must ship its oil exports through the gulf, where its tankers are prey to marauding Iraqi jets. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> exports its oil through pipelines across neighboring <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> which are far less vulnerable to attack.
