<HEAD>`21st Century Medicine' Finding New Ways To Test, Manage Stress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Someday, doctors will have a system for identifying stress-plagued patients who are headed for heart trouble even though their blood pressure readings may look normal, says a heart researcher. Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eliot </PERSON>, a cardiovascular researcher from <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, told cardiologists meeting in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> this week that new ways of testing can identify `` hot reactors'' _ stressed but seemingly healthy people. `` These are people who fight saber-toothed tigers 30, 40 times a day and do n't even know it,'' <PERSON> Eliot </PERSON> told reporters Wednesday at the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cardiology </ORGANIZATION>. `` A doctor ca n't tell from resting blood pressure -LRB- tests taken at rest -RRB-,'' he said, adding that conventional blood pressure readings do n't tell how much blood is pumping or how much resistance the heart is fighting. <PERSON> Eliot </PERSON>, director of the cardiovascular institute at <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>'s Swedish <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, has worked 10 years on ways to measure the rapid, stress-induced fluctuations in the cardiovascular system That work, he said, has yielded a 30-minute test using devices to monitor heart performance, blood pressure and other factors to find `` hot reactors,'' who apparently make up more than 10 percent of the population. With so many seemingly healthy people at risk of illness, within three to eight months in some cases, he said, `` I think it's worth testing in people.'' <PERSON> Eliot </PERSON> and his colleagues plan to expand their efforts to three other locations next year. Someday soon, he hopes, physicians will agree on a standard way of conducting such stress tests. `` We have a model,'' he said. `` It's been successful.'' Those efforts are part of what <PERSON> Eliot </PERSON> terms `` a new kind of medicine,'' emphasizing not just technical medical techniques, but beneficial lifestyle adjustments. Some, he noted, have called it `` medicine from the 21st century _ teaching people what they can do for themselves.'' `` Drugs and surgery are not sufficient for most people'' with cardiovascular problems, said Dr. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Ornish </PERSON>, an assistant professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> and president of the <ORGANIZATION> Preventative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. `` Cardiology has tended to ignore the role of the brain on the heart,'' <PERSON> Ornish </PERSON> said.
