<HEAD>Taiwan Replacing Nuclear Plant That Concerned U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government official today confirmed that <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> is replacing a research nuclear reactor. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> long has worried the reactor could be used in an atomic weapons development program. <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuang-chi </PERSON>, secretary-general of the government <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was assisting in converting the reactor to a new system that would provide `` less possibility to produce plutonium,'' a key component in the production of atomic weapons. The comments were made one week after <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration pressured <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> to close the reactor and to stop work on a secret installation that could have processed the reactor's spent fuel to extract plutonium. <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> had earlier confirmed that the research reactor at Lung Tan, 25 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION>, was closed in January but denied the move was made because of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pressure. Today, however, he acknowledged that `` maybe there's some influence -LRB- from -RRB- the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>'' behind the decision to replace the reactor, adding that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> `` did express its concern about our research.'' The energy official said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> concern over Lung Tan goes back many years and may partly be caused by reports that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> developed atomic weaponry using a reactor of the same design. <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> reiterated <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s position of not developing atomic bombs and said of the Lung Tan overhaul, `` Since we decided not to make -LRB- atomic -RRB- weapons, why not make them -LRB- the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> -RRB- happy?'' <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> said the main reason for changing Lung Tan's design was to make it compatible with <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s nuclear power reactors, which run on a different system. `` It's a major change, the reactor is completely changed,'' <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> said. `` It is a very major task ... It is keeping everybody busy.'' He said the conversion would take at least two years, but he did not have a cost estimate. According to <PERSON> Liu </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is providing technical help and will provide assistance in obtaining fuel for testing the new core. The Lung Tan reactor, which opened in 1973, has used heavy water to control the splitting of atomic nuclei, a system that can use natural uranium as fuel. The reactor is being converted to a `` light water'' system that requires enriched uranium fuel. <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuo-lung </PERSON>, professor of physics of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taiwan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said the high-tech production of enriched uranium is limited to a few countries, making the fuel comparatively difficult to obtain and its use easier to monitor. <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> can not make the enriched fuel. <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> also stressed that <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> does n't have facilities to process spent fuel into weapons-grade plutonium. When asked whether <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> had worked on a secret processing installation, he replied: `` Baloney.'' Still, local newspapers have been filled with reports that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government learned from a missing top-level Taiwanese nuclear researcher that <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> had plans to make nuclear weapons. The media reports claim that Col. <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> <PERSON> Hsien-yi </PERSON>, former deputy director of the official <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, is working for the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> and has moved to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since disappearing in January. <PERSON> Liu </PERSON>, who previously worked with <PERSON> Chang </PERSON>, said he did not know where the missing official was or what had happened to him. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s nuclear policy is a particularly sensitive topic because Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has said <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> production of atomic weapons would be a reason for invading the island, which <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> views as a renengade province.
