<HEAD>Navy Finds Anti-Aricraft Missiles, Rockets on Iranian Boat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two portable anti-aircraft missiles, tentatively identified as Soviet-made SAM-7s, were found aboard an Iranian gunboat recovered by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> last week, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said today. The weapons on the boat, found abandoned and drifting in the <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>, also included three `` chaff rockets'' of unknown origin and four other unidentified rockets with fusing devices. Chaff is a material blown into the air to confuse the homing system of a radar-guided missile. Maj. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Willey </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, said the twin-barrelled gun mounted in the cockpit of the 30-foot boat was a Soviet-made ZSU 23mm anti-aircraft weapon. The gun apparently had been used for attacks on ships in the southern <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> and the Hormuz. It was rusty, but functional, and was loaded for firing when found. Authoritative references say the Soviet SAM-7, a shoulder-fired missile similar to the American-made Redeye, is known to be a part of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s weapons inventory. But <PERSON> Willey </PERSON> said he did not know whether it had previously been seen in the gulf. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> also is believed to possess some U.S.-made Stinger missiles, a more advanced missile than the Redeye. It fired at least one at a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> helicopter last October, but missed. Several Stingers and a spent launcher were found in a sunken Iranian speedboat recovered by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> divers on Jan. 3. The gunboat, an open-cockpit, twin-diesel craft, was found by the guided missile frigate <PERSON> Reuben </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON>, drifting in 10-foot seas in the Hormuz passage last Thursday. The boat's whereabouts were not disclosed. <PERSON> Willey </PERSON> would say only that it was in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> custody. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officers have said they do not know why the boat apparently was abandoned by the Iranians. It appeared to have been recently vacated by its crew and was trailing a sea anchor. The fiberglass-hulled boat was the fourth Iranian small craft captured by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> in the past six months, but the first taken in the southern waterway where <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s naval frigates and Revolutionary Guards concentrate their surface raids on neutral shipping. In addition to the rockets and missiles, <PERSON> Willey </PERSON> said the boat yielded one Soviet-designed AK-47 assault rifle and 203 rounds of ammunition, 500 rounds of ammunition for the mounted gun, and related items. The missiles apparently were contained in a sealed wooden box, six feet long, found in the bottom of the boat. Officers on the <PERSON> Reuben </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> did not open the box, but there was speculation at the time that it might contain Stingers or other portable rockets. The SAM-7, known as the `` Strela,'' or arrow in Russian, has an effective range of about two miles, atttacking aircraft by homing in on their engine exhaust. Although it has been replaced in the Soviet inventory by a newer portable missile, the SAM-14, the <LOCATION> Strela </LOCATION> is still being produced for Soviet forces and for export sales. It also is manufactured by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, and more than 40 countries, including both <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, are believed to have the weapon in their arsenals. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials gave no further information on the chaff rockets found on the Iranian boat. Such rockets are carried aboard most warships and aircraft in the gulf.
