<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The `` Mole Patrol'' is on a roll. For nine years, Officer <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> worked underground, patrolling the 3 -LCB- - mile network of corridors, platforms and tunnels of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>'s mass-transit system His unit was justly dubbed the Mole Patrol. He now helps run the <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s two battery-powered carts, which cruise silently through the concourse at the hub of the city's transportation system. The white and blue industrial carts, fitted with searchlights, rescue gear, two-way radio, roll bar and dome lights, can carry 8,400 pounds and have a top speed of about 10 mph. They cost $ 6,200 apiece. The new carts were quickly dubbed `` mole mobiles.'' After all, `` transit response vehicles'' just sounds too stuffy. Before the carts came, if <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> heard of trouble in another part of the concourse, `` it would be a footrace,'' he said. `` You'd be exhausted by the time you got there.'' `` We see a very positive response by all the store owners,'' Capt. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Norton </PERSON>, commander of the transit unit, said Wednesday. `` They see this cart, they come out and want to say hello. The public stops you all the time,'' he said. `` They get a real kick out of the fact that the police are down here in strength.'' Within the next year the department hopes to add five more of the vehicles, because a cart is cheaper than paying for extra officers, <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> said. The vehicles are parked and recharged during morning and evening rush hours, when the transit system's 350,000 daily passengers clog the passageways. <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said he and another officer arrested a burglar their first night, when they received a suspicious-person report and sped off to a far-off part of the concourse, which features stores, restaurants and banks. `` Lo and behold, there's a man standing there inside a closed store,'' <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said. `` The only thing he said was, ` I did n't hear you coming.'''
