<FIRST>r a PM-AIDS-HeartDisease     03-31 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Heart Disease,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heart Disease Early Indicator Of Some AIDS Cases, Researchers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cardiologists should be aware that heart disease can be an early indicator of AIDS, and some patients can live longer with proper cardiac care, according to research presented at the American College of Cardiology convention. In a 1983-86 study of 86 AIDS patients in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, 18 had heart disease and seven of those had heart disease before other AIDS-related ailments, Dr. <PERSON> Evlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinney </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday at the ACC meeting. `` Heart disease was present in 5 percent of all AIDS patients _ that's our estimate based on the patients we have seen,'' she said. `` Cardiologists need to be aware of AIDS heart disease.'' While little could be done for AIDS patients suffering from tumor-based heart disease, she said, cardiac disease stemming from opportunistic infections such as tuberculosis _ rather than from tumors _ can be treated, prolonging the lives of terminally ill patients. `` There were patients who, with treatment, survived as long as -LRB- AIDS -RRB- patients without heart disease,'' <PERSON> Kinney </PERSON> said. `` Some of these patients, we did manage to prolong their lives for many months.'' AIDS cripples the body's ability to fight off disease, allowing a variety of ailments _ including heart disease _ to cause death. Fourteen of the 18 AIDS heart patients were dead within four months of diagnosis, but the other four _ all with infection-related heart disease _ lived for about two years, she said. Another participant in the study, Dr. <PERSON> Jean-Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Monsuez </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Hopital </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, said early, specific diagnosis of the ailments plaguing AIDS patients can help physicians prolong life. Tuberculosis, for instance, is a frequent ailment in AIDS patients, and it can be treated. `` If we can treat each organ involved, it's a very important thing,'' <PERSON> Monsuez </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kinney </PERSON> noted that there were only eight women among the 86 AIDS patients studied, but half of them were suffering from AIDS-related heart disease. While noting that the number of female patients was small, she said, `` Females seem to be more susceptible to AIDS heart disease ... the women were represented disproportionately.''
</TEXT>
