<HEAD>Men Tested Without Permission For AIDS, Suing Doctors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three men are suing doctors for allegedly testing them for AIDS without their permission, complaining their privacy was violated and that the test results caused them mental anguish. The lawsuits say one of the three considered suicide and another was forced to leave his home town because of societal pressure after they were told they tested positive for the AIDS virus. Lawyer <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Webber </PERSON>, who filed all three suits, said such testing occurs more often than patients realize. `` I believe that such testing is going on all over,'' <PERSON> Webber </PERSON> said. `` In most cases, people are tested without their knowledge and simply never know.'' <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Forbes </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for Action AIDS, a nonprofit organization that assists people with AIDS in the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> area, said AIDS testing without permission is `` happening far too frequently.'' `` Often this testing is being done without consideration of the impact it has on people and their families,'' she said. `` Telling people that they are infected with the virus is a psychological bombshell because you are dealing with an incurable disease.'' A study published last week in the Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said 34 percent of 189 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hospitals surveyed rarely asked patients' permission before testing for the AIDS virus. The three men, who were not identified at their request, are suing the doctors for more than $ 200,000 in damages. The doctors and their representatives refused comment to comment on the suits. In one lawsuit, filed Wednesday in federal court in <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION>, a 40-year-old man contends he was forced to leave his home after he tested positive for exposure to the virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome. He said his physician never asked his permission. The man said although he is infected with the virus, he does not have AIDS or AIDS-related diseases. The plaintiff in another suit, filed in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> Common Pleas Court, said he went to a hospital for treatment of a minor eye infection and gave permission for a blood test but not for an AIDS test. He contemplated suicide after he was told he tested positive for AIDS, according to the suit. In the third suit, also filed in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> court, the plaintiff alleges that he was tested for the AIDS virus without permission after he went to her for a premarital blood test. A second test showed he was not infected.
