comment. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `The appeals ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> has offered to hold separate talks on conventional forces and battlefield nuclear arms and urged the superpowers to sign by July 1 a pact to halve their long-range nuclear arsenals. The Soviet-led alliance's seven foreign ministers also said Wednesday after a two-day meeting in the Bulgarian capital of <LOCATION> Sofia </LOCATION> that the superpowers should agree to abide by the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> says the treaty bars development of a space-based missile defense system. The <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> foreign ministers urged <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> to begin talks this year on reducing conventional forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and backed down from a longstanding position by offering separate negotiations on battlefield nuclear weapons. The offer appeared aimed at overcoming a more than year-old absence of movement toward new talks on reducing conventional forces across <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` We welcome the statements of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact foreign ministers ... to the extent that they seem to reflect some of the concerns of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> members,'' said a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> statement released today in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>. The statement added that it was important that the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact's words be translated into concrete proposals at the negotiating table The appeals, published by the Bulgarian news agency <ORGANIZATION> BTA </ORGANIZATION> and monitored in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, indicated Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is eager to seal a pact on intercontinental nuclear missiles but not insisting it be ready to sign when he meets President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in <LOCAT