<HEAD>Human-Powered Plane Makes Successful Test Flight</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with no flight scheduled Friday.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRAKLION, Crete (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A high-tech human-powered aircraft made a successful series of test flights today in preparation for a world-record distance attempt that also will recreate the ancient Daedalus myth. But organizers of the Daedalus project called off plans for a record bid on Friday because southerly gales were expected with winds gusting up to 30 mph. Flight Director <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bussulari </PERSON> told reporters that the 68-pound ultralight <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> 88 `` is in good shape ... and we may see favorable conditions'' for a flight on Saturday or Sunday. The aircraft completed six flights lasting less than three minutes each in calm dawn weather above a <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> air force base adjoining <LOCATION> Iraklion </LOCATION> airport. Five athlete pilots took turns to pedal the shimmering pink-and-silver plane at speeds of around 14 mph, flying about 15 feet above the tarmac. The three-year <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> project aims at breaking the world record for human-powered flight over the 74-mile distance from <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION> to the island of <LOCATION> Santorini </LOCATION>, also known as Thira. The flight also will update the myth of <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION>. According to the 3,500-year-old myth, the inventor and his son, Icarus, tried to escape from <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION> on wings made of feathers and wax. <PERSON> Daedalus </PERSON> succeeded, but <PERSON> Icarus </PERSON> flew too close to the sun, the wax melted and he fell into the sea. After nine days of blustery weather, conditions today appeared near-perfect for the <LOCATION> Santorini </LOCATION> flight, which requires temperatures below 70 degrees Fahrenheit and almost dead calm, a rare occurrence on this wind-swept southern island. `` It feels like a day for the record, pretty calm. I was flying the plane with no hands,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Scioscia </PERSON>, 27, a professional cyclist from <LOCATION> Scranton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bussulari </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> aerospace expert who will make the decision to fly, said the record probably could have been set today, although the plane would have met strong headwinds about five miles off <LOCATION> Santorini </LOCATION> `` But we felt we needed a test flight to shake down the aeroplane,'' he said. The pilots _ four Americans and one <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> _ are taking turns to stand by for 48 hours in readiness for the flight. The pilot who had been scheduled to fly Friday is <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Zack </PERSON>, 26, of <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, whose father was born in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. The pilot pumps bicycle pedals that turn the contraption's propeller, and steers the plane with a joystick, coordinating with ground-based radio instructions `` For the record the pilot must keep pedaling a steady 15 mph but the effort is equivalent to riding 23 miles an hour on land,'' said <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Tremml </PERSON>, a medical student from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>. Tremml set the 37.2-mile world record for human-powered flight in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in 1987, flying a <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> prototype After an unassisted takeoff, the pilot will skirt the offshore island of <LOCATION> Dia </LOCATION> and head due north hoping to land on a sandy beach on <LOCATION> Santorini </LOCATION>. Two Greek navy patrol boats and a flotilla of inflatable crafts will escort the plane across the <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> sea </LOCATION>, ready to pick up the pilot if he crashes and salvage the aircraft, although it probably would be unuseable. Two backup flying machines are ready for assembly here if needed. Like <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> 88, they are constructed of lightweight composite material _ graphite epoxy, plastic fiber and mylar, an extra-thin plastic skin that covers the jetliner-sized 112-foot wingspan. The $ 1 million Daedalus project, with its 36-member team, has produced new information on endurance and low altitude flying aerodynamics and meteorology during its three years of development, its organizers said. `` The project does have a research and educational application, particularly in human physiology and aeronautics,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Langford </PERSON>, the project director. `` The plane itself does n't have any practical application. It should be seen as a work of art.''
</TEXT>
