<HEAD>CDC Statistics On U.S. AIDS Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are the latest statistics on acquired immune deficiency syndrome in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, as reported this week by the national Centers for Disease Control:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Number of Cases</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Total cases reported since June 1981: 57,575. Cases, year to date: 7,183. Total deaths: 32,190, or 56 percent of all cases.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Transmission Categories</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Homosexual or bisexual males: 36,234, or 63 percent. Intravenous drug abusers: 10,192, or 18 percent. Homosexual male and drug abusers: 4,226, or 7 percent. Heterosexual cases: 2,285, or 4 percent. Transfusion or blood cases: 1,500, or 3 percent. Hemophilia patients: 621, or 1 percent Undetermined transmission cause: 1,815, or 3 percent
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Age and Race</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Childhood cases -LRB- under age 13 -RRB-: 913, or 2 percent. Cases among whites: 34,218, or 59 percent. Cases among blacks: 14,755, or 26 percent. Cases among Hispanics: 8,082, or 14 percent. Cases among other: 520, or 1 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 These statistics are through March 28 and have been rounded by the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> to the nearest whole percent. Cumulative totals are for AIDS cases reported since June 1981, and include 75 cases subsequently found to have occurred prior to that date. The `` other'' classsification under Age and Race includes Asians, American Indians and native Alaskans.
