<HEAD>At Least 17 Killed As Tamils Attack Moslem Villages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tamil militants attacked and set fire to two Moslem fishing villages in eastern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> today, and at least 17 people were killed, Indian and Sri Lankan sources said. The sources said the attackers burned a mosque and more than 80 mud-and-straw houses in villages near <LOCATION> Kalmunai </LOCATION>, 137 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, the capital. The sources spoke on condition of anonymity. Some reports said the death toll was higher. There also was confusion over how many of the dead were Tamils and how many were Moslems because a battle apparently broke out after the initial attack. Moslems make up 7 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people. They have been caught up only rarely in the Tamil rebels' nearly five-year war against the dominant Sinhalese for a separate Tamil nation. But the Moslems make up about one-third of the population in eastern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, which the rebels want as part of their homeland, and they recently have come under attack. Under an Indian-sponsored peace accord, a vote is be held in the island's north and east for a temporary council to rule the two areas as one province. Both Sinhalese and Moslem leaders charge that the Tamils are trying to drive out members of the other two communities to gain political advantage. An Indian diplomat in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> said <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> peacekeeping troops investigating the attack found 17 bodies in the villages of <LOCATION> Sainthamaruthu </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malaiyandu </LOCATION>. The diplomat, who spoke on condition her name not be used, said six people also were injured. `` Indian troops have now moved a battalion to the stricken villages,'' she said. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> mantains about 40,000 soldiers in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> under a peace accord signed last July. A police official in <LOCATION> Kalmunai </LOCATION>, who also spoke anonymously, said 86 houses, all belonging to Moslem fisherman, were burned to the ground. Many people fled into the nearby jungle, he said. <PERSON> Mohamad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashroof </PERSON>, general secretary of the Sri Lankan Moslem <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> that he had firm reports the death toll was 20 Moslems, including six who perished after taking refuge in the mosque. But sources in the coastal city of <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION>, north of <LOCATION> Kalmunai </LOCATION>, said survivors' accounts indicated 17 died, including seven Tamils killed when Moslem villagers tried to repulse the attack. The largest rebel militia, the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION>, have been operating in eastern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> since being driven out of their stronghold in the north by Indian troops. They have resisted the peace accord, which calls on the rebels to give up their fight in exchange for more autonomy for Tamils. Tamils, mostly Hindus, make up 18 percent of the population. They claim they are discriminated against by the <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinhalese </ORGANIZATION>, who form 75 percent and dominate the government and military. Within the last month, nearly 150 civilians have been killed in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION> in attacks blamed on the Tamil rebels. Within the past week more than 30 Moslem-owned homes and businesses have been looted or set afire in <LOCATION> Kalmunai </LOCATION>. Two weeks ago seven Moslem businessmen in the area were kidnapped and are still missing.
