<HEAD>Members of Alleged Gypsy Burglar Ring Stole Nationwide, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty Polish Gypsies who were arrested at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> while carrying jewelry-stuffed bags are part of an elusive nationwide burglary ring, authorities said. Nineteen of the 20 men and women pleaded innocent in <ORGANIZATION> Pasadena </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday and Tuesday to charges of receiving stolen property. One suspect is still to be arraigned. Sheriff's Detective <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiese </PERSON>, who has tracked members of the group since 1984, said they specialized in rifling senior citizens' houses from coast to coast, often while the victims were at home Group members are wanted in connection with a string of similar burglaries across the country and in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, he said. `` We have n't even touched the tip of the iceberg, that's how big we believe this activity is across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Wiese </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Police Detective <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kagele </PERSON>, working with more than two dozen law enforcement agencies in the case, said the Gypsies would drive through affluent neighborhoods looking for senior citizens standing outside their homes, watering their lawns or chatting with neighbors. While a man remained at the wheel of the car, a woman would ask the homeowner for directions or a drink of water. A second woman would sneak into the house and rummage through bedroom dressers and closets in search of jewelry, expensive heirlooms and silver, <PERSON> Kagele </PERSON> said. `` If the woman was seen inside the house, she would make up a quick story that she's looking for a ` Joe' or ` <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON>' and must have the wrong address,'' <PERSON> Kagele </PERSON> said. `` It was n't all that sophisticated, but it worked.'' Still wanted is the group's alleged Gypsy `` queen,'' <PERSON> Danuta </PERSON> <PERSON> Reszuta </PERSON>, 31, authorities said. All 20 people arrested last week have been charged with one count of receiving stolen property and held in lieu of $ 500,000 bail each. Police said the high bail was needed because alleged members of the group have fled before trial in the past. Polish translators are assisting the Gypsies because none of the 20 speak enough English to follow their court proceedings. Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> agents also are reviewing their files on the suspicion that several may be in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> illegally.
