<HEAD>Mulroney Shuffles Cabinet Heading Into Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> shuffled his Cabinet today with major changes in the controversial trade and immigration portfolios. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> faces a re-election campaign later in the year. International Trade Minister <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Carney </PERSON>, noted for her combative style, was replaced by former Transport Minister <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Crosbie </PERSON>, who will take over responsibility for implementing the free-trade agreement negotiated last year with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The agreement dismantles tariffs and other trade barriers over the next decade. It faces a ratification battle in Parliament later this year and stubborn opposition from at least two of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s 10 provinces. <PERSON> Carney </PERSON> takes over as president of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, a post formerly held by Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazankowski </PERSON>. Changing more than a quarter of his 38-member Cabinet, <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> replaced both Immigration Minister <PERSON> Benoit </PERSON> <PERSON> Bouchard </PERSON> and his deputy, <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON>, following two years in which <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> has struggled to curb an influx of up to 2,000 illegal aliens a month. <PERSON> Bouchard </PERSON> takes over as transport minister while <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON> becomes minister of state for multiculturalism. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> McDougall </PERSON>, formerly in charge of women's affairs and privatization, becomes immigration minister. In a surprise move, <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> reached outside <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> to name his old school friend <PERSON> Lucien </PERSON> <PERSON> Bouchard </PERSON>, recently <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s ambassador to <LOCATION> Fra