<HEAD>Government Cancels Dam Project Near Prague</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government has canceled a long-planned project to build a dam and hydroelectric power station in a river valley west of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> because it would cause ecological damage, it was reported Thursday. Ecologists said it was the first case when a major project has been canceled for ecology reasons in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, expressing the growing official and popular concern over increased pollution, the Communist daily Rude Pravo reported. Serious objections to the Krivoklat dam, which was initiated in the 1960s, were raised by the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Culture </ORGANIZATION> and local officials, and that led to several postponements of the project. In 1977 the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> declared that the area should be preserved. Flooding in the <LOCATION> Berounka </LOCATION> river valley would destroy fauna and flora surviving in the area since the Ice Age, as well as valuable forests which are to be used to revitalize the tens of thousands of acres of woods damaged by pollution in this country, ecologists say. The decision, however, was not expected to change official plans for <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s most grandiose current project: the construction of a giant dam and hydroelectric plant on the <LOCATION> Danube </LOCATION> where it crosses the Hungarian border. Hungarian and Austrian environmentalists have said the project will alter water levels and damage forests and farmland across a wide area. But <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s planners are still going ahead with a plant they say will provide enough power to reduce the burning of sulfur-laden brown coal by 3.8 million tons a year. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> coal and other materials used to fuel a rapid 1950s industrialization inspired by the Soviets' Stalinist efforts have inflicted great damage on the environment in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, a landlocked country whose natural assets are its forests and rivers. The damage grew unhindered throughout the 1970s, while the West woke up to ecological issues. Now, a similar consciousness has arisen in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, causing popular alarm and forcing the government to finance projects designed to restore environmental standards to 1970 levels by the next millenium.
</TEXT>
