<HEAD>Latin America Keeps Its Distance from U.S. Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials point proudly to how many Latin American countries have become democratic in recent years, but on the hemispheric issues of most concern to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> _ <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> _ it's hard to find one willing to align itself with American policy. On Tuesday, a day when the administration was issuing veiled warnings about the possibility of military intervention in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, a regional conclave in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, decided that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had already gone too far in its campaign against military strongman <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. `` We urge the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government to revoke immediately the coercive measures it has adopted against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Latin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> said in a communique after a two-day meeting. Nations ranging from rightist <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Marxist </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> signed the declaration. The underlying message was clear: the 26 countries are worried that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is setting a precedent in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> that could be used against any one of them in the future. This consideration far outweighs the distaste that many have for <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, named in two federal narcotics indictments. They believe they themselves might be an American target some day if they get caught smuggling drugs to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or run afoul of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy in some other way. Over the past month, the administration has contributed to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s economic collapse through measures that have had the effect of aggravating an acute cash shortage in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. It has, for example, taken steps to deny <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> access to some $ 50 million in official Panamanian funds deposited in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks and has withheld a $ 6.5 million payment due to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> for services related to <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canal </ORGANIZATION> operations. But many in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, where opposition to <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is virtually unanimous, believe the administration has not gone far enough. Some advocate a comprehensive trade embargo. The administration has moved against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> in the name of restoring democracy in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, but none of the democracies which now dominate the hemisphere has seen fit to back the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> actions. The one source of comfort for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> concerning <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is that the only nations that have provided overt support for <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> are <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. Another frustration for the administration has been the persistent refusal of Latin American nations to support the Nicaraguan Contra rebels. Some countries, such as <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, have fought <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy since the beginning while many others finessed the issue by refusing to take a stand. Asked for an explanation, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say many nations have expressed support for the Contras in private but refuse to do so publicly. The reason, officials say, is that these countries fear a left-wing backlash at home if they side with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. To ensure domestic tranquility, disassociation from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy has been a time-honored tactic. All this generates considerable hand-wringing among administration officials. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was once routinely accused of backing unpopular dictators against the wishes of their subjects. But, particularly in the case of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has not been able to count on <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> support even when it takes an assertive stand against a strongman like <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. A generation ago, it was relatively easy for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to win diplomatic support in the hemisphere. With minimal opposition, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> orchestrated the diplomatic and economic isolation of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s revolutionary government and won <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> support, with some exceptions, for its armed intervention in the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> in 1965. The sole recent instance in which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> have been in harmony was in 1979, when there was a common effort to bring down the <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> family dynasty in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration called on President <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> to step down and, within a month, he was gone.
</TEXT>
