<HEAD>Uganda Prostitutes Don School Garb To Lure AIDS-Wary Clients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prostitutes are masquerading as schoolgirls to lure clients wary of getting infected with AIDS, the head of <LOCATION> Uganda </LOCATION>'s task force on the disease said Thursday. Dr. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Okware </PERSON>, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prevention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acquired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immune </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deficiency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Syndome </ORGANIZATION>, said his organization had started a nationwide program to warn people of the charade. Men are `` diverting their attention to schoolgirls and ignoring bar maids and prostitutes'' because of their fear of catching the sexually transmitted disease, he said. Prostitutes are donning school uniforms and carrying books during the late afternoon when students normally return home from school, <PERSON> Okware </PERSON> said. He said in the last three months, the practice had become common among prostitutes in <LOCATION> Masaka </LOCATION>, about 85 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Kampala </LOCATION>, the capital. There are 2,300 confirmed cases of AIDS in <LOCATION> Uganda </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Okware </PERSON>.
