<FIRST>r w AM-PostalRates     03-31 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Postal Rates,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Raising Stamp Prices: How It's Done</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New postal rates taking effect Sunday complete a complex process that got under way 11 months ago. While most of the attention on the new 25-cent stamp has occurred in the last few weeks, the rate was actually proposed by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service in May 1987. Since then, there has been so much discussion that some consumers may be confused about how many times rates have risen, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Griesemer </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. When it was made an independent federal agency in the early 1970s, the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> was directed to break even by raising rates to cover costs. The taxpayer subsidy that had been provided to the old Post Office was gradually eliminated. But to prevent sudden, sharp rate hikes, a separate <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> was set up to monitor mailing costs. Under the law, the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> balances its funds over a term of years. When losses accumulate it raises rates. Subsequently it may show a surplus for some years, until costs rise to push it back into the red and again result in another hike. The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 223 million in fiscal 1987, and the red ink was expected to increase this year despite cost-cutting efforts. The agency had a $ 305 million surplus in 1986, following sharp cost-cutting in the wake of 1985's loss of $ 251 million, agency managers reported. Surpluses were reported in 1984, 1983 and 1982, following rate increases in 1981. After the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION> proposed new rates last May, the case went to the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which is charged with listening to all interested persons and recommending whether the new rates should take effect. The commission has 10 months to reach a decision, which then goes back to the postal Board of Governors. The commission issued its ruling March 4, three days early. That decision on a rate hike, which was close to the original request, was then ordered into effect by the postal governors.
