<HEAD>Laughter Costs More, But You Can Insure Against `Bombs'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans are paying more to laugh less. But do n't worry, the presidential election campaign should produce some cheap chuckles. The 1988 Cost of Laughing Index, released to coincide with April Fool's Day and adjusted for inflation, showed a 5.8 percent increase in the humor scale over last year. The annual index, which measures 18 leading humor indicators, compares the punch line to the bottom line. It showed the wholesale price of rubber chickens increased $ 4.80 per dozen during the past 12 months. `` The trend in playful poultry is particularly worrisome,'' said <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Kushner </PERSON>, a self-described humor consultant who compiled the index. `` Over the past two years, rubber chickens prices have jumped 23 percent and dancing chicken telegrams have risen by 9 percent. `` Funny fowl may soon become a memory for most American consumers.'' Other increases included an 8 percent hike in comedy club ticket prices and an 11 percent jump in the newstand price of Mad Magazine. On the up side, the wholesale price of Groucho glasses and arrow-through-the-head gags did not change. Former attorney <PERSON> Kushner </PERSON>, whose consulting operation is based in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruz </LOCATION>, also gives seminars on how to use humor to communicate. His clients include <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> and the notoriously funny <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>.
