.. and the ribs are a little bit bruised,'' <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, an auto dealer and perennial political outsider, told a group of <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> supporters Wednesday. But he said he still had plans for `` when I get back there'' in the governor's office. The vote to dismiss the third charge Wednesday was a surprise to most involved, including the senator who made the motion, Republican <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Stump </PERSON>. Several of those who voted to dismiss said they wanted to avoid prejudicing <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s upcoming criminal trial on felony charges that he concealed a $ 350,000 campaign loan. That would have been the subject of evidence on the third impeachment charge and <PERSON> Stump </PERSON> said it would have put the governor in `` quasi-double jeopardy.'' The decision set the stage for a vote as early as Monday on two other charges against the first-term <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION>, who also faces a May 17 recall election and an April 21 criminal trial. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> remains accused of misusing $ 80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership and of trying to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official Those voting for the dismissal motion were an unusual coalition of all 11 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democrats plus five Republicans who have steadfastly supported the governor. Lawmakers refused to predict whether there will be the two-thirds majority of the 30-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> needed to convict on the remaining two charges.. Democratic Sen. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Rios </PERSON> disputed speculation that Democrats voted for the dismissal motion because they think they have the votes to boot <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> `` I think this needs to be brought to a conclusion,'' he said of the 5-week-old impeachment trial, `` and this is my view of one way to bring it to a conclusion.'' `` I've always been confident,'' <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> told reporters Wednesday night. He refused to comment directly on the dismissal. Defense attorney <PERSON> Jerris </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> said he considered it a victory. If <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> is convicted, Secretary of State <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>, who has been acting governor since <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s Feb. 5 impeachment by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, would become governor. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> was expected to receive jury instructions this afternoon. Closing arguments are scheduled for Monday morning, and a vote can be taken any time afterward. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> has repeatedly insisted he is innocent of all wrongdoing and that he is the victim of persecution by the state <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> establishment and the media. He has been surrounded by controversy since he took office in January 1987. The day after taking office, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> canceled a Martin Luther King holiday for state workers on grounds it was illegally created by his predecessor, Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON>. He also has made comments that angered blacks, homosexuals, women, Jews and Japanese. The governor said Wednesday night that if he is returned to office he would be willing to declare that `` bygones can be bygones'' in his relations with the Legislature.
