<HEAD>Pope Celebrates Holy Thursday Mass, Washes Feet of Priests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> on Thursday re-enacted <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>'s last supper with his apostles by washing the feet of 12 priests in a solemn Holy Thursday ritual. Some 3,000 worshipers gathered for the two-hour ceremony in the vast, marble-columned <ORGANIZATION> Basilica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lateran </ORGANIZATION> with its 16 rooftop figures of Christ, the apostles and saints silhouetted against the early evening sky. The 17th century basilica, built on an ancient Roman property, is the pope's church as bishop of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. Earlier Thursday, the pontiff celebrated Mass at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peter </LOCATION>'s Basilica in <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, leading <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> clergymen _ including 22 cardinals, 30 bishops and some 1,000 priests _ in renewing their vows of celibacy During the evening ceremony, the 67-year-old pope, draped in white vestments, washed the feet of the dozen mostly elderly priests in a service symbolizing <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>' humility before he was crucified on Good Friday. Wearing a protective apron, the pontiff poured water from a golden urn onto one foot of each priest, wiping it with a white cloth before bending down to kiss it. The priests, dressed in white, red and gold, were seated on a platform under the austere, gold-leaf nave of the basilica, which is said to contain the heads of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peter </LOCATION> and <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> and where until a century ago popes were crowned. The service included hymns and chants by the <ORGANIZATION> Sistine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chapel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Choir </ORGANIZATION>, as well as a homily in Italian by the pope on the theme of Christian humility. The two rites Thursday began four days of ceremonies that culminate on Easter Sunday, celebrating the passion, death and resurrection of Christ. On Friday, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> is to carry a wooden cross in the traditional Good Friday ceremony starting from the torch-lit Colosseum. He will celebrate the Easter vigil on Saturday night, and a Sunday Mass in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peter </LOCATION>'s Square.
