<HEAD>Four Legislative Leaders Want Voters To Decide How Often
Legislature Meets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETSY HENDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four legislative leaders on Thursday said annual sessions were `` an experiment that did n't work'' and called for a return to sessions every other year. `` We have seen legislative expenses rise and we have seen good lawmakers make the hard choice not to run again because they can not be in <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION> every year and at the same time make a living for themselves and their families,'' House Speaker <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Scamman </PERSON> said at a news conference. <PERSON> Scamman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Palumbo </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON>, and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democratic Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> support a proposed constitutional amendment that would put the change before voters in November. `` They -LRB- voters -RRB- should have the chance to judge the efficiency of annual sessions based on the experience of the last four years and to register their opinion with their vote,'' <PERSON> Scamman </PERSON> said. On Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constitutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statuatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revision </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted 12-4 to recommend legislation that would put the proposed constitutional amendment on the ballot. Voters approved annual sessions in 1984. Those supporting annual sessions, including <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Democratic Leader <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON>, say state business is too complicated for legislators to meet every other year. `` I have n't seen a piece of legislation -LRB- this year -RRB- that could n't have waited until next year,'' <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> said.
