<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said today it had cracked a major heroin-importing ring involving trafficking through <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION> and was arresting 233 people in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> told a news conference it was the largest international drug case ever developed by the federal government and said it has been a `` stunning success.'' The arrests were the result of a lengthy criminal investigation in cooperation with Italian authorities, and involved the import of southwest Asian heroin into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The 69 defendants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> include 38 charged in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, six in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, 10 in <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, eight in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, two in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> and five in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, authorities intend to charge 164 people, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Authorities seized six kilograms of heroin and four kilograms of cocaine during the course of the investigation. Italian authorities seized 22 kilograms of heroin last month. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said the purpose of the investigation has been to penetrate organized drug operations and not just to make random drug seizures. `` The tentacles of this network spread out across this country,'' he said. The attorney general declined to speculate on what impact the arrests will have on drug traffic in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` Nobody knows for sure the quantity of heroin or any other drug coming into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he said. But the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s strategy of penetration `` is going to the heart of drug trafficing networks rather than just cutting off the tentacles.'' During the news conference to announce the drug arrests, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> refused to answer reporters' questions on the resignation of two of his top aides amid increasing skepticism on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> over whether he can continue to run the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, who is the target of a broadening criminal investigation, turned aside at least half a dozen questions relating to the possibility that he might quit in the wake of Tuesday's resignations of Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> and Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Weld </PERSON> `` The business of law enforcement is going forward energetically and without interruption,'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said. `` Our strong management team is on the job.'' Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, who has called for <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s resignation, said, `` I think he has lost his credibility It's a joke when he's talking about drug enforcement when everyone wants to know why he's still attorney general.'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Story </PERSON>, chief of the narcotics section of the criminal investigations division of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, said authorities also have seized business assets in connection with the arrests. Suspects arrested today have been charged with conspiracies to import, possess and distribute drugs, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said. Authorities used physical and electronic surveillance during the investigation. Authorities were alerted to the presence of a Sicilian Mafia drug network operating out of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and trafficking in heroin by a 1985 drug case involving a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> pizza restaurant, authorities said. A government affidavit filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> said two of the defendants in the current case operate pizza restaurants in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and another is a former pizza restaurant owner there. Two of the defendants in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and one of those charged in <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION> are fugitives from Italian drug convictions, The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said. The Sicilian Mafia's drug trafficking plan involved exporting cocaine from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, where it would be exchanged for heroin and then smuggled back to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said the difference in the price of cocaine here and in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> made the scheme profitable for the network. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sessions </PERSON> commended the cooperation of the Italian government and law enforcement agencies in coordinating the investigation and arrests. Sessions said Italian law enforcement officials have made 68 arrests so far and are pursuing fugitives in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION>, <L