<FIRST>u w PM-Teamsters-Truckers     03-31 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teamsters-Truckers,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Teamsters union and the trucking industry reached a tentative agreement today on a national freight contract covering some 200,000 drivers and warehouse workers. The three-year National Master Freight Agreement would replace a contract of similar length with the industry's collective bargaining arm, <ORGANIZATION> Trucking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, that was scheduled to expire at midnight. Terms of the accord, which still must be ratified by rank-and-file union members, were not disclosed immediately. But Teamsters President <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> said it `` addresses the economic need of our members and advances their legitimate claims for job security.'' Going into the talks, <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> officials were under pressure to end a pattern of concessionary bargaining since the industry was deregulated in 1980 and win wage and benefit gains in the range of 3 percent to 4 percent over their current base pay of $ 14.71 an hour for drivers. While some large carriers are enjoying fairly healthy profits now despite freight rate-cutting wars among them, several smaller companies are having financial troubles. Teamster employees of the smaller firms had indicated they were more interest in job protection than large wage gains. Since deregulation of trucking in the last year of the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration, at least 78 Teamster-organized carriers have gone out of business or been swallowed up in mergers. The union has lost about 120,000 members in the industry since 1979, although it has stablized in recent years. `` Negotiations were difficult because the industry is in such financial chaos,'' <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> said, encouraging his union's members to ratify the accord. Under the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>' constitution, it takes a two-thirds membership vote to reject a contract approved by the union's leaders. <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeller </PERSON>, a spokesman for the union, said both sides had agreed not to discuss details of the tentative contract until after it had been submitted for a ratification vote.
