<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolGuide     03-31 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Guide,0825</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bold New Consumer's Guide Rates School Districts On Scale Of 0-100</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A first-of-its-kind guidebook rating some 500 metropolitan school districts offers families relocating to a new area a way to begin answering the question: Where are the good schools? The answers in `` Public Schools <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>,'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Williamson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION>, $ 17.95 -RRB- a 366-page book by 25-year veteran education writer <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, are n't surprising: Larger urban districts like <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> generally rate low, and wealthier suburban districts, especially in the Northeast, score high. But what is surprising is the book's daring `` Effective Schools Index,'' which rates all 500 or so districts on a scale of 0-100. The highest score by any district was <LOCATION> Brighton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, an affluent <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION> suburb cited for an excellent program for gifted students, with a near-perfect 98. At the opposite end, <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, scored 13. The book noted high levels of classroom disruption, vandalism, lack of funds and `` fair to poor'' building maintenance. Still, the book to be published late April is meant as a consumer guide, not a scientific study or survey. Its introduction stresses: `` We have not tried to pick the so-called ` best districts' in an area.'' <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, who spent a year and about $ 10,000 of his money researching the book, profiled each district using 22 statistics gathered in mailed questionnaires filled out by the districts themselves. Using 10 of those 22 statistics, <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> devised his `` effective schools index.'' The median score nationwide was 58. School districts earned from zero to 10 points on each of 10 criteria: average daily attendance, spending per pupil, dropout rate, average combined SAT or ACT scores, percentage of eligible students taking the SAT or ACT, number of Advanced Placement courses, teacher-student ratios in elementary and secondary grades, counselor-student ratio, and number of students per music specialist. Districts that did n't provide a statistic or misinterpreted a question received a zero. Twenty of the 26 districts that scored 85 or higher were in the Northeast. A dozen were in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> metropolitan area, and seven of those were in <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> counties on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. Outside the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Elmhurst </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, scored 91; <PERSON> Mayfield </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, 86; <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Euclid-Lyndhurst </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, 86; <LOCATION> Bloomfield </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, 93; <ORGANIZATION> Westside </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, 89, and <PERSON> Kirkwood </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, 88. But quite a number of districts did not respond to <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>'s mailed requests and therefore received no rating, including <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> And the guide covered only districts with at least 2,500 students located within 25 miles of 52 core cities _ meaning thousands of districts were excluded because of size or location. The book also evaluated `` quality of school leadership,'' `` quality of instruction,'' and `` quality of school environment,'' drawing on the expertise of about 1,000 local education reporters, parent groups and others. Those write-ups offer consumers a way to look beyond the statistics. `` Statistically, cities seem to look bad,'' said <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> in an interview. `` But our profiles point out that there are conclaves of excellence, magnet schools of high quality, good principals and good teachers. We did n't want to write the cities off.'' <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, for example, scored a below-average 30 on the book's effectiveness index But the district's profile praised its gifted programs, and added building maintenance is good, `` especially for a district of this size.'' On the other hand, <LOCATION> Grandview </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, rates a strong 70, but its write-up warns readers to `` take note of the low score on the state competency test in math.'' While the numerical rankings are sure to attract the most attention, they can be misleading taken alone. For example, <LOCATION> Ridgewood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> scored 86, earning perfect 10s in many of the index's 10 statistical categories. But it received only 3 out of 10 points for spending $ 5,034 per pupil, well below the $ 5,544 average for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. While <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>'s index penalizes <LOCATION> Ridgewood </LOCATION> for `` underspending,'' <LOCATION> Ridgewood </LOCATION>'s taxpayers may, in fact, be getting better value for their education dollars than, say, <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, which scored a comparable 88 but was awarded the full 10 points for spending $ 11,500 per pupil. `` Some persons might argue that our information does not provide a complete picture of a district,'' <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> wrote. `` Frankly, we have never heard two educators agree on what data would constitute a complete picture. `` What we have done,'' he said, `` is to enable every American to fairly evaluate hundreds of school districts ... using a great many yardsticks that educators themselves, government statisticians, and scientific researchers consider important and valid.'' Copies of the book, or information about it, can be obtained by calling the publisher at 1-800-356-8791.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE: <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitgang </PERSON> has covered education for the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> since 1981.
