<HEAD>Toshiba Import Ban Gets Approval from Trade Bill Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators agreed Thursday to attach to their sweeping trade bill tough sanctions against <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and a subsidiary for selling submarine silencing equipment to the Soviets. House members relented and agreed to the measure despite <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration warnings that a similar provision was too inflexible and could bring on a presidential veto. Sen. <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Garn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, urged lawmakers to ignore the warnings, declaring that he was embarrassed by the Republican administration's reluctance to discipline <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has been kicked in the shins and instead of yelling ` Ouch,' they have chosen to surrender,'' <PERSON> Garn </PERSON> said. The complex measure would ban <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government purchases of <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> goods for three years. It would ban all sales in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of products from its <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary. There would be no waivers, but exceptions could be made for national security. The measure calls for two - to five-year import bans to punish any companies that in the future might send militarily useful equipment to communist countries in defiance of <ORGANIZATION> Cocom </ORGANIZATION>, an agreement among Western nations that is designed to control the flow of such goods Retroactive sanctions contained in the measure also would apply to <PERSON> Kongsberg </PERSON> <PERSON> Vapenfabrikk </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. Like <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION>, that company allegedly was involved in the sale of computerized milling equipment that the administration says has been used to produce submarine propellors that are hard for detection equipment to hear. Cabinet members warned lawmakers earlier this week that stringent sanctions against <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> could mean a veto of the 1,000-page trade bill that lawmakers are drawing up in a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee. House members had been holding out for allowing the president to make the decision on whether sanctions should be mandatory. But after three hours of debate, they relented and accepted a somewhat softened proposal by <PERSON> Garn </PERSON>. The full conference committee in theory could drop the provision or alter it, although that would be hard to arrange. There was considerable reluctance, but no outright dissent, as <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dante </PERSON> <PERSON> Fascell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., accepted the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> offer on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Rep. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Neal </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.C. </LOCATION>, repeatedly urged the panel to trust the judgments of the State and <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> departments as well as the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> that a <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> ban would amount to a mistake. <PERSON> Garn </PERSON> retorted: `` I was elected as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senator to represent the State of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, and not <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> and not <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and not the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and not -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary -RRB- <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>.''
