<FIRST>r w AM-TaxGap     03-31 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Gap,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tax Gap Expected Incease by One-Third To $114 Billion by 1992</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Inflation and economic growth over the next four years will boost by one-third _ to almost $ 114 billion _ the gap between federal income taxes owed and voluntarily paid, the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. However, <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> cautioned <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> against counting on that money as potential income to reduce the federal budget deficit. An undetermined portion of the `` tax gap'' represents taxes that would not be worth the effort to collect even if enforcement activities were stepped up. `` Our estimates of the income-tax gap are measures of total non-compliance,'' <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` They are not intended to be measures of the potential for additional enforcement yields.'' Using information collected in 1983, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> estimates the tax gap at $ 84.9 billion for 1987. That is down from $ 95 billion in 1986. The agency projects an $ 87 billion gap next year and $ 113.7 billion in 1992. <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> said the estimates for this year and the future are less than they would have been had not <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> made significant changes in the tax law in 1986. Those changes included cuts in tax rates, reduced itemized deductions and higher personal exemptions, which, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> believes, will reduce incentives for cheating. That increase in voluntary compliance among individuals will be offset by inflation and growth of the economy, <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> said. Although the new estimates still indicate a sizable tax gap, the commissioner said, they are considerably below what the agency had forecast in 1983. The 1983 projection was for a gap of $ 115 billion for 1987. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> said individuals accounted for $ 63.5 bilion of the 1987 gap and corporations were to blame for the remaining $ 21.4 billion. While the agency expects the voluntary compliance rate among individuals will increase slightly over the next few years, corporate compliance will decline, partly because the 1986 law shifted a significant part of the tax burden from individuals to corporations. Individuals' underreporting of income was to blame for $ 48.3 billion of the tax gap in 1987; overstated deductions, $ 6 billion; overstated credits, $ 900 million; math errors, $ 1 billion; and the failure of many people to even file a required return, $ 7.2 billion. <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurtz </PERSON>, who headed the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> during the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration, cautioned against reading too much into the tax-gap figures, noting they are estimates based on small samples. He and <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, who was <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> commissioner during the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> administration, agreed on a major point: The agency must be given enough money to provide a top level of service to taxpayers. Recalling several years of what he said were underfunding of the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Kurtz </PERSON> said, `` If you have to write a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> to straighten out an account, you're going to learn the meaning of frustration.'' In hiring and retaining employees, he said, `` the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> is not competitive with private industry.'' <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> added: `` How can someone whose salary is so low as to be eligible for food stamps be expected to answer all the complex questions thrown at taxpayer assistance -LRB- employees -RRB- during the current -LRB- return -RRB- filing period?'' The telephone `` assistors'' who field taxpayers' telephoned questions are paid as little as $ 13,000 a year _ considerable less than many garbage collectors, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jennie </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stathis </PERSON>, an associate director of the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees other federal agencies for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> already is weighing several <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> recommendations for reducing the tax gap. These include a capacity for matching business information documents against business returns just as computers already match individual wage and income statements against returns; stepping up efforts to improve the reporting of taxable tips; and trying to find a bigger share of illegal income to tax.
</TEXT>
