<FIRST>r w AM-Medicare-TPA     03-31 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medicare-TPA,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medicare Won't Raise Payments for New Anti-Clotting Drug TPA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal officials said Thursday they have decided against increasing <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> payments to hospitals for treating heart attack victims with an expensive new anti-clotting drug called TPA. `` There is a question as to whether the circumstances involving TPA are so unique as to justify some special accommodation,'' <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roper </PERSON> said in a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` We have concluded that they are not.'' The hospitals have been pressing the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to take into account the high cost of TPA _ which runs about $ 2,000 a dose _ in paying for the treatment of heart attack victims. <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> pays hospitals a flat, predetermined amount for treatment of various illnesses rather than reimbursing hospitals for itemized expenses _ such as particular drugs or procedures _ used on a particular patient. Those fees are adjusted annually to take into account rising costs and other factors and are predicated on the assumption that, while a hospital may lose money on one patient, it is just as likely to reap an excess profit on another patient with the same diagnosis. TPA costs about 10 times as much as other clot-dissolving drugs, such as streptokinase, which have been available longer and have been used on many more patients. Nonetheless, an <ORGANIZATION> HCFA </ORGANIZATION> fact sheet issued in connection with the decision raises the possibility that use of TPA `` may even result in cost savings'' by reducing the length of time a heart attack patient would need to be hospitalized. `` It is too early to know what the exact outcome will be,'' the fact sheet said. It noted that if TPA use does prove to increase overall costs for treating heart attack patients, such a determination would be taken into account automatically in the annual hospital payment adjustments. Although TPA, short for tissue plasminogen activator, has been judged safe and effective by the Food and Drug Administration for quickly dissolving blood clots in heart attack patients, the evidence is less clear on whether it is significantly more effective than streptokinase in saving lives. Trials making a direct comparison between the two drugs are about to begin in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, but results will not be known for a couple of years. Study results released at the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cardiology </ORGANIZATION> this week showed TPA reduced the number of heart attack deaths by more than 50 percent, when compared to a placebo, in a study of 700 patients. A much larger trial, involving about 17,000 patients, showed a combination of streptokinase and aspirin reduced mortality by nearly 60 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> HCFA </ORGANIZATION> fact sheet also said some of the warnings carried on TPA labeling `` include factors likely to be more prevalent in the Medicare population than in the general population.'' `` For example, almost 50 percent of Medicare beneficiaries admitted for -LRB- heart attacks -RRB- in fiscal year 1986 were 75 years or older, an age cohort for which physicians are cautioned to weigh the expected benefits of TPA against the risks,'' it said.
</TEXT>
