<HEAD>Vietnam To Send Back 27 Remains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Vietnamese government is prepared to make the single largest repatriation of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> remains since the end of the Vietnam War, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. `` We are announcing that <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> will repatriate 27 remains to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government representatives on April 6, 1988 in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s chief spokesman. Once transferred in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>, the remains will be flown to the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Identification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, for identification, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> added. `` This will be the largest number of remains repatriated at one time,'' the spokesman said. `` Previously, the largest turnover of remains was 26 on Aug. 14, 1985.'' There are currently 2,404 Americans still listed as missing in <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION> as a result of the Vietnam War, of whom 1,767 are listed as missing in either North or <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. Up to now, the remains of 152 Americans have been repatriated to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and subsequently identified by the laboratory. On March 2, the Vietnamese turned over 17 remains to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. Those remains have yet to be identified, however. The upcoming transfer would be the fourth since retired Army Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Vessey </PERSON> traveled to <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> last August as a special presidential emissary, hoping to step up the process of accounting for missing Americans. `` We've continued to press the Vietnamese and we are getting some results,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said Thursday. Asked if the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> could explain the sudden increase in repatriations, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> replied: `` It's really not for us to do that. The Vietnamese are the ones who should be explaining to the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people and to the world what happened to the rest of the remains and where they are.'' Lt. Col. <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>, another <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said the Vietnamese government informed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials during technical meetings in mid-March they were investigating 29 new reports of remains being found or information regarding servicemen uncovered. Then earlier this week, the Vietnamese disclosed they did have 27 remains to repatriate, <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON> added. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government appreciates the initiative taken by <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to repatriate these remains and hopes it represents just one of many continued steps to resolve this long-standing humanitarian issue,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement.
