<HEAD>Frequency Of Autopsy Declining In U.S., CDC Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The frequency of autopsies is declining in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, possibly making it harder for researchers to determine causes of death, the national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> said. In 1985, autopsies were conducted in 14 percent of deaths in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, down from 17 percent in 1980, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday, citing data from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>. The decline `` may have adversely affected the accuracy of determining the underlying cause of death,'' researchers with the Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said in their weekly report. During the five-year period, the frequency of autopsies performed varied widely among causes of death, from 12 percent of natural deaths to 97 percent of homicides. Autopsies in natural deaths dropped from 13 percent in 1980 to 10 percent in 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. On the other hand, autopsies following unintentional injuries and poisonings rose from 46 percent to 51 percent, and autopsies in suicides rose from 48 percent to 52 percent. In 1985, 34 percent of autopsies performed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> involved deaths from other than natural causes, compared to 30 percent in 1980, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said.
