<HEAD>US Company Signs Drug Pact With China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pharmaceuticals company signed an agreement with the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government Thursday that officials say could lead to increased American drug sales in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and development of Chinese drugs for world markets. Officials of <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Searle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> said it was too early to tell what specific drugs might be involved in the research agreement. But both sides said it could involve a range of products, including possible future AIDS treatments developed in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` This is a good beginning between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yonggang </PERSON>, a vice president of the Chinese administration who signed the <ORGANIZATION> Sino-Searle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. Speaking through a translator, <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> said it was the first such agreement with an American company. The agreement says <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> will have the right to license exclusively any products that result from research and development under the trust. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> U. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeSchutter </PERSON>, president of <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s international operations, said the company already sells seven products in <LOCATION> China </LOCATIO