<NOTE>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EST. Subs 2nd graf and adds one graf to
include full list of best and worst.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> was surly, angry and disagreeable and `` did n't do a thing as president,'' according to his predecessor, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>. In notes for a book <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> never completed, the former president lists <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> as one of eight presidents `` we could have done without,'' the others being <PERSON> Zachary </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchanan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ulysses </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Harding </PERSON> and <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Coolidge </PERSON>. In notes for a book <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> never completed, the former president lists <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> as one of eight presidents `` we could have done without,'' including <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Harding </PERSON> and <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Coolidge </PERSON>. `` I'm not one of Mr. <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>'s admirers,'' <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> wrote. `` I tried so hard to be pleasant and cooperative when I was turning the office over to <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>, but he acted as if I was his enemy instead of the fellow who'd had the job just before him.'' Once he was in the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, `` <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> never made any effort to put forward the leadership to which he was entitled, and he did n't have any program,'' <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> claimed. <PERSON> Ike </PERSON> was n't even nice, according to the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> Democrat. `` It's interesting that a single thing, that great smile of <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>'s, gave him the reputation of being a sunny and amiable man,'' <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> wrote, `` when those of us who knew him well were all too aware that he was essentially a surly, angry and disagreeable man, and I just do n't mean to me, either.'' <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>'s comments, many of which were dictated to secretaries and relatives in the years between his departure from the White House in 1953 and his death in 1972, have been collected in a book titled `` More Plain Speaking,'' edited by his daughter, <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON>. Parts of the book were published in the April 3 Parade magazine. Besides the eight worst presidents, <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> listed his eight best: <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Polk </PERSON>, <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, <PERSON> Grover </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleveland </PERSON>, <PERSON> Woodrow </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>.
