<HEAD>Study Suggests Airlines Not Prepared to Handle Rare In-Flight
Deaths</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 5:30 p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Passenger deaths during airline flights are extremely rare, but crews are not adequately prepared and medical equipment aboard airliners is insufficient to deal with the problem, researchers conclude. `` Airlines simply ca n't count on doctors being aboard flights,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Cummins </PERSON>, one of five authors of a study published in Friday's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` They should take a look at the duration of the flight, the number of passengers aboard and determine what additional measures are needed,'' added <PERSON> Cummins </PERSON>, an associate professor of medicine at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. An average 72 passengers die during flights each year, which researchers called `` a vanishingly small rate'' of three deaths per 10 million passengers. The study reviewed deaths reported from 1977 to 1984 to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which has 120 members and carries 50 percent to 60 percent of the world's scheduled international and domestic air traffic. Researchers concluded that 56 percent of the deaths appeared to be heart-related. Nearly two-thirds of the deaths during flight involved men, whose average age was 54. Doctors aboard the aircraft came forward to offer assistance in 43 percent of the deaths, the study found. Researchers concluded, however, that programs are needed to train flight attendants in the skills of basic cardiopulmonary resuscitation and the use of automatic external defibrillators, the electric-shock `` heart starters,'' said <PERSON> Cummins </PERSON>. `` They are not part of the on-board medical kits now, and we're not advocating they be added to every flight,'' he said `` But some flights should have them.'' `` If flight attendants can be trained to open airplane doors in an emergency, they can be trained to operate a defibrillator,'' he said. `` And the machine provides a simple way to diagnose many kinds of cardiac arrest. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackman </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a trade organization representing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines, said flight attendants on most major carriers already receive training in CPR skills. Earlier this week, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> attendant <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Holt </PERSON> used CPR to save a stricken passenger for the second time in her career. A man collapsed just after boarding her plane in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and an unidentified doctor on board helped her until paramedics arrived at the airport. CPR proficiency is part of flight attendants' training, Ms. <PERSON> Holt </PERSON> said, and `` you never forget it.'' <PERSON> Jackman </PERSON> noted the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> did not include defibrillators in its August 1986 guidelines on mandatory equipment for airline medical kits. Those guidelines are scheduled for review this summer. `` Basically, our policy has been to land as soon as possible, and in this country, that means no more than 20 or 30 minutes no matter where you are,'' said <PERSON> Jackman </PERSON>. `` Crews call ahead for medical teams at the runway and, once on the ground, we're certain that experienced, capable doctors are providing treatment,'' he added. `` And we just ca n't ask flight attendants to diagnose an ailment ... to know the difference between a heart attack and say, a diabetic one,'' said <PERSON> Jackman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Cummins </PERSON> countered that a delay of 20 minutes or longer could prove fatal in instances of sudden cardiac arrest. `` The law does n't obligate the airlines,'' <ORGANIZATION> Cummins </ORGANIZATION> said, `` but it's time they started taking responsibility in some of these emergencies.''
