<HEAD>Toni Morrison Wins Fiction Award; Alfred Uhry for Drama</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS graf 15, ``The play,'' to CORRECT name of theater to
Playwrights Horizons Studio Theater</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 1988 Pulitzer Prize for fiction was awarded Thursday to <PERSON> Toni </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> for `` Beloved,'' a novel which was at the center of controversy when it did not win two other major literary prizes. The prize for drama went to `` Driving Miss Daisy,'' by <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Uhry </PERSON>, which like `` Beloved'' deals with race relations in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The prize for general non-fiction went to <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> for `` The Making of the Atomic Bomb.'' The prize for biography went to <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> for `` Look Homeward: A Life of <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>,'' about the American novelist. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> also won the Pulitzer Prize for biography in 1961 for `` <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Sumner </PERSON> and the Coming of the Civil War.'' The prize in history went to <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON>, a professor at <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, for `` The Launching of Modern American Science 1846-1876.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON>, an award-winning poet associated with <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, won the poetry prize for `` Partial Accounts: New and Selected Poems.'' The prize for music was awarded to <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolcom </PERSON>, a professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION>, for `` 12 New Etudes for Piano.'' The focus of attention this year was on the fiction prize, which was awarded against a backdrop of controversy and literary politics. After `` Beloved'' did not win either the National Book Award or the National Book Critics Circle Award, 48 prominent black writers and critics signed a statement deploring Ms. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>'s lack of recognition. Because she had never won the National Book Award or the Pulitzer Prize, said the statement, published as an open letter in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION>, `` she has yet to receive the national recognition that her five major works of fiction entirely deserve.'' Ms. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>'s `` Song of Solomon'' did win the National Book Critics Circle Award for 1977, but the two other awards are considered more prestigious. `` Beloved'' is the agonizing story of a former slave in post-Civil War <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> who struggles to cope with the brutal death of her daughter. Ms. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> uses flashbacks, multiple points of view and a singularly vivid ghost to describe the emotional trauma of slavery from the perspective of <LOCATION> Sethe </LOCATION>, who kills her daughter rather than yield her to bondage. `` Driving Miss Daisy,'' the drama winner, tells the story of an irascible white woman and her black chauffeur. The play follows their relationship over a quarter-century, ending in 1973. The play opened off-Broadway in April 1987 at the Playwrights Horizons Studio Theater and later moved to a larger off-Broadway theater where it is still running. `` The Making of the Atomic Bomb,'' the winner for general non-fiction, won a National Book Award last fall in the same category. <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON>, who spent five years researching and writing the book, said in a recent interview: `` The making of the bomb is a story on the scale of ` Moby <PERSON> Dick </PERSON>.' I do n't see much of a difference between writing fiction and fact, except, of course, that fact has to be documented.''
