<HEAD>With AM-Meese Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Presidents can be reluctant to fire their closest aides, and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who has shown great loyalty to top advisers in the past, is unlikely to oust his longtime friend, Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, White House observers say. `` He's been a friend for over 20 years,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told reporters Wednesday in response to questions about whether he would remove the attorney general, who faces mounting legal problems. `` I have every confidence in him.'' His statement recalled the time in the summer of 1984 when the president, arriving in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION>, was quizzed about whether he would oust <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Donovan </PERSON>, who faced a federal indictment. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> declared that he would n't give in to a `` lynch mob atmosphere.'' When <PERSON> Donovan </PERSON> finally was indicted, he saved <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> the decision by resigning immediately. <PERSON> Donovan </PERSON> later was found innocent in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> court of larceny and fraud charges involving a construction company he co-owned. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> so dislikes firing top aides that an embittered Secretary of State <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Haig </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> had to try at least twice to quit before the president finally accepted his resignation in June 1982. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> did n't fire <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Watt </PERSON> after he made offensive remarks about blacks, women, Jews and the handicapped in 1983. <PERSON> Watt </PERSON> offered to step aside. `` After watching <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON