<HEAD>Teachers Union Chief Calls for Experimental Schools Within Present
System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that small groups of teachers should be given the autonomy and funds to create experimental schools within regular public schools. AFT President <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> said the current public school system is not working for as many as 80 percent of the students and `` we've got to do something totally different.'' <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> suggested that groups of six to 12 teachers be allowed to organize their own schools, provided they can win the approval of principals, fellow teachers, parents and education authorities. `` It is time once again to take a major step forward in trying to improve the schools of our nation,'' said <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON>, whose 665,000-member union represents teachers in some of the nation's largest cities, including <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> He said state-mandated reforms and more stringent standards imposed over the past five years have improved schools for students at the top, `` but unfortunately -LRB- reform -RRB- is bypassing about 80 percent of kids.'' `` We now need to seek ways that will enable any group of teachers ... and parents of children who want to do something different to opt for a different type of school,'' he said in a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> address. The autonomous schools `` ought to get their per capita share of what the school spends,'' he said. Public schools spend roughly $ 4,000 per pupil on average. <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> said, `` There would have to be a guarantee that such a school would be left alone for five or 10 years provided that parents wanted to keep sending their kids there.'' They would be strictly voluntary for teachers and students. `` If there's anarchy, the customers will be gone in no time at all,'' he said. `` This is not pie in the sky.'' He said such a system would give teachers an alternative to trying to `` shove reform down the throats'' of unwilling colleagues. <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> said only a handful of districts now are trying to restructure public schools. He claimed his idea could open the door for thousands of experimental schools. <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> said he would want the teachers to include in their proposals ways for teachers to govern themselves, to give students alternatives to sitting in class for six hours listening to lectures and to spur cooperative learning. The students also should `` reflect the composition of the entire school'' and not just be drawn from the top or bottom, he said. Last week, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, proposed that state leaders and teacher unions designate at least one experimental school district in each of the 50 states.
