<HEAD>White House Getting Repainted In Spruce-Up For 1992 Bicentennial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Paint that has built up on White House walls since 1797 is being removed as part of a project designed to spruce up the presidential residence for its bicentennial in 1992. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said the job will involve removing some 30 coats of paint and repairing some of the carved stonework on the sandstone walls. Work began this week. The work will be done on the exterior north walls and part of the south walls and will be the first time in nearly two centuries that these walls have been exposed. The walls will be kept bare until the spring of 1989 to allow the porous sandstone to dry so the paint will adhere to the walls better. Repainting is scheduled for next spring. The paint is being removed by brushing chemicals on the walls and then flushing them with a stream of water. The work is being done by <ORGANIZATION> Ramco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, under a $ 384,200 contract. <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Palumbo </PERSON>, master carver for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION>, will oversee repair of the stone carvings. The project is part of a long-range exterior restoration program to repair and replace deteriorated stonework, remove old paint, repoint and seal masonry joints and then repaint. The east wall was restored in 1980 and the north portico in 1984. The entire program is to be completed for the bicentennial of the laying of the cornerstone of the `` President's House'' in 1792. The White House has been the home and office of every president since <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>.
