<HEAD>Byrd Puts INF Pact on Hold Over Future Weapons Question</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said Thursday he will not call up the U.S.-Soviet medium-range missile treaty for debate until the question of whether the pact bans futuristic weapons is better resolved. But Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>, R-Wyo., the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s deputy <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> leader, said the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> has put `` 400 lawyers to work'' on the issue and added: `` I think it can be resolved. Sen. Chic Hecht, R-Nev., a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said, however, that the general question of futuristic weapons is a serious one and must be addressed sooner or later <PERSON> Hecht </PERSON> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence reports show the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has 10,000 scientists working on the development of futuristic weapons using lasers and directed energy. <PERSON> Hecht </PERSON> said the information came from a classified intelligence briefing, but that he had been given permission to release it. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> told reporters that the question of futuristic weapons had been addressed inadequately by the administration and it was not clear that they are banned by the treaty's restrictions. `` It is too important to risk going ahead,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said. `` It is better to be sure, to be cautious and to be right. I intend not to call it up until it is better resolved than it is now.'' `` The treaty has to be good for us,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said, adding that his decision to delay action on the treaty is `` a signal to the administration not to do in haste'' what should be done with care. On another treaty issue, a group of <ORGANIZATION> Republica