<HEAD>Public Broadcasting Corp. Publishes Booklet For Latchkey Kids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> has published a booklet designed to teach `` latchkey'' children basic skills they will need to make their time at home alone safer. The 16-page booklet, titled `` What If I'm Home Alone? Your Family's Guide to Home and Personal Safety Skills,'' teaches children such things as how to get home from school safely, how to use a telephone in an emergency, how to escape a fire and how to deal with strangers who knock at the door. The publication is written in an easy-to-read, entertaining style with large type and illustrations. It also includes a quiz at the end so parents can assess how well their children understand the safety tips. The booklet opens with a letter to parents suggesting ways they can make their home safer and includes a form for emergency and other phone numbers they can fill in and post near the telephone. The booklet is part of a CPB public service campaign designed to help <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> families cope with changes in society that have left a majority of families headed by a single parent or two working parents. An estimated 5 million to 6 million children ages 5 to 12 who daily come home to an empty house or apartment or have to care for younger siblings, <ORGANIZATION> CPB </ORGANIZATION> said. The campaign is being run in conjunction with public broadcasting's year-long, national `` Child Care America'' project being kicked off April 10. The project will focus attention on the issue throughout the year with outreach activities and programming, including a PBS documentary called `` Who Cares for the Children?'' <ORGANIZATION> CPB </ORGANIZATION> is a private, nonprofit corporation funded by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to develop noncommercial radio and television services. Copies of the booklet are available for $ 1 each, by ch