<HEAD>After A Month of Missiles, Tehran Fears Poison Gas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-end with 18 grafs to ADD Khomeini remarks on
missiles and elections, reorder info. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The warning broadcast over the radio for the first time Thursday was simple: three beeps, a pause, then three more beeps. That signal would mean <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has launched a poison gas attack on <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, where Iraqi missiles have fallen day and night and where fears of chemical warfare by <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> are growing. After the warning beeps on <ORGANIZATION> Tehran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>, an announcer said: `` God willing, we hope no such thing will ever happen, but the enemy is so mean and despicable he could do anything.'' An official of the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guidance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> escorting visiting Western correspondents around the battered capital, a city of more than 6 million people, said the Iraqis `` would pay dearly if they dared to do it.'' The city of <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> seems to have paid enough already. Officials said half of its population has left since <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s missiles began wrecking apartment houses, markets, shops, office buildings, hospitals and schools. On Thursday, many <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> schools and stores stayed closed in case of attack, but people came up to the streets from underground shelters. There were few of the traffic jams for which <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> was notorious before the missiles. The missiles that have been rained on the city since Feb. 29, when the Iraqis began firing such weapons into <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> for the first time in the war. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> says it has launched more than 100 surface-to-surface rockets at <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> in that period. Others have have hit the holy city of <LOCATION> Qom </LOCATION>, 100 miles to the south, and <LOCATION> Isfahan </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which was the capital of <LOCATION> Persia </LOCATION> during the 17th century. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has fired about half as many missiles into <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, a city of 5 million. A statement by <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> exhorted his people to ignore <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> missiles and turn out for the April 8 parliamentary elections. `` Even if the nation is subjected to missile and bombing attacks, it will go to the ballot box,'' said the statement, read on the radio by an announcer. `` I personally will participate in the elections under any conditions.'' By Thursday, no Iraqi missiles had exploded in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> for three days, although other cities were hit. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> declared Thursday that it was suspending attacks for three days because of a visit to <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> by <PERSON> Turgut </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON>, prime minister of <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. Officials in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> said they believe the reason is the scheduled arrival Monday of two <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> experts, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Holger </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and Dr. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmona </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, to investigate the alleged <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> gas attacks in <LOCATION> Kurdistan </LOCATION>. A 1925 <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement outlaws the use of chemical weapons. Civilians usually have about four minutes notice of incoming rockets after they are detected by radar installations at the border, about 290 miles to the west. The radio and street loudspeakers blare warnings. People scurry to bomb shelters, basements and underground parking lots. Yellow signs on walls show where shelters are located. State television broadcasts film of Londoners sheltering in subway stations during the German blitz of 1940. The message seems to be that, like <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and its Allies, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> will win the war. But it is poison gas that residents of <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> fear most, according to those questioned randomly on the streets Thursday. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said Iraqi warplanes dropped cyanide and mustard gas bombs on three Kurdish towns in northeast <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> on March 16-17 after Iranian troops have captured them. The Iranians, at war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> since September 1980, said 5,000 civilians and some Iranian soldiers were killed, and another 5,000 people were wounded. They claimed the Iraqis dropped chemical bombs because the Kurds, long in rebellion against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, welcomed their `` liberators.'' <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> also said Thursday that <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> warplanes dropped chemical bombs on villages in the <LOCATION> Marivan </LOCATION> border region of northwest <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> earlier in the day, killing several people. After months of international criticism for failing to comply with a cease-fire resolution the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> passed last summer, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is making all the mileage possible from the claims of chemical warfare. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s official press has likened the alleged Iraqi use of gas bombs in <LOCATION> Kurdistan </LOCATION> to the Americans dropping atomic bombs on <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION> in 1945, and demanded international condemnation of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has denied the claims.
