<SECOND>AM-Hogs-Pork,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hog Production Continues To Climb Despite Slimmer Profits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hog farmers continue to expand production, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report showed Thursday. As of March 1, the inventory of hogs and pigs in the 10 major pork states totaled an estimated 40.5 million head, up 6 percent from both a year ago and two years ago, the report said. The number of breeding hogs was up 4 percent and 10 percent from March 1 of 1987 and 1986, respectively, to 5.42 million head. That indicated further production increases in the months ahead. Officials said the March 1 inventory of market hogs _ animals headed for slaughter and the consumer market _ totaled 35.1 million head, up 6 percent and 5 percent from the previous two years. The pig crop during the winter months of December, January and February was 15.8 million head, up 6 percent from the same period of 1986-87, the report said, and 11 percent more than in the winter of two years ago. Looking a future prospects, the report said hog farmers surveyed intend to have 2.4 million sows give birth in the March-May period, 2 percent more than a year ago and 11 percent more than the actual farrowings of two years ago. The 10 leading hog states account for about 79 percent of the nation's pork. The following list shows the March 1 inventory. The first number, in thousands, is the total number of hogs in the state, the second is the March 1 figure's percentage of a year earlier.
