<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former presidential aide <PERSON> Lyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> should be imprisoned for illegally lobbying the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> because he flouted the law and compared his offense to `` running a stop sign,'' a prosecutor said Thursday in court papers. Independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> said in a sentencing memo that remarks <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> made following his conviction Feb. 11 showed `` a total lack of remorse or contrition'' about violating the Ethics in Government Act's ban on lobbying former colleagues less than a year afte leaving government service. <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>, 63, should be fined and imprisoned to `` impress present and former government employees, as well as the general public, that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> intended those restrictions to be taken seriously and that they will be enforced with meaningful penalties,'' <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> said in the memo filed with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Flannery </PERSON>. Minutes after the verdict, <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> stood outside the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Courthouse and called the ethics statute `` a lousy law.'' He also said, `` I do n't think I did anything wrong'' and compared the offense to `` running a stop sign.'' <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s former political director, repeated his profession of innocence in a Feb. 18 letter to the court that was quoted in the prosecution brief. `` I have never thought, and I do not think today, that I am guilty morally, ethically or legally of the crimes of which I am convicted,'' he wrote. <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> said `` that intransigent attitude is a consideration arguing in favor of a sentence that includes a period of incarceration.'' The sentencing is scheduled for April 8. `` To request jail time for a 63-year-old man with a spotless record of public service who did not intend to violate the law is ridiculous, unnecessary and totally lacking in compassion,'' said defense lawyer <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Barcella </PERSON>. <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> said <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> also ignored the advice of lawyers he consulted about the ethics law when he left <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s staff in early 1982 to form a consulting business with <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bragg </PERSON>. The prosecution brief recounted an incident in which <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> uttered a profanity when one of the attorneys, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Artiano </PERSON>, advised him not to make any White House contacts without first contacting the law firm. During the trial, associate independent counsel <PERSON> Merrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Garland </PERSON> related the episode to the judge during a bench conference out of hearing of the jury and the public, according to the trial transcript. <PERSON> Garland </PERSON> told the judge that after responding with the profanity, <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> said, `` These are my friends and I am going back to them if I want to.'' <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> noted in the sentencing memo that <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>'s defense lawyers have `` attempted to minimize the significance of this episode by asserting that defendant <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>'s profanity ... was characteristic of their client's jocularity.'' `` Perhaps so,'' <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> wrote, `` but his lawyers at the time took the incident seriously. They have told staff members of the independent counsel that this episode caused concern'' within the law firm. `` Whatever his choice of words, however, it is evident that defendant <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> was alerted to and deliberately chose to ignore written and oral advice that Section 207 -L