<HEAD>Pedal-Pusher Plane Succeeds in Test Flight Before World Record
Attempt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, ``Friday's test ... and 9th graf, ``Conditions
appeared ... to CORRECT Friday to Thursday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRAKLION, Crete (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sophisticated, ultralight aircraft run by human power made six successful test flights Thursday preparing for a record distance attempt inspired by the 3,500-year-old Greek myth of <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION>. The record attempt was to be made Friday, but organizers of the 3-year-old, $ 1 million project postponed the flight until the weekend because gusts of up to 30 mph are expected Friday. The <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> project is aimed at breaking the world record for human-powered flight over the 74-mile distance from <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION> to the island of <LOCATION> Santorini </LOCATION>, also known as Thira. Thursday's test flights each lasted less than three minutes in calm dawn weather above a <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> air force base next to <LOCATION> Iraklion </LOCATION> airport. Flight Director <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bussulari </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> aerospace expert, told reporters the 68-pound <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> 88 `` is in good shape ... and we may see favorable conditions'' for a flight Saturday or Sunday. Five pilots _ four Americans and a <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> _ took turns pedaling the pink-and-silver ultralight at speeds of about 14 mph, flying about 15 feet above the tarmac. The craft is named in honor of the mythical inventor <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION>, who tried with his son <PERSON> Icarus </PERSON> to escape from <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION> on wings made of feathers and wax. <PERSON> Daedalus </PERSON> succeeded, but <PERSON> Icarus </PERSON> flew too near the sun, the wax melted and he fell into the sea. The record flight requires temperatures below 70 degrees and almost dead calm. Conditions appeared perfect Thursday following nine days of blustery weather. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Scioscia </PERSON>, 27, a professional cyclist from <LOCATION> Scranton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, reported, `` It feels like a day for the record, pretty calm. I was flying the plane with no hands.'' But <PERSON> Bussulari </PERSON> noted that <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> 88 would have run into strong headwinds about five miles off <LOCATION> Santorini </LOCATION> and that in any case, `` We felt we needed a test flight to shake down the airplane.'' The pilots are taking turns standing by in readiness for the flight. The pilot who had been scheduled to fly Friday was <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Zack </PERSON>, 26, of <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, whose father was born in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. The pilot pumps bicycle pedals that turn the ultralight's propeller He uses a joystick to steer the plane, coordinating with ground-based radio instructions. `` For the record the pilot must keep pedaling a steady 15 mph but the effort is equivalent to riding 23 miles an hour on land,'' said <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Tremml </PERSON>, a medical student from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>. Tremml set the 37.2-mile world record for human-powered flight in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in 1987, flying a <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> prototype Two backup flying machines are ready if needed. All the craft are made of lightweight composite material _ graphite epoxy, plastic fiber and mylar, an extra-thin plastic skin that covers the 112-foot wingspan. Its organizers said the Daedalus project has produced new information on endurance and low altitude flying aerodynamics and meteorology during its three years of development. Project director <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Langford </PERSON> explained, `` The project does have a research and educational application, particularly in human physiology and aeronautics. The plane itself does n't have any practical application. It should be seen as a work of art.''
