 `` I'm not trying to cast any blame or concern upon them. That was the system. They've got their laws. They've got things they've got to comply with and we're trying to help them through changes in <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> regulation.'' He played down the amount of money involved, saying it was not significant. Asked if it was not a setback for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, `` It's a minor setback in the sense that one day there's zero -LRB- money -RRB- and the next day there's something, but these are fairly small payments in the total picture and are not going to solve Mr. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s very serious and long-term problem.'' He said the administration was studying a plan by which the companies would make tax payments into an account in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> controlled by President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, who has been in hiding since demanding <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s resignation. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continues to recognize <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> as the legitimate head of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s government. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> resolution was introduced by Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. `` The use of these monies -LRB- paid by American companies -RRB- has enabled Gen. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to buy himself time and prolong himself in power as he ruthlessly continues in his efforts to thwart the democratic will of the people of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and crush the general strike,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said. The resolution urges <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to use his authority under the Emergency Economic Powers Act `` to prevent future transfers to the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> regime of currency and credit subject to t