<HEAD>Church Leaders Criticize Dissidents, Seek to Ease Restrictions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Five grafs SUB for 9th graf pvs, Yakunin was ... UPDATING
with Yakunin comments. Picks up 10th graf pvs, Filaret said ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Church leaders said Thursday they are working with the authorities to ease restrictions on religion in a society dominated by atheists, but may fail unless clerical dissidents stop causing trouble. Metropolitan Filaret of <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Galitsky </PERSON> said the Rev. <PERSON> Gleb </PERSON> <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON>, a former political prisoner, and the Rev. <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Gainov </PERSON> were two of those in the Russian Orthodox church who seek `` to press on us methods of solving our problems that would lead to confrontation between church and state.'' He described the dissidents as a small group of priests and lay people. The church always has cooperated with the government, which is dominated by the officially atheist <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, but its leaders say they want to moderate a 1929 law that requires registration of religious groups and prevents charitable activities and religious education of the young. Although they did not directly attack the law during a news conference, their veiled criticisms appeared to be among the strongest in years. <PERSON> Filaret </PERSON> stressed, however, that the church `` will continue to use the same method of solving problems it has used in the whole post-revolutionary period.'' Last week, <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON> called for the resignation of Patriarch <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON>, 78, as head of the Russian Orthodox church on grounds he is ill and senile. The priest also has criticized the willingness of church leaders to subordinate themselves to the government, demanding greater freedom to practice religion and publication of more religious books. <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON> was excluded from the ministry for 20 years, but reinstated last year and assigned to a small parish outside <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Contacted by telephone Thursday night, <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON> said <PERSON> Filaret </PERSON>'s comments were moderate `` Earlier they -LRB- church leaders -RRB- would have taken our work away and imprisoned us. It's a sign of perestroika that they are willing to listen to us,'' <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON> said, referring to Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s word for restructuring of society. <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON> said he and Gainov are not seeking confrontation between church and state but simply want to `` help the church improve its situation.'' `` We think church leaders are falling behind matters of perestroika and want them to work more actively,'' he said. <PERSON> Filaret </PERSON> said the church has the right to discipline dissidents, but `` we are urging them to use common sense and join with us to solve the problems.'' Archbishop <PERSON> Kiril </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Smolensk </LOCATION> said the government is rewriting the 1929 law and consulting Russian Orthodox officials, but described the consultations as a `` discussion of principle'' not involving the text. <PERSON> Kiril </PERSON> said the law, adopted at the height of anti-religious fervor after the 1917 Bolshevik revolution, was no longer appropriate for Soviet society. He said the replacement statute should be ready soon, but the text was not complete and he could not provide details. The archbishop said church officials were optimistic that it `` will open the possibility for a fuller church life for all believers.'' A list was revealed of nine people who will be made saints during celebrations in June of the 1,000 th anniversary of Christianity in what is now the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> Metropolitan Yuvenali of <PERSON> Krutitsky </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kolomensky </PERSON> granted that the list did not include anyone killed during the repression after the revolution, as critics have demanded. He said study of the issue would continue. Yuvenali accused the Russian Orthodox church that split away after the revolution and now is based abroad of canonizing such people for political purposes. Church officials said Patriarch <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON> participated in opening and closing ceremonies and fulfilled his other obligations during a three-day conference completed Thursday.
