<DATELINE>FORST, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> jet fighter slammed into the middle of this small town and exploded Thursday, killing the American pilot and at least one resident, injuring 16 people and forcing scores to evacuate. `` The neighborhood looks like the bombed-out houses of World War II,'' said <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Loef </PERSON>, a 52-year-old baker who lives down the street from where the F-16 crashed into at least five homes. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> spokesman Capt. <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Cody </PERSON> identified the pilot as Lt. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON>, 24, of <LOCATION> Oroville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. He entered active duty in May 1985 and had been at Hahn Air Base since September 1987. He graduated from the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> in 1985. Wreckage was scattered over a wide area, and several hours after the flames had been doused, black smoke still billowed from <PERSON> Forst </PERSON>, a town of 6,000 people. Emergency crews evacuated more than 70 residents because the plane was carrying a canister of hydrazine, which is used to restart engines and which produces toxic gas when mixed with water. Officials said there was no evidence of a gas leak. The plane crashed eight miles from a nuclear power plant, one day after a French jet fighter crashed and exploded just a mile from a nuclear plant in the West German state of <LOCATION> Bavaria </LOCATION>. The pilot in that accident also was killed. The crashes sparked calls from members of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s opposition <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> and the environmentalist Greens party for more restrictions on military training flights Witnesses reported seeing smoke and flames pouring from the F-16 as it plunged toward <PERSON> Forst </PERSON>, about 60 miles south of <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. It struck the roof of one house, tore off the front of another and set several on fire, they said. <PERSON> Hilde </PERSON> <PERSON> Loef </PERSON> said her first thought when she saw the jet was, `` My God, the planes are coming awfully low today.'' `` Then I saw smoke and flames streaming out of the jet,'' she said. The body of <PERSON> Theo </PERSON> <PERSON> Huber </PERSON>, 60, was found in the wreckage of his home, officials said. Rescuers were searching for any other victims. Twelve firefighters were hospitalized for smoke inhalation, two residents were treated for shock, and two more were being held for observation in a hospital after apparently suffering smoke inhalation, officials said. Authorities said the 10 a.m. disaster could have been far worse had the plane crashed a couple of hours earlier, before residents left for work. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Maj. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> told reporters at the scene that an investigation into the cause of the crash was under way. He said there was no live ammunition on the jet. The F-16 was part of the 50th Tactical Fighter Wing based at the <ORGANIZATION> Hahn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in the nearby <LOCATION> Eifel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, said Lt. Col. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Neunherz </PERSON>, another <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. The crash occurred 185 miles west of Wednesday's crash of the French jet fighter, which went down in the Bavarian village of <LOCATION> Ohu </LOCATION> near the <LOCATION> Isar </LOCATION> nuclear plant. Environmentalists maintained the country had escaped disaster by a `` split second,'' and the accident raised concerns about military flights over nuclear power plants. But officials said the concrete domes built over <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> nuclear plants are designed to withstand the force of a plane crash, so there was no danger of a nuclear accident.
