PERSON>'s criminal trial April 21 if they took evidence on the last charge. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON>, Democratic minority leader, said Thursday neither he nor the 10 other Democrats who voted for dismissal were willing to reconsider. One of those who voted on the prevailing side would have had to seek reconsideration for the matter to be reopened. `` There was a lot of backroom manipulating today,'' said <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON>. `` People apparently made their decisions on the merits of the arguments and that did n't change in 24 hours.'' Only five of the 19 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republicans supported the dismissal of the last charge. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> rules gave members 24 hours to rescind any action. <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said his main concern was not letting the trial drag on past <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s scheduled May 17 recall election. But some Republicans argued that they were duty-bound to hear all the evidence on all the charges. Republican <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON> complained angrily that the Democrats had divided the impeachment proceeding along partisan lines for the first time since it began Feb. 29. `` That action yesterday was political roulette,'' he said. `` If there are not the votes to convict, and Gov. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> is back on the ninth floor -LRB- in the governor's office -RRB- on Wednesday ... they have dealt themselves a losing hand,'' West said. It would require a two-thirds vote of the 30-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to convict <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>. If he is convict, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> may then take a vote to disqualify him from ever holding office again.
