of dancing and yelling and singing when the announcement came over the wire _ but that's not unusual for the Journal newsroom,'' quipped <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Tharpe </PERSON>, managing editor. The Journal and the Lawrence -LRB- Mass. -RRB- Eagle-Tribune each won an award for general news reporting; the <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> paper's series dealt with infant mortality. `` The Journal decided it was time to commit some resources to the problem,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, executive editor of the Journal and its sister daily, The Montgomery Advertiser. `` A Pulitzer Prize is nice,'' said <PERSON> Tharpe </PERSON>, `` but it's a plaque on the wall. If we hope something will come of our work as journalists, it's that the state will deal with the problem of infant mortality.'' At the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>, the winners were <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Baquet </PERSON>, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaines </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lipinski </PERSON> for investigative reporting on `` on the self-interest and waste that plague <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>.'' `` We're thrilled. It's been quite a few years since we've won one here for local news coverage,'' said <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Soeteber </PERSON>, assistant <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> managing editor for metropolitan news. `` I think the team of reporters deserved this so much. ... It was their idea, and they brought it off beautifully,'' she said. `` I'm so glad some of the leaders in our profession recognized it.'' The Wall Street Journal captured two prizes: <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> Bogdanich </PERSON> for specialized reporting and <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hertzberg </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart 