<HEAD>Panama Accuses U.S. of Looking for Excuse to Invade</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES thruout with government accusing U.S. of looking for
reason to invade, ordering military not to invade, White House
action; no pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government accused the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Thursday of looking for a pretext to invade <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, and said it ordered its military not to harm Americans in the country. Government offices closed Thursday for a long Easter weekend that looks bleak for 130,000 public employees, who were left without paychecks for the second time this month. An eerie quiet gripped the streets of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, which had been filled in recent days with demonstrations against Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> commander who controls the civilian government. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON>, the president installed by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, said in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> armed forces in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and its waters constituted a threat to the country. `` In spite of the situation created by the mobilization of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces ... the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> have orders to refrain from using lethal or destructive weapons at any time against the armed forces of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> civilians,'' said the letter, released by the presidency. The `` mobilization'' of forces apparently referred to the passage this week of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> helicopter carrier <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> through the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military maneuvers in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> that began in early March. `` Aware of the overwhelming power threatening it, the Republic of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> ... will not provide the foundation for fabrication of a charge of aggression that could pretend to justify the launching of acts of war against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' the letter said. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has raised the possibility that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military might be used to protect the estimated 50,000 American citizens in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> against possible harrassment by that country's security forces. It made the suggestion after Panamanian soldiers arrested and beat several journalists, including <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> reporters, during a raid Monday on a <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> hotel. With most businesses and industries observing an 11-day-old general strike against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> Thursday, the largest congregations of people in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> were found in the food lines of welfare agencies. Leaders of the National Civic Crusade were meeting to plan new strategies in their frustrated effort to oust <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. `` We'll be talking over the weekend, discussing where we go from here,'' said <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Aleman </PERSON>, a director of the Crusade, a coalition of about 200 professional, business, labor, political and other groups. In <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, former President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> said he understood <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> had promised to resign in May, the unofficial start of a presidential campaign leading to elections in May 1989. The general is under indictment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges. Major supermarkets and drug stores, and a few small