<HEAD>US Seeking Agreement From Soviets on Continued Aid to Combatants</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New thruout with Shultz saying Soviets could keep arming
Kabul if US could keep supplying rebels.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANNON, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said Thursday the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> could keep arming Marxist forces in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> as part of a peace agreement, provided the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could maintain supplies to the rebels. `` It would be better to have a moratorium,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said as he launched another overseas trip to pursue peace in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. But, he told reporters aboard a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> jet en route to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, `` To date, the Soviets have not wanted to do that.'' The issue of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet military aid to rival forces is the main roadblock to an agreement to end the war in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> after more than eight years. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> proposed in March to Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> that both sides declare a moratorium. It would be in effect while the Soviets withdrew their estimated 120,000 trroops and for three months afterward. The Soviets accused the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of posing a last-minute obstacle to an agreement. Negotiations between <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which were held under <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> auspices, stalled. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, who will go on to <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> on Sunday to begin a five-day <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> shuttle, made it clear he preferred a suspension of Soviet aid to the Marxists and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for the resistance group. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid has included Stinger missiles that were effective against Soviet aircraft and he