nvolved for months in U.N.-sponsored efforts to bring about a withdrawal of the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops fighting in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The Soviets have agreed in principle to begin the troop withdrawal two months after a settlement is reached and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is eager for such a deal so that millions of Afghan refugees on Pakistani territory can go home. Preventing a final agreement, however, has been a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> demand that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> stop aiding the Afghan government after Soviet troops depart. Until such aid ceases, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will continue backing the Afghan rebels, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has said. During talks with <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> last month, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> renewed a plea for what the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been calling a `` symmetrical cessation'' of superpower aid to the Afghan combatants. The new proposal, rather than calling for symmetrical cessation of aid, envisions parallel continuation of assistance. `` We now express the policy in terms of ` we will continue aid to the Mujahadeen as long as the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> continues aid to the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government,''' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` The basic point to make is that our policy has not changed in the sense that we will not desert the Afghan rebels,'' the spokesman said. `` We will not cut off money to them as long as the Soviets are providing aid.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> did not explain how the new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> language might be more palatable to the Soviets except to say `` there are some negotiating reasons why it could hopefully allow the agreement to be signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> and clear the way for a pullout.'' A <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said `` it would go too far,'' to say <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> signaled an interest in the proposal last week, although he did not specifically reject the idea. The source said that before the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal was devised, some administration officials warned against making an agreement to continue aid to the Afghan combatants part of a secret understanding with the Soviets. It would be against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law to sign an Afghan peace accord that required a cutoff of aid to the resistance forces while agreeing privately with the Soviets to continue such assistance, the official said. Asked on Thursday if a decision to continue aid would be part of an open agreement, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said `` that's always been our stance.''
