<HEAD>OSCAR COUNTDOWN: Best Actor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Comedy Makes a Rare Appearance Among Best Actor Nominees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Comedy makes a rare appearance in this year's Academy Awards, with stand-up comic <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> vying with four dramatic performers for the prize as best actor Some critics of <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON>'s seriousness argue that <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> should have been nominated for best actor because of his modern-day <PERSON> Cyrano </PERSON> in `` Roxanne.'' But in a year that saw a number of impressive performances by comedians, only <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> drew the nod for his manic disc jockey in `` Good Morning, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> plays <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronauer </PERSON>, the real-life announcer who regaled American troops with jokes and rock' n' roll over the <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> service </ORGANIZATION>. The funny side of the role was a breeze for <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, and director <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Levinson </PERSON> allowed him free rein. `` Obviously, the radio part offered me a chance to do some open-field running,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> says. `` <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> had been a comic himself, and he would spark to some of my suggestions and let me go with them. Many of the things in the movie, like the <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> impression and playing records at different speeds, happened spontaneously.'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' depth of feeling in the later, dramatic scenes of `` Good Morning, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'' surprised some reviewers. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> studied drama under <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Houseman </PERSON> at the famed <ORGANIZATION> Juilliard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, but even then his comedic side was emerging. One of his teachers chided him: `` You're mimicking people. Where is YOUR voice?'' He soon found it. After a broken romance, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> dropped out of Juilliard and began playing <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> comedy clubs. The comic's contenders in the best actor race are thought of as being more dramatic thespians. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> was considered for two powerful roles: as the venomous inside trader of `` Wall Street'' and the erring husband of `` Fatal Attraction.'' The actors branch of the Academy decided to nominate him for `` Wall Street.'' `` It was a marvelous role that <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> wrote,'' <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> says. `` I do n't know why he chose me for the part, but he must have seen something in me that even I did n't even know about. `` Playing a heavy is just fantastic; it's so much more fun than being the good guy. I can understand the attraction that -LRB- villains -RRB- have for actors. `` All of us try to be civilized human beings, but deep down inside we have this feeling to tell everything like it is. The part of <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Gecco </PERSON> was a wonderful opportunity for this release. After playing moral redeeeming characters and goodie guys, it was a ball.'' Can an actor win an Oscar for a performance in a foreign language? <PERSON> Sophia </PERSON> <PERSON> Loren </PERSON> did it in 1961 with `` Two Women.'' Now <PERSON> Marcello </PERSON> <PERSON> Mastroianni </PERSON> stands a chance for his role as the vain Italian aristocrat who pursues a new love to <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> in `` Dark Eyes.'' <PERSON> Mastroianni </PERSON> has acted in 116 films, and he still averages three a year. Why does he work so hard at 64? `` Basically, I am an empty person,'' he said. `` When I act I feel complete because I use the personalities of these characters to fill this emptiness. I am also a childish person, and what better way to live life than by traveling to all these countries and getting paid to have fun and act like a fool, no?'' What <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurt </PERSON> feels about acting is not publicly known, since he is one of the least interviewed of film stars. Obviously, he is doing something right, since he has been nominated three times in seven films and won the Oscar for `` Kiss of the Spider Woman'' two years ago. His latest nomination came for his portrayal of <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Grunick </PERSON>, the handsome but not-too-bright network anchor man in `` Broadcast News.'' Hurt's few interviews have produced somewhat turgid quotes. As he himself explains: `` I have, fortunately or unforunately, skill at going down paths of endless non sequiturs. In a recent Premiere magazine interview, <PERSON> Hurt </PERSON> expounded on what he considered the major question of `` Broadcast News.'' `` What is the nature, to put it simply, of romance in our time? What are our motives in wanting to be together? How do we pair up? Who do we mate with, and why do we do it? A lot of us do n't know the answer, a lot of us feel in flux,'' he said. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicholson </PERSON> has also been recently scarce in the media, apparently content to do his work without theorizing about it in public. In 1987, he shone in three roles: as the devil in `` The Witches of Eastwick''; as the Depression bum in `` Ironweed''; as star network anchor in `` Broadcast News.'' He won his ninth nomination for his role as the former big-league ballplayer in `` Ironweed.'' Despite the cynical roles he has played, <PERSON> Nicholson </PERSON> has maintained that he remains an optimist. In a 1986 interview he remarked: `` I do n't want to do what I accuse other people of doing: not taking the time to smell the roses. Something very wonderful has happened to me. I do n't want the fact that I see this endless din and gloom in the world to make me incapable of expressing something that's quite frankly wonderful. I'm a very fortunate person to be where I am and do what I do.''
