<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> found out that she had been nominated for an Academy Award as supporting actress when a friend called her at 5 a.m. `` Within 15 minutes a television crew was at the house,'' she said. `` I had time to wash my face, and that was about all. I was absolutely flabbergasted.'' The nomination of <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON>, <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> DeVito </PERSON>'s horrendous mother in `` Throw Momma From the Train,'' provided one of the highlights of a race that includes a 60-year veteran of films, the cousin of a presidential candidate, a classic Argentine actress and a young actress who stood her own against a galvanizing performance by <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Close </PERSON>. Here is a look at the nominees: <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Aleandro </PERSON> played the Mexican Indian who devoted her life to be the constant companion of a severely handicapped girl in `` Gaby.'' A distinguished theater actress in <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>, she was forced into exile by the military government of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. After the junta was overthrown, she returned home to star in the Oscar-winning `` The Official Story,'' which dealt with the atrocities of the regime. `` Gaby'' was Miss <PERSON> Aleandro </PERSON>'s first film in English. She regrets that the movie has found a limited audience, apparently because people were scared away by its theme. `` It's not a sad movie,'' she says. `` We are not speaking about sadness. We are speaking about people, about seeking freedom. Sometimes people forget that freedom is in the mind.'' <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Archer </PERSON> was nominated for the part of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' wife in `` Fatal Attraction.'' Considering the galvanic role afforded <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Close </PERSON> as the vengeful other woman, you might think that <PERSON> Archer </PERSON> would have had reservations about her role. `` Not at all,'' she says. `` I always thought that -LRB- the wife -RRB- was a strong and interesting character, and she got to go through an interesting change. That is something you always look for: It's important that a character be different at the end of a script than in the beginning `` She was sexy and vulnerable and strong. An interesting lady. I never felt even remotely that she would be overshadowed.'' <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Sothern </PERSON> made her first movie in 1929, according to the record books. After a long and diverse career in films and television, mostly in comedy, she won her first Academy recognition for a serious role in `` The Whales of August.'' Along with co-stars <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lillian </PERSON> <PERSON> Gish </PERSON> and <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sothern </PERSON> filmed `` The Whales of August'' on a remote <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> island. `` There was no hotel, only a tiny store,'' she recalls. `` We all stayed in private homes; mine was a lobster fisherman's. The weather was murder: beautiful and sunny in the morning, and stormy in the afternoon. `` There was absolutely nothing to do at night. Fortunately, I brought my cook and my poker chips.'' <PERSON> Olympia </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has long been a working actress in theater, films and television, but she did n't impress a national audience until `` Moonstruck.'' Her success came at the same time her first cousin, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, sought the Democratic nomination for president. She grew up in a Greek family in which everybody argued politics. After graduating from <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, she worked as a physical therapist to earn enough money to return and study theater arts. Despite her newfound fame, she intends to remain in the theater; she is the artistic director of the Whole Theater in <LOCATION> Montclair </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> `` I'm not convinced this being a celebrity is going to be long-lived,'' she says cautiously. Fame was also a long time coming for <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON>: `` Thirty-nine years later, after everything I've tried to do and everything I've wanted, this has happened What a curious moment. Thank God, thank <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> DeVito </PERSON>, who directed ` Momma' -RRB-, thank everybody.'' <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> has more to be thankful for than an Academy nomination. A year and a half ago, she underwent surgery for cancer of the tongue. She apparently has recovered, but reconstruction of her tongue gave her slurred speech. Happily, it fit perfectly into the character of the fierce Momma. The actress admits that she dreamed of an Oscar as a child growing up in suburban <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I have a diary in which I wrote about it,'' she said. `` I was a real movie buff when I was a little girl. I read all the fan magazines, and I wrote for autographs and pictures from the stars. I wanted to be an actress from the time my father took me to see ` The Petrified Forest' at the age of 4. `` I fell in love with actors, especially in the romantic films _ <PERSON> Tyrone </PERSON> <PERSON> Power </PERSON>, <PERSON> Errol </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>, <PERSON> Greer </PERSON> <PERSON> Garson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Pidgeon </PERSON>. I just loved movies. And now this -LRB- nomination -RRB- has happened. It's unbelievable.
