<SECOND>PM-Mystery of Oradour, Adv 08,0848</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs April 8 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Book Revives Mystery of Nazi Massacre in France</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 ORADOUR-SUR-GLANE, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ Just after lunch on the warm afternoon of June 10, 1944, the Nazi SS began rounding up people in this prosperous country town and dividing them into groups. Then they tortured, shot and burned them. Historians have long pondered the reasons for the slaughter of 642 children, women and men and the destruction of Oradour-sur-Glane, carried out four days after the Allied invasion of <LOCATION> Normandy </LOCATION> in a village with no history of ties to the French Resistance. A new book by a British businessman, <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackness </PERSON>, claims to solve the mystery, suggesting that the massacre was a desperate attempt by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> to find a lost fortune in gold. Survivors of the massacre and the families of those who died have vowed to stop publication in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> of `` <LOCATION> Oradour </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Massacre </ORGANIZATION> and Aftermath,'' already No. 5 on the British bestseller list and scheduled for publication by <ORGANIZATION> Random </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this fall. They claim the book warps history and insults the memory of <LOCATION> Oradour </LOCATION>'s `` martyrs.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hebras </PERSON>, 62, who says he hid under the bodies of his neighbors to escape Nazi bullets, put it more bluntly. `` Everyone makes money from the name of Oradour-sur-Glane. This must cease.'' <LOCATION> Oradour </LOCATION> has been preserved _ in ruins _ exactly as it was the day the Germans marched off after the slaughter. In 1945 the French government declared the centuries-old village near <LOCATION> Limoges </LOCATION> a national historic site and it has been visited by more than 500,000 people each year. Plaques mark the sheds, cellars and barns where men were shot in the knees, interrogated, then machine gunned and their bodies burned. A cross stands outside the church where women and children huddled in terror for hours listening to gunfire kill their menfolk before the SS came to gun them down and set the sanctuary ablaze. A piece of twisted metal in the corner of the altar was once a baby carriage. A car on the village green rusts where it was parked by the mayor's son. Only 13 people survived. `` My wife lost all her family, her mother, sister, uncle, aunt,'' said <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Montaigne </PERSON>, a spokesman for the survivors' association `` She still goes to the ruins because she feels at home there. She sees them all, even though they are dead.'' The new Oradour-sur-Glane, built adjacent to the ruins, has taken decades to recover. `` No one got married here for 20 years and it was only a couple of years ago that we had a wedding in June,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lapuelle </PERSON>, mayor of the town since 1959. `` It was 1963 before we had enough youngsters to make a soccer team. `` No wonder people here are upset about this book.'' Mackness' story is full of intrigue and personal adventure involving smuggled gold ingots and a shadowy figure named <PERSON> Raoul </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mackness </PERSON> writes that <PERSON> Raoul </PERSON> told him that the ingots were a part of more than half a ton of gold that he and a few French Resistance companions seized during a midnight ambush of an SS convoy. According to the book, the only survivors of the ambush were <PERSON> Raoul </PERSON>, who buried the treasure by the side of the road, and a German soldier who reported the event. The gold apparently was a sort of floating pension fund for some officers of the 2nd SS Panzer Division, planning to stash it in <LOCATION> Swiss </LOCATION> banks for after the war, <PERSON> Mackness </PERSON> writes. It goes on to say that following the ambush, SS Maj. <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickmann </PERSON> rushed to the scene and, finding nothing and panicking, dashed to <LOCATION> Oradour </LOCATION>, the nearest village. About 10 books have offered different explanations for the slaughter. But all have left questions dangling. Mackness claims to answer many of these, but he seems to be having trouble getting anyone to accept his story because his sources are concealed. <PERSON> Dickmann </PERSON> and <PERSON> Raoul </PERSON> are dead. <PERSON> Mackness </PERSON> refuses to divulge the names of his living sources, many of whom, he says, fear prosecution for the massacre. For many historians, <PERSON> Mackness </PERSON>' word is n't enough. `` No historic fact allows me to give this business the least credibility,'' <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Delarue </PERSON>, a French historian, was quoted by the French newspaper <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Figaro </PERSON> as saying. But Mackness stands by his story. `` It fits the known historical facts,'' he said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. `` The people in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> who object to my book have n't read it because it has n't been, and may not be, published there.'' In <LOCATION> Oradour </LOCATION>, Mackness is accused of dancing on the graves of the dead. `` Mr. <PERSON> Mackness </PERSON>' ambush never happened, at least not near <LOCATION> Oradour </LOCATION>,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Lapuelle </PERSON>, who added that the villagers want to preserve the simple, brutal truth of the event, so `` this will never happen again.''
</TEXT>
