<HEAD>Film Teaches Safe Sex to Retarded Adults</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retarded men and women around the nation are being shown an explicit videotape about sex in hopes it will help keep them safe from AIDS. The video uses startling illustrations _ including still photographs of surrogates in specific sexual positions. `` You ca n't generalize or use words. They do n't know what you're talking about,'' explained <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, program director of the <ORGANIZATION> Cerebral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palsy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION>, which will present the video at 12 group homes `` Their ability to abstract information is impaired,'' added <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> <PERSON> Porper </PERSON>, a public health educator from the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> who appears in the film. `` You have to deal absolutely in black and white, with no grays, and it has to be reiterated in several ways, preferably multi-sensory.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Adult </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, the non-profit agency that created the 17-minute video, with help from the city health department, acknowledges the idea offends some people. `` Someone called from <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and said, ` How dare you put homosexuals on the tape?''' said <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Samowitz </PERSON>, the institute's training director `` We do n't want to come across as crazy liberals from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> who are promoting promiscuity. But what are the alternatives? We do n't want our clients to die _ no matter who gives us flak.'' The main goal is `` to make sure a condom is worn'' if a retarded adult decides to have sex, <PERSON> Samowitz </PERSON> said. For <PERSON> Tina </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>, who has Down's syndrome and lives with 14 other mildly retarded people in their 20s and 30s at a suburban <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> apartment building, talking about AIDS is scary. But after she saw the video, she said, `` I tried to urge that -LRB- condom use -RRB- to a friend at the workshop.'' `` There are times I do n't really want to talk about it or think about it,'' agreed fellow resident <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sigman </PERSON>. `` It's kind of painful, but it's better to learn all about it. AIDS kills.'' No statistics indicate how many AIDS victims are retarded, according to <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Fallis </PERSON>, spokesman for the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Porper </PERSON> said she knew of eight AIDS cases among the retarded in the metropolitan area, and a retarded New Yorker died last year of AIDS contracted through a blood transfusion, according to <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganim </PERSON>, a spokesman for the state <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> and Developmental Disabilities. The risk of AIDS is no less real for the retarded. And so the film is explicit. In one photograph, male surrogates are positioned as if they were about to engage in anal sex so viewers can understand the link between that practice and AIDS. Oral sex and the use of condoms in heterosexual intercourse are also illustrated. `` I'm sure we'll get one or two people who will go bananas about it,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>. `` A small proportion of people do not believe that their children, whether adults or not, have a right to be active or have knowledge of sexual activity.'' `` I do n't dare bring it up with my parents,'' said <PERSON> Abbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Colpoys </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> group home. `` My parents talk a lot about that kind of thing. They warn me about what could happen to me,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>. `` I say, ` Ma, please _ I can take care of myself. I care about myself.''' Teachers stress in group discussions that the film is not intended to advocate any act, and that abstinence is acceptable. Role-playing is included to help participants refuse unsafe sex. `` It teaches them how to be sensitive and relate to people in a caring, responsible way,'' said <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> YAI </ORGANIZATION>, which runs 50 programs for the retarded in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> area, including 24 group homes. Group home residents also practice putting condoms on a plastic penis and are told to use condoms themselves, even when it's not clear where a romantic moment will lead. `` The mildly and moderately retarded know their judgment is impaired,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Porper </PERSON>. `` If you give them a choice they are incapable of making _ like when to put on a condom _ it raises tremendous anxieties in them.'' Some professionals have qualms about the film's approach. `` I think the general feeling of our staff is that it was too negative, too scary,'' said <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Berger </PERSON>, prevention specialist with the <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Developmental Disabilities. YAI sent the tape to 150 agencies, and the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> council was among five that returned it, said <PERSON> Samowitz </PERSON>. `` They -LRB- the filmmakers -RRB- see this as a very serious issue and their intent is to make people aware of it by scaring them. We're concerned about that approach,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Berger </PERSON> It also concerns <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> group home resident <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Mintzer </PERSON>. She and her boyfriend understand safe sex, but can not use condoms because of poor hand coordination _ a problem for some retarded people. `` It's hard to talk about because it's scary,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Mintzer </PERSON>, who adamantly refused to see the film a second time. `` Sometimes, denial is an easier way of dealing with scary feelings,'' the residential supervisor, <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Eldridge </PERSON>, told others in the group. `` But I do n't feel it's healthy.'' Some members of the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> council also were bothered by the film's explicit nature or felt that it `` left some questions that might confuse people,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Berger </PERSON>. They agree the retarded need AIDS education, she said. `` But it's not like there's a canned program that works for everybody. Agencies have different perspectives, and communities have different attitudes.'' The film is out of the question for Roman Catholic programs for the retarded because of religious doctrine against condoms and premarital sex, said Monsignor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cassidy </PERSON>, director of health and hospitals for the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Archdiocese </LOCATION>. `` We'd be against it purely from the medical point of view,'' said <PERSON> Cassidy </PERSON>. `` Condoms fail. If we relied solely on condoms, we'd have every darn one of the females pregnant. Instead, abstinence is taught to the 350 retarded adults served through archdiocese programs. `` It's just a reinforcement of what we've been doing all along,'' said <PERSON> Cassidy </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ganim </PERSON>, the spokesman for the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> mental health office, felt ambivalent about the film. `` I certainly know it's explicit and some people have expressed concerns about that,'' he said. `` But by and large, what we have heard back about the tape has been positive. They've brought up the fact that there is a need for this kind of thing.'' Dr. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolbe </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> and Special Projects, said no one has studied what kind of AIDS information is available for the retarded and what might be effective. <PERSON> Kolbe </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> guidelines issued in January suggested that schools address the issue of AIDS education for the disabled. `` We need to think about it,'' said <PERSON> Kolbe </PERSON>. `` The questions, I think, are important ones.'' `` It's not like you should just forget about it and pretend AIDS does n't exist,'' said <PERSON> Lauren </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, a resident at the group home. `` A woman has to be prepared.''
</TEXT>
