<FIRST>a a AM-Ritalin-Matthews Adv04   03-31 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ritalin-Matthews, Adv 04,0565</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Murder Case Called Attention to Ritalin</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-R Is for Ritalin I</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON> was a sullen, introverted boy, fascinated with death, obsessed with fire. <PERSON> Shaun </PERSON> <PERSON> Ouillette </PERSON> was outgoing and happy; he played hockey and talked of counseling troubled youths. Sixteen months ago <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON> beat <PERSON> Ouillette </PERSON> to death with a baseball bat. Last month the 15-year-old was found guilty of second-degree murder and given life in prison. The horrible crime was n't the only link between murderer and victim. Both took Ritalin, a stimulant used to calm hyperactive children. And while the trial served as a stage to the debate over the drug, it also provided testimony on how Ritalin, in combination with other treatment, can help children, and how its casual use can allow deeper problems to go undetected. <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON>' attorney, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, claimed the drug nudged the boy into the madness it took to plan and commit murder. The <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, an anti-psychiatry group connected with the <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientology </ORGANIZATION>, trumpeted the case as an example of the dangers it associates with the drug. A stream of psychiatrists and psychologists gave offsetting testimony. Defense witnesses said <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON> was psychotic, that the Ritalin `` enhanced'' his obsession to kill. Prosecution witnesses said the boy's emotional problems were not enough to obscure his notion of right and wrong. Ritalin, they said, played no factor. Ironically, <PERSON> Ouillette </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Jeanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON>, says <PERSON> Ritalin </PERSON> helped her son, calming him enough to allow the counseling and therapy that taught him how to control himself. Guidelines by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pediatrics </ORGANIZATION> say Ritalin should be prescribed after detailed diagnosis and used only in combination with counseling and careful monitoring. According to testimony, <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON> received Ritalin without other therapy. His mother, <PERSON> Janet </PERSON>, portrayed him as a quiet child who said little more than yes or no in his early years. When he became a behavioral problem in the third grade, a pediatrican prescribed Ritalin. Mrs. <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON> said there were no special psychological or physical tests, no monitoring of her son's progress over the next five years. Mrs. <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON> said her son went off the drug a few months before the killing, then asked for more pills a few weeks later. A bottle of Ritalin was found in his school locker; no one knows if he was taking the drug at the time of the killing. In contrast, Mrs. <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON> said her son `` went through all kinds of tests'' before he was diagnosed as hyperactive and given Ritalin at age 7. She said she attended sessions for parents with hyperactive children, watched her son's diet and diverted his energies into activities like hockey and bicycling. After four years, <PERSON> Ouillette </PERSON> was weaned from the drug. `` We had taught him to learn self-discipline and self-control,'' she said. White said the effect Ritalin had on his client remains a mystery, but he believes that reliance on the drug, instead of testing and therapy, played a role in the tragedy. `` The whole affair was a lost opportunity to spot a potential problem,'' he said. `` As a result, we've got one boy in prison and another boy dead.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 4</NOTE>
