<FIRST>a a AM-RIsforRitalinII Adv05-2Takes   03-31 1244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-R Is for Ritalin II, Adv 05-2 Takes,1275</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, April 5, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`R' Is for Ritalin</HEAD>
<HEAD>Part II: Sometimes Misused, Ritalin Is Fixture in Schools</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto, LaserLogo</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 One hyperactive student is greatly helped by Ritalin, so the teacher encourages the parents of others to try it _ and they tell other parents about the happy results. Ritalin's success many have led to its excess: some fear it's now overused The second story in a three-day series, ` R' is for Ritalin, looks at the increased role of a prescribed drug in the nation's schools.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<HEAD>and</HEAD>
<HEAD>SCOTT McCARTNEY</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Something new is tucked amid the workbooks, pencils and sandwiches in an increasing number of school backpacks each day. It is a pill, no bigger than button candy, prescribed to help youngsters get through their multiplication tables, spelling tests and geography lessons. The pill is Ritalin, a stimulant that can assist hyperactive children in concentrating, completing their work and controlling frenzied outbursts that turn classrooms to chaos. Some parents describe Ritalin as a godsend. `` It was like the difference between day and night,'' said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, mother whose daughter, 11, and son, 8, take the drug. `` The first day <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> took Ritalin was the first time she was able to read something and understand it. That night she told me and started crying. `` I cried, too.'' But Ritalin's success may be leading to its excess. As many as 1 million children may take the drug, and happy endings like the <ORGANIZATION> Andersons </ORGANIZATION>' are encouraging more doctors to prescribe it, sometimes with less triumphant results. Many doctors say superficial diagnosis and limited follow-up have led to the medicating of the children who do n't need it, or who need additional counseling to learn how to tame the confusion inside their minds. `` I know of several communities and school districts where people are excessively prescribing medication for children without adequately evaluating them,'' said <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Barkely </PERSON>, director of psychology at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Barkely </PERSON> said these communities to the <LOCATION> west </LOCATION> and north of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> `` may be seeing the children once a year and renewing the prescription by telephone.'' The five states with the highest per-capita consumption of Ritalin _ <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> _ have begun investigating its use. <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> officials alarmed by high Ritalin use in suburban <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> found school personnel were urging Ritalin treatment on parents. `` We looked at what was driving the marketplace and wound up with the conclusion that it was the school systems,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Watry </PERSON>, executive director of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Composite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiners </ORGANIZATION>. `` Parents were calling us with a lot of anecdotal information about how their arms were twisted to take the medication.'' <PERSON> LaVarne </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, a suburban <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> mother, believes Ritalin is used as a chemical billy club to subdue problem students. She has filed suit against the doctor and school officials who encouraged her to medicate her son. `` It's almost like someone said we've got a pill to give a child who wo n't do what you want him to do,'' she said. When <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, had trouble in first-grade at <LOCATION> Hingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, she sought medical help on the school's advice. Her pediatrian prescribed Ritalin. But <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> did not improve and, according to his mother, suffered from insomnia, depression and a loss of appetite. Mrs. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> finally took <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> to a neurologist who found the boy's problems were due to a hemiparesis, a limited brain injury not treatable by Ritalin The Marshalls are suing the pediatrician. `` He simply prescribed Ritalin,'' she said. `` We were not given a diagnosis.'' Parents like Mrs. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> claim Ritalin carries harsh side effects, from facial tics and lost appetite to depression and suicide. Their anxieties are fed by the <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> _ a group, supported by the <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientology </ORGANIZATION>, that opposes psychiatric treatment and is conducting a nationwide media campaign against Ritalin. Doctors and government regulators dismiss most charges against <PERSON> Ritalin </PERSON> as exaggerated and unsubstantiated, citing some 500 research papers that mostly agree side effects are temporary and minimal. Manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Ciba-Geigy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and known generically as methylphenidate, Ritalin is one in a small group of drugs used to treat childhood behavioral disorders and narcolepsy. As a Class II drug, it is listed, along with amphetamines, morphine and the painkiller Demerol, as a drug with legitimate use but high potential for abuse. Prescribing drugs for problem children is not new. The Roman physican <PERSON> Galen </PERSON> suggested opium for overactive children in the first century. Research in the 1930s indicated that treating hyperactive children with stimulants, usually amphetamines, helped calm them. Ritalin was developed in 1955 as an alternative to amphetamines. What has changed in the last decade is the awareness _ some say overawareness _ of the malady that Ritalin is used to treat. Known variously over years as hyperactivity, hyperkinesis and minimal brain disfunction, the syndrome is now called attention deficit disorder, a catch-all of symptoms ranging from wild, destructive behavior to an inability to concentrate or, in educational jargon, `` stay on task.'' Researchers say 3 to 10 percent of the nation's 45 million schoolchildren exhibit some symptoms of ADD. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s diagnostic bible lists ADD symptoms such as fidgeting, difficulty awaiting turns at games, blurting out answers before being called on, excessive talking and a penchant for losing things. While many parents would recognize some of these noisome habits in their children, ADD parents say it is the intensity of the behavior that separates theirs from normal children. `` It's the constantness of it,'' said <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Conner </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Newbury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, mother who publishes a newsletter for ADD families. `` You are trapped in it. You ca n't take these children anywhere, you ca n't get babysitters to stay with them. It is so emotionally tough to get through this day by day.'' ADD is the single most researched area of child psychology. Some 600 research papers on the subject were published last year. ADD seminars are commonly held around the country for doctors, educators and parents. Regional diagnostic clinics have sprung up, often near research centers in states with high Ritalin use. As a result, more and more children are being diagnosed with ADD and treated with medication. Critics note with alarm that Ritalin production has doubled since 1983. But the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, which sets production levels, says that statistic sheds little light on how many people take a drug. A better gauge is number of prescriptions. An <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> report shows 2.2 million prescriptions for Ritalin and related drugs were filled and refilled in 1986. The figure does not show the number of people using the drug, but it does indicate an increase in use _ the number is 14 percent higher than in 1983. `` That's unusual,'' said <PERSON> Carlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Baum </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> psychologist. `` The average annual increase in prescriptions for most drugs is 1 percent.'' No one is certain how many of the nation's children get a daily dose of Ritalin. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Safer </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> child psychiatrist who has studied surveys at various school districts, believes 600,000 to 800,000 schoolchildren receive stimulant medication, mostly Ritalin. `` It's been going up steadily,'' said Safer, `` and I do n't see it going down.''
</TEXT>
