<TEXT>
 In 1971, 1.1 percent of <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> school students were taking Ritalin, <PERSON> Safer </PERSON> said. By 1983, the number was up to 3.5 percent. `` The increase is a multiple of factors: parent-teacher satisfaction, the ease of treatment and its relative success,'' he said. Most Maryland school districts recommend parents seek medical help only after teachers, counselors and administrators have met to discuss a problem student. `` We do n't prescribe Ritalin,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubel </PERSON>, superintendent of the <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>. `` All we do is refer children to medical help, the same as we would if a child had problems seeing a blackboard. We would tell the parents and they would have the child's eyes examined.'' Yet when <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> officials, threatened with a lawsuit, reviewed their policy late last year, they found such a measured response was not always the case. `` I am convinced that we probably do have some people out there who sidestep some of the procedures and say ` You have to get that child on Ritalin,''' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Farley </PERSON>, an assistant county attorney. In <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Watry </PERSON>, the director of the medical examiners' board, tells of one school counselor who would `` pressure parents on a mass scale to use Ritalin.'' `` He told parents he was playing the percentages because it had helped with so many cases,'' said <PERSON> Watry </PERSON>. Late last year a special study group for the <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> recommended school personnel be warned against `` pressuring'' parents to seek medication and leave diagnosis and treatment to medical professionals. But often these professionals are not doing a complete job. The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends extensive testing and discussion among doctors, parents and educators before prescribing medication. Guidelines also stress that medication is only part of the solution. Counseling, therapy, tutoring, even special classes for parents are recommended. `` Almost everybody in the field will say you have to do more than give the pill,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Satterfield </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles-area </LOCATION> psychiatrist whose research found hyperactive children responded dramatically better to a combination of therapy and Ritalin. `` We've heard about pediatricians who have said, ` Here's six months of prescription, come back when it runs out,''' he said. `` That gives a message to parents that here's this magic pill, you do n't need any other treatment.'' But some question if many of those getting treatment need it. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, a psychologist and director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, believes doctors choose medication when counseling and different parenting might be enough. `` We have created a society that relies on medication to solve our problems,'' he said. `` The first thing you go to when you have a problem is some kind of pill.''
