<FIRST>a a AM-RitalinandTom Adv05   03-31 0967</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ritalin and Tom, Adv 05,0995</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, April 5, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Ritalin Prescribed for ``Attention Deficit''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-R Is for Ritalin II</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Each weekday morning our 7-year-old son <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> starts breakfast with a tiny white tablet he calls his `` daydream pill.'' The pill has become part of our daily routine. There was a time when my wife and I, people who think twice before taking aspirin, would have been incredulous had you told us we'd be giving our child a behavior-modifying drug. As <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> grew into an active toddler, he gave no indication anything was amiss; we were sure he was a superstar. With blond curls and a sturdy well-coordinated body, he was quick and good at everything: an early walker and talker, a cheerful elf full of eager questions. But by the time <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> was ready for kindergarten, we were concerned. He could n't seem to keep his mind on a task. He did n't like to play alone, and he did n't stay with an activity for more than a few minutes We hoped it was just immaturity. Perhaps we had spoiled him? With his quick mind and pleasing personality, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> drifted through kindergarten. We wondered why he was n't picking up academic skills as quickly as we'd anticipated, but his school reports were generally good and he was having a good year with soccer and T-ball. Everything changed in first grade. He was one of 30 classmates, and most of the school day required independent seatwork. We realized something was very wrong when <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> began collapsing into tantrums of free-floating rage and frustration after school. We were completely taken aback, especially because we had high confidence in his small, caring school. We were mystified by our little soccer player's rage. At what? Was it the oversized class? The school principal assured us that, although the class was large, the children were doing fine. We spoke to psychologist friends about whether some deep-seated anxiety could be surfacing. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> himself was unable to give us any clues until one night in the midst of an emotional collapse, he said, over and over, `` I'm dumb. Fortunately for us all, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON>'s class took a group intelligence test about this time. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON>'s score was so high in comparison with his performance that the principal called us in. She wanted to do further testing and mentioned `` attention deficit,'' a term that seemed to fit the child we knew. The principal also mentioned Ritalin, saying she had seen dramatic changes in kids like <PERSON> Tom </PERSON>. We were appalled by the suggestion we give our boy a drug, skeptical that this was the proper way to approach a learning problem. Instead, we tried a highly publicized diet and spent an agonizing month keeping <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> from many of his favorite foods, ones with cyclamates and additives. The stress of the diet increased <PERSON> Tom </PERSON>'s rage and frustration. We next urged the school to institute behavioral techniques, such as rewarding <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> for even brief periods of concentration. These helped, but only moderately, and we started to reconsider. After reading all the research we could find, and considering the side effects -LRB- such as the possibility <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> would be one-quarter inch shorter as an adult -RRB-, we concluded the risks of trying Ritalin were minimal. A factor in our decision was our own dependence on our morning cups of coffee, which help us get going and stay focused. Were we depriving <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> of the equivalent of a morning cup of coffee? The pediatrician said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> might temporarily lose his appetite or have trouble sleeping. None of this happened, and <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> was surpringly amenable to taking the tiny pill. Indeed, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> was the first to let us know it was making some difference. He started calling it his `` daydream pill,'' saying it helped him control the daydreams that distracted him in class. His teacher soon reported his behavior was improving, and we saw this reflected in his school work. Still, we could n't be certain it was n't just a placebo effect on <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> and the teacher. This year, with a new teacher who shared our lingering reservations, we withheld the Ritalin for a couple of weeks. Simultaneously, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> and his teacher reported he could n't concentrate and urged us to return to the pill With the increased demands of second grade, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> has begun taking an additional 5 milligrams at lunch. Occasionally, when he's having trouble staying with his homework, he'll say, `` Maybe I should take a pill.'' Last week we filled yet another prescription at the pharmacy where we are now recognized as regulars. Last month, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> proudly brought home a report card with B's in math and English and A's _ his first ever _ in reading and spelling. In categories such as deportment, handwriting and follows directions, which last year produced a string of F's for failure and N's for non-satisfactory, there were 2 N's and 13 S's _ for satisfactory. Is Ritalin a panacea? No. Even with the pill, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON>'s attention deficit still requires the guidance of a skillful teacher. Are we comfortable about him taking medicine? Yes and no. We like the results but are uncomfortable treating a symptom, the cause of which no one knows. We are especially uncomfortable that the psychologists and doctors seem unconcerned why <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> has trouble paying attention. Will we keep giving him the pill? Yes, at least while <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> thinks it's helpful. We'll also keep trying to find a deeper understanding of what's involved. As <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> says, `` It's not perfect, but it works, some.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Strat </PERSON> <PERSON> Douthat </PERSON> is the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> regional reporter, based in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. His wife, attorney <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Falk </PERSON>, helped write this article about their son, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
