<HEAD>Greece Follows Dukakis Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MYTILENE, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' cousins in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> like to tell how his father ran away from his home on the Turkish mainland to a merchant uncle who lived on the <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> island of <LOCATION> Mytilene </LOCATION>, after being forbidden to leave for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. A telegram was sent home saying that young <PERSON> Panos </PERSON> was safe. `` And the answer came, ` Tie him up in a bundle if necessary and send him back,''' said <PERSON> Elly </PERSON> <PERSON> Petridou </PERSON>, a retired bank employee who still lives on the island. `` But my grandfather _ <PERSON> Panos </PERSON>' uncle _ knew the future lay in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and did n't obey,'' she said. `` Instead, he found <PERSON> Panos </PERSON> an English teacher and later on paid his fare from <LOCATION> Mytilene </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. ... And eventually his parents followed him there.'' That was early in this century. Today, at least a few `` Mike Dukakis-President'' stickers are showing up as far away from <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> as this northern <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> island where his father lived, as Greek interest grows in the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor's campaign for the White House. Greek television newscasts lead off with coverage of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> primaries, and <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> newspapers run front-page stories detailing <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' progress. Politicians and analysts discuss the 54-year-old Democrat's lack of experience in foreign affairs. And they study his campaign speeches for clues to what might be future American policy. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, in interviews with <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> media, stresses his Greek heritage. But he avoids comment on eastern <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> disputes such as the Greek-Turkish disagreement over <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> oil rights and the divided island of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. A mix of pride and caution marks the mood among the half-dozen cousins and their families who make up the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> clan in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. `` We all think <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> is an exceptional person and we're convinced he'll win the Democratic nomination. But that's still a long way from getting to the White House,'' <PERSON> Patra </PERSON> <PERSON> Zourelli </PERSON>, a second cousin who lives on <LOCATION> Mytilene </LOCATION> _ also known as <ORGANIZATION> Lesbos </ORGANIZATION> _ said in an interview. From a political standpoint in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, `` I can tell you it's an advantage to be an immigrant's son,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was recently quoted as telling the <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> daily <PERSON> Vrathyni </PERSON>. `` The minorities see in me their children's opportunity to get ahead.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' father, <PERSON> Panos </PERSON>, became a respected family doctor in <LOCATION> Brookline </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. His mother, <PERSON> Euterpe </PERSON>, now 83 and campaigning actively for her son, was one of the first Greek-American women to qualify as a teacher. `` <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is probably unique in that his parents made it to the professional classes. ... Usually it's the second generation which makes that jump,'' <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitroeff </PERSON>, a historian who teaches at <ORGANIZATION> Queens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said in a telephone interview. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' father was the youngest of four brothers who left <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> as teen-agers in the early 1900s. It was a time when Greeks flocked to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, working in textile factories, flower stalls and shoeshine parlors to escape dire poverty at home. <PERSON> Mytilene </PERSON>, lying close to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and covered with millions of olive trees, boasts a literary tradition that began in the 7th century B.C. with <PERSON> Sappho </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s first woman poet. Another lyric poet from the island, <PERSON> Odysseus </PERSON> <PERSON> Elytis </PERSON>, won the Nobel Prize for literature in 1979. The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> family came from <LOCATION> Pelopi </LOCATION>, a cluster of stone houses reached by a dirt road winding up <PERSON> Mytilene </PERSON>'s highest mountain and still considered one of the poorest villages on the island. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' grandfather moved away in the 1880s to make a better life on the nearby coast of <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, where Greeks prospered as store-owners and merchants. `` <PERSON> Mike </PERSON>'s grandfather and mine were cousins who both left the village of <LOCATION> Pelopi </LOCATION> and settled in <LOCATION> Edremit </LOCATION> on the Turkish side. His grandfather ran a general store and mine ran a bakery,'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Grigoriou-Dukakis </PERSON>, 76, a retired agronomist, said in an interview. The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> property at the top of the village was sold in 1933 and <PERSON> Yiannis </PERSON> <PERSON> Manolis </PERSON>, the villager who bought it, keeps the yellowed sale contract in his pocket. `` I want to stay around long enough to welcome <PERSON> Michalis </PERSON> back here as president,'' said <PERSON> Manolis </PERSON>, 81, who lives in a two-story house he built on the ruins of the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> home. There are no records surviving to clarify whether <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' father was born on <LOCATION> Mytilene </LOCATION> _ then ruled by <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> _ or in <LOCATION> Edremit </LOCATION> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' mother was born in the northern city of <LOCATION> Larissa </LOCATION>, then a sleepy farm town but now a booming center for the <LOCATION> Thessaly </LOCATION> region. `` Cousin Euterpe is a tough lady who'd be called a feminist if she were young now. ... Her family all left for the <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the early 1900s after losing their land to the Turks,'' said <PERSON> Nikos </PERSON> <PERSON> Milingos </PERSON>, a third cousin who runs a farm chemicals business. Like most of the relatives, the <PERSON> Milingos </PERSON> family first met <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> when he came to <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> in 1976 during his first term as governor. Now they visit Massachussetts regularly. `` We found him very warm and welcoming, but he's certainly a man of principle,'' said <PERSON> Olympia </PERSON> <PERSON> Milingos </PERSON>. `` When we went for dinner at their home in the days of energy-saving, <PERSON> Euterpe </PERSON> told us to take sweaters because the heating would be low _ and it was.'' The <PERSON> Greek-American </PERSON> community in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, numbering between 1 million and 3 million by various estimates, is pouring in funds to back its `` patrida'' -LRB- homeland -RRB- candidate. According to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aides, around 25 percent of his first $ 15 million in campaign funds came from Greek-Americans. Apart from the wish to claim a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president of <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> descent, many in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> say that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' election would repair the damage to their self-image caused by former Vice President <PERSON> Spiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Spiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON> was an embarrassment to <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and the migrant tradition. It's a bad memory for us that we'd like to erase through <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>,'' said former Culture Minister <PERSON> Dimitris </PERSON> <PERSON> Nianias </PERSON>, a member of parliament for Mytilene.
