<FIRST>s a BC-JamesEarlRay Adv03   03-31 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-James Earl Ray, Adv 03,0646</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Inmate No. 65477 Says, `I Didn't Kill Anybody'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Killing King</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PETROS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> has spent most of his `` free time'' at <LOCATION> Brushy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> State Prison plotting ways to get out, either by going over the wall or into a courtroom. So far, he's been more successful at breaking out. In 1977, inmate No. 65477 managed to scale the wall and remain free for three days before being apprehended in the rugged hills near the prison. A couple of years earlier, he escaped from his cell through an air vent only to be captured inside the prison walls a few hours later. But the 60-year-old <PERSON> Alton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, native has n't been able to get back into court since March 10, 1969, the day he pleaded guilty to killing the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. And although he is doggedly determined to win a day in court, <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> apparently has become more resigned to prison life than he was in his escape-artist days, which included a 1967 breakout from the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penitentiary </LOCATION>, where he was serving 20 years for armed robbery `` He's a good inmate,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Worthington </PERSON>, an officer at <LOCATION> Brushy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION>, a maximum security prison 40 miles west of <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>. `` He does good time and does n't cause us any trouble _ not of late, anyway.'' <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> works in the prison laundry, earning $ 1 a day. He shares an 11-by-8-foot cell with another inmate and spends most of his weekends in the prison law library. `` I work five days a week, from 7 a.m. to 3 o'clock in the afternoon,'' he said in a recent interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` We get an hour a day for exercise in the yard through the week and two hours on Saturdays and Sundays.'' He maintained, as he has ever since pleading guilty, that he did n't kill King and does n't know who did. He said he pleaded guilty only because he was pressured into it. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> speaks in a quiet but determined voice when discussing his legal problems. Although he has spent nearly half of his life behind bars he still looks fit: his hair is dark, with white sideburns, his dark blue eyes are alert and his body is trim in a blue denim uniform. `` It's always a good idea to keep fit in prison,'' he said, rubbing a scar on his left cheek, the result of an attack by three black inmates in 1980. Two of his attackers got 60-year sentences for attempted murder, and the third was given 20 years. `` I got careless for a moment,'' he said, recalling the assault. `` Like a fool I went into the law library when there were no guards present. But, then I was lucky, too; they stabbed me in the arm, face and chest but never hit an artery.'' <PERSON> Worthington </PERSON> describes <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> as a quiet loner who usually keeps to himself when he goes out to the prison yard for exercise with other prisoners. Although married in 1983 to a <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> artist who was teaching art appreciation to inmates, <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> has n't had a visitor since last fall. To pass the time, he reads and paints _ mostly watercolor landscapes from memory. He recently helped prepare a second edition of his autobiography, which he said he wrote to tell his side of the story about the King assassination. As for his 99-year sentence, he said, `` I really do n't think I should have had to spend all this time in prison. I did n't kill anybody.''
</TEXT>
