<HEAD>Oil Prices Recover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A positive new report on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stocks of refined oil products has helped lift oil prices out of a temporary slump. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, contracts for May delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, settled Wednesday at $ 17.08 per 42-gallon barrel, up 10 cents from Tuesday's close. Among refined products, the April contract for wholesale heating oil jumped 0.45 cent a gallon to 48.60 cents. Unleaded gasoline for April rose by 0.39 cent a gallon to 48.65 cents. Trading on the exchange was described as light, muted by the approach of the Easter holiday weekend. The advance came on the heels of a modest decline on Tuesday _ which had broken a four-day rally as many investors sold futures contracts and took profits. The recent strength stems from hopes that the pricing committee of the 13-nation <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> will achieve an agreement to prop up prices, analysts say. The pricing panel is due to meet in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, starting April 9. Prices have risen in nine of the last 12 trading sessions on the <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Traders said prices got an additional boost in Wednesday's session from the latest weekly report on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil stocks compiled by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, an industry group based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> The API statistics, released after the market closed on Tuesday, showed substantial drawdowns in stocks of both gasoline and heating oil in the week ended March 25 compared with the previous week. The decrease in product inventories was seen as indicating a continued robust demand, analysts said. `` We had a fairly rational reaction here'' to the API figures, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, an oil futures analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>.
