<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Economists shrugged off an 0.8 percent decline in orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories for manufactured goods during February, even though it represented the second consecutive monthly decline. The financial markets put in a mixed performance Wednesday. On Wall Street, the stock market faltered but the dollar showed signs of steadying in foreign exchange, where the British pound stole center stage. Bond prices were little changed. Orders for durable and non-durable goods dropped to a seasonally adjusted $ 210.86 billion last month following a 0.6 percent decline in January, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. The February setback was the biggest since a 1.4 percent drop last August and marked the first time that factory orders have fallen for two consecutive months since the summer of 1986. Economists said the declines indicated that businesses cut back on orders in the early part of the year to help trim high levels of unsold goods that had built up in the final quarter of 1987. While this process will dampen growth, economists said it appeared that the cutbacks had been moderate and would set the stage for faster growth in the months ahead. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 10 points in the early going, closed with a 20.22-point loss at 1,978.12. Investors were reluctant to take large positions ahead of the upcoming three-day Easter weekend. The dollar showed signs of steadying after a wave of tumbles, but it was the pound that posted far greater gains, rising in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to $ 1.8780 from $ 1.86425. In the past seven years, the pound has hit a low of $ 1.0470, in February 1985, and a high of $ 2.4525 in November 1980. In jumping to its highest levels in two years, the British currency has been boosted by a strong economy, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s relatively high interest rates and Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s unrelenting grip on inflation Bond prices eased slightly. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s bellwether 30-year issue fell 7-32 point, or about $ 2.50 per $ 1,000 in face value, to yield 8.77 percent. Oil prices rebounded from a temporary setback. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, contracts for May delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, settled at $ 17.08 per 42-gallon barrel, up 10 cents from Tuesday's close.
</TEXT>
