<HEAD>American Stores Stock Jumps; Lucky `Pac-Man' Bid Rumored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Lucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> may turn the tables on rival grocer <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to thwart the pursuer's $ 1.74 billion buyout offer, analysts say. Talk of the rarely used `` Pac-Man defense'' pushed <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> stock up $ 2.75 to $ 59.75 a share on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday, while Lucky lost $ 1.50 a share to close at $ 48.37 -LCB-. Earlier this week <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> launched a $ 45-a-share tender offer for Lucky. But the <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City-based </LOCATION> supermarket giant later said it was prepared to boost the offer to $ 50 a share, or $ 1.93 billion, if Lucky's management supported the acquisition. Lucky has declined to comment on the offers, but analysts said rumors focused on whether Lucky might be considering making its own bid for <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>. A combination of the two companies would rival <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> as the nation's largest supermarket operation. <ORGANIZATION> Lucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Lissa </PERSON> <PERSON> Perlman </PERSON> said the company `` does n't comment on rumors.'' The only comment Lucky has made is that its board is studying <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>' two proposals. `` There has been conjecture all along about what options Lucky might have,'' said <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziegler </PERSON>, an analyst with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Sutro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ziegler </PERSON> noted that Lucky, which operates in the lucrative <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> market, would have to take on a huge amount of debt to acquire <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts specualted Lucky might be trying to put <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> stock `` in play'' on Wall Street to take the spotlight off itself. The rumors came a day after <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> Chairman L.S. <PERSON> Skaggs </PERSON> complained of `` various reports'' that Lucky might be considering a `` defensive acquisition'' of another company to make itself financial unattractive. In a letter Tuesday to <ORGANIZATION> Lucky </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors, <PERSON> Skaggs </PERSON> cautioned against a maneuver that could interfere with his company's takeover plans and warned that any attempt to `` frustrate the choice given to your shareholders through a defensive acquisition'' would affect American's willingness to increase its tender offer to $ 50 a share. <PERSON> Skaggs </PERSON> reiterated that <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> would consider divesting stores if it acquired Lucky, in order to mitigate any antitrust concerns that might exist. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> is the nation's third largest grocery retailer with 1,700 stores and annual sales of $ 15 billion. Lucky is the sixth largest with 480 stores and sales of $ 7 billion. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> filed a lawsuit last week in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> charging Lucky and its executives with breaching their fiduciary duties by `` following a course of conduct directed toward entrenching themselves in control of Lucky Stores.'' As part of defensive measures taken over a year ago to stave off corporate raider <PERSON> Asher </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>, Lucky voted senior management lucrative `` golden parachute'' contracts and announced a restructuring plan that included changing the company's state of incorporation from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and a buy-back of 27 percent of its outstanding shares. The company has noted that its bylaws also contain an anti-takeover provision limiting the voting power of any shareholder who acquires more than 10 percent of Lucky's stock.
