<HEAD>Lotus Announces Enhanced Data Base Link</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has announced its Blueprint tool kit, an upgraded product by <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to give its computer users easy access to a wide range of non-Lotus data bases. `` I tend to view this as a building block kind of an announcement,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Readerman </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` They are trying to build a better connection between third-party data bases and their own PC software tools.'' `` It fits in their long-term strategy,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Dillon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Read </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. Inc. in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> `` It's a positive step for the future.'' Analysts say Blueprint is part of <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION>' strategy to expand applications for its software in a period of increased competition from spreadsheet manufacturers, such as <ORGANIZATION> Borland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Scotts </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> stock rebounded slightly following Wednesday's The stock had tumbled nearly $ 7 a share since last week after the Cambridge-based firm announced plans to delay release of the Lotus 1-2-3 Release 3 spreadsheet software until the fourth quarter. The delay caused analysts to cut 1988 per-share earnings estimates from about $ 1.95 to about $ 1.50. <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> stock closed up 50 cents a share to $ 22.50 in over-the-counter trading Wednesday. The Blueprint kit, scheduled to be released late this year, will aid data base manufacturers in creating drives that will greatly streamline the process of accessing software not specially designed for <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> systems, said <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kosheff </PERSON>. The drives will be sold to consumers by data base firms including <ORGANIZATION> Oracle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Belmont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, which has formally announced plans to place a Blueprint drive in its upcoming product line. Other firms expressing interest in Blueprint include <ORGANIZATION> Microrim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> PC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Synex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> statement. <PERSON> Kosheff </PERSON> said the drive will allow <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> system users to hit one key to connect with various data bases, rather than the many steps now required. Data obtained through Blueprint drives will be compatible with existing and planned <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> software, including spreadsheets and graphics, she said. <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenough </PERSON> said Blueprint is an enhancement of Application Connection, a Lotus-created data base connection drive introduced in 1986. The Blueprint drives will be available for use on all sizes of Lotus computer systems, said <PERSON> Greenough </PERSON>.
