<HEAD>Dollar Down Sharply Against Yen; Stocks Also Close Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar dropped sharply against the yen today while stock prices fell slightly after three days of substantial gains. After opening lower at 125.15 yen, the dollar dropped further and closed at 124.50 yen, the day's low, down 0.93 yen from Wednesday's close of 125.43 yen. The <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> appeared to step into the market to support the dollar late in the morning and at the outset of the afternoon session, traders said. `` Profit-taking dollar selling brought the dollar down, but besides that there was no notable movement in the market,'' said <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Iiya </PERSON> of the Bank of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. The market still is anticipating a weaker dollar, he said. Another trader said market participants were hesitant about trading while awaiting the scheduled release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic data on Friday. In addition, he said, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> markets will close for a holiday Friday and will not provide any lead for <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> after the data is released. Figures to be released Friday include <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment in March and construction expenditures in February. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, which rose 366.89 points Wednesday to a post-crash high, sliped 59.81 points, or 0.2 percent, closing at 26,260.26 points. `` The market has come to a rest as investors stepped to the sidelines, following the three days of sharp gains,'' said <PERSON> Yoshio </PERSON> <PERSON> Shimoyama </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. The Nikkei average gained more than 1,000 points in the three days. The dollar's fall did not affect the market, which kept a positive mood about prospects for the new fiscal year beginning Friday, he said. Investors also were cautious while awaiting the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic data, traders said. The volume of the first section was estimated at 1.4 billion shares, down from 1.8 billion shares Wednesday.
