picks up 4th graf pvs bg'ng, News releases ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mythology failed to record who supplied the wax and feathers for <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION>' wings 3,500 years ago. That omission is not being repeated in 1988. Thanks to the miracle of modern public relations, corporate backers are getting a share of the acclaim in the current attempt to recreate the mythical flight of <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> from the Greek island of <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION>. A high-tech human-powered aircraft made a successful series of test flights today in <LOCATION> Iraklion </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION>, in preparation for a world-record distance attempt that also will recreate the ancient Daedalus myth. The 68-pound ultralight <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> 88 completed six flights lasting less than three minutes each in calm dawn weather above a <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> air force base adjoining <LOCATION> Iraklion </LOCATION> airport. Five athlete pilots took turns to pedal the shimmering pink-and-silver plane at speeds of around 14 mph, flying about 15 feet above the tarmac. News releases, an innovation unknown in ancient <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, have let it be known to the world that <ORGANIZATION> Arrow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Downers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, supplied gearboxes for the <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> aircraft. <ORGANIZATION> Poly-Flex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Walworth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, donated plastic wheels. Polar-Electro KY of <LOCATION> Kempele </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, contributed heart rate monitors. <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> sponsored the prototype <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION> aircraft The design and construction of the Daedalus is mainly the work of students, faculty, staff and recent alumni of <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Langford </PERSON>, the program manager, is on leave from the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analyses </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>. The attraction of the Daedalus Project for a corporate sponsor is obvious. It brings together high technology, teamwork, imagination and daring. `` It's been a super project. It's a natural fit for us,'' said <PERSON> Clare </PERSON> <PERSON> Hertel </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for San Francisco-based <ORGANIZATION> Shaklee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Shaklee </ORGANIZATION> sponsors the <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> crew and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is the financial sponsor of the aircraft itself The two companies are treating the project as part of their research-and-development efforts. <ORGANIZATION> Shaklee </ORGANIZATION> says the energy drink it is developing for the <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> pilots might lead to a beverage for endurance athletes that could be sold commercially. In cooperation with <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Ethan </PERSON> <PERSON> Nadel </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Shaklee </ORGANIZATION> has developed a drink containing easily digestible carbohydrates for quick energy. `` If they -LRB- pilots -RRB- run out of energy or feel fatigued, no matter how wonderful the plane is, the engine might run out,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittam </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Shaklee </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for science and technology. <PERSON> Whittam </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Shaklee </ORGANIZATION> has recently improved the flavor of its experimental beverage, but wo n't describe the flavor. `` It wo n't be a fruit punch, I can tell you that,'' <PERSON> Whittam </PERSON> said. `` It's our secret weapon.'' <ORGANIZATION> Shaklee </ORGANIZATION>, a company with an eye for the dramatic, has also sponsored the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ski Team, the around-the-world flight of the Voyager and <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillette </PERSON>'s rowboat trip from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>. The engine of the Daedalus is a human being, so the jet engine builders at <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pratt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Whitney </LOCATION> do n't have much to learn from it. But the air conditioner makers at Carrier could gain insights into how to keep air flowing smoothly over slowly turning blades, said <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyerand </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chief scientist of the <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, Conn.-based company. Better understanding of air flows could also help in streamlining the exterior frame of Otis elevators. It could even help the company develop concepts for a solar-powered aircraft that would hover at 100,000 feet and serve as a communications relay station for communications, <PERSON> Meyerand </PERSON> said. The high-altitude aircraft would presumably have military uses. <PERSON> Meyerand </PERSON> said it would be developed only if it received government support. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> says it has contributed $ 430,000 to the Daedalus Project, plus eng