<HEAD>MCI Looking for Positive Cash Flow by Early 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> expects that by early 1989 the company will achieve a positive cash flow for the first time in its 20-year history, a company spokesman confirmed Thursday. Once that goal is achieved, <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> plans to reduce its debt and later begin buying back the 16 percent stake in the company held by <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said spokesman <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodrich </PERSON>. The company, the nation's second-largest long-distance carrier, wants to reduce its debt-to-equity ratio from 67 percent to around 40 percent over the next four years, <PERSON> Goodrich </PERSON> said. `` At that point, we would look at the market and see if the next step is to buy back the <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> stock,'' he said. `` We're talking three to four years before we would consider that and then we'd have to consider market conditions.'' <PERSON> Goodrich </PERSON> confirmed a report in Thursday's editions of The Wall Street Journal, in which <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> officials outlined the company's future plans Financial pressures on the company have eased now that it has finished building its digital network. It also has added 800 service, operator services and direct-dial service virtually worldwide to match the offerings of industry leader <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> acquired <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s share of <ORGANIZATION> Satellite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 in exchange for 47 million shares of <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> stock Under the agreement, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> can not acquire more than 30 percent of <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION>'s stock without the company's approval. With a stock repurchase, <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> could assure its independence and increase its earnings per share, <PERSON> Goodrich </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> ended 1987 with earnings of $ 88 million, or 31 cents per share, on revenues of $ 3.94 billion. The company's capital and other expenses exceeded its cash flow by $ 200 million last year. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> had no comment on <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION>'s stock-repurchase plans. A company achieves positive cash flow when its net profit plus depreciation is greater than its expenditures on dividends and investment in plant and equipment. <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> does not pay dividends.
</TEXT>
