<NOTE>EDs: New material, editing thruout; also running on general news
wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators broke a longstanding deadlock today and moved to place sharp import curbs on <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and a subsidiary for selling submarine-silencing equipment to the Soviets. Approval of the <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> provision as part of a sweeping trade bill came despite <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration opposition and a major lobbying campaign by the Japanese electronics manufacturer. On the eve of the action, several <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> officials warned lawmakers that a stringent punishment for <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> could precipitate a presidential veto of the 1,000-page trade bill. They said the president should have more flexibility in determining national security and trade relations with other countries. `` I was elected as a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senator to represent the State of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and not <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> and not <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and not the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and not <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>,'' declared Sen. <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Garn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, in urging lawmakers to defy administration opposition. He said he was embarrassed that a Republican administration would fight the sanctions, adding, `` The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has been kicked in the shins and instead of saying ouch they have chosen to surrender. The provision was accepted by a subcommittee of a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee working on a compromise version of the trade bill. It would ban for three years <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government procurement of <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> products. The company has massive sales within the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of televisions, microwaves and other electronic products. It would ban import for three years of products manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the subsidiary involved with the Norwegian firm of <ORGANIZATION> Kongsberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vapenfabrikk </ORGANIZATION> in selling sophisticated computerized milling equipment to the Soviets that the administration says has greatly submarine propeller noise. There would be exemptions for national security. The measure also provides for a two to five-year ban in the future on imports of products by foreign makers that violate the so-called <ORGANIZATION> Cocom </ORGANIZATION> agreement under which western nations act to keep high-tech equipment with military uses out of communist hands. But the president could waive such action against parent companies in some cases. Lawmakers are pushing to put the finishing touches on the trade bill before starting on their spring break. `` We're going to give it our best,'' Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said Wednesday as a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee plowed through a stack of proposals but stopped short of the big decisions. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wants to have all the provisions wrapped up except a few minor loose ends before heading for its spring break at the end of the week. The committee, attempting to fashion a compromise between rival 1,000-page trade bills passed by the two houses, heard Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mo </LOCATION>., appeal to lawmakers to save the heart of his controversial trade plan The plan to force 10 percent annual reductions in unfair surpluses that other countries run with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> formed the centerpiece of <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s abandoned campaign for president. He said any final version should focus on key countries that make unfair trade practices part of a systematic trade strategy. Wholesale negotiations should be shunned in favor of working on major trade trouble spots, he said. Mandatory retaliation is needed when negotiations fail, he said. `` You have to have a stick in the closet,'' he said. But he added that flexibility is necessary in dealing with trading partners and the president should have the power to waive retaliation.
</TEXT>
