<HEAD>Trump Gives Up Tender Offer for Resorts International Stock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investor <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> gave up his $ 22-a-share tender offer for the <ORGANIZATION> Resorts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> stock he does n't own, saying he is confident a takeover bid by entertainer-businessman <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> will never be approved Control of Resorts International is now held by <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, who owns nearly all of Resorts' 572,000 Class B shares that have 100 votes each, giving him 88 percent of the company's voting power. On Wednesday, <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> revised his offer for $ 36 a share for all of the company's Class A stock and called for Resorts to sell <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> 1.2 million new Class B shares at the same price. The new stock would give <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> voting control. The company has 5.7 million Class A common shares that have one vote each. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> said late Wednesday he will return all tendered shares after his offer. The merger agreement expires at midnight tonight. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> said he will never sell his Class B stock and will not pay more than $ 22 for Class A stock. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> said Wednesday he is no longer making his offer contingent upon <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> tendering his Class B stock or terminating a five-year management contract valued at about $ 100 million for Resorts' hotel-casinos in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>. Consummation of the offer would result in <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> owning a majority of the voting power and more than 90 percent of the equity of Resorts. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> would be able to participate in <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s new offer only by converting his stock to Class A shares. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>, through his privately held investment firm, <ORGANIZATION> Griffin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, made his revised offer to Resorts' outside directors, noting he believes only those board members should vote on the proposal. `` The other directors have interests in Mr. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s competing bid,'' <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> said. Three of Resorts' six directors are nominees of <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, who is the company's chairman. Resorts referred media inquiries to <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Nusbaum </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> would continue to use his voting power to resist <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s offer and it was unlikely Resorts' outside directors would meet independently to consider the proposal <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> is offering $ 22 a share to buy the Resorts stock he does n't already own and take the company private. In mid-March, <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> countered with a bid of $ 35 a share, or $ 225 million, for all of the company's stock, but it was contingent upon <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> tendering his stock and terminating the management pact. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> has repeatedly indicated he would n't agree to either contingency. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> subsequently said he would boost his bid to $ 295 million, with Resorts' board members able to decide how to apportion the additional $ 70 million between Class A and Class B holders. The move was seen as a way to pay a higher price to <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, but the New Yorker again said he was n't interested.
</TEXT>
