<HEAD>Homeless, Rape Victims Featured in New United Way Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In new public service commercials for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Way </LOCATION>, a mugger tears a coat off the back of a homeless man, an assailant grabs an unsuspecting woman and an older man is felled at the office by a heart attack. By the end of the 30-second ads, the homeless man gets a new coat, the distraught woman dresses up to face the world again and the older man enjoys restored health on a beach. They each got help from agencies assisted by donations to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Way </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Roberta </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Voort </PERSON>, a senior vice president of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Way </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday that by showing people the `` vital link'' between their donations and good deeds, the ads may help dispell skepticism about charitable organizations. <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Wooden </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Advertising </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, the non-profit organization that oversees $ 1.1 billion a year in public service advertising, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Way </LOCATION> is the first organization to address the issues of homelessness and rape in a national advertising campaign. She said she expects `` exceptionally strong media play'' for the campaign with the media donating more than $ 70 million in free time and space this year, up from $ 40 million donated for the national <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Way </ORGANIZATION> campaign last year. The ads were created by the New York-based agency <ORGANIZATION> Lowe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marschalk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which took over responsibility for the campaign this year. The ads continue the theme `` The <L