<HEAD>Company, Two Executives Fined $604,000 For Using Foreign Steel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A company fined $ 604,000 for using foreign-made steel in hacksaws sold to the government will appeal a verdict that found it violated the Buy American Act, its attorney said Thursday. `` It is not a rational interpretation of the Buy American Act,'' said <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Facher </PERSON>, who represented Rule Industries in the case. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury on Wednesday convicted Rule Industries and two of its executives of 302 violations of the act, which calls for goods purchased by the federal government for public use be manfactured with mostly American-made parts. The number of violations corresponds with the number of invoices the company submitted during its contracts with the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in 1981 and 1982 totaling $ 1.3 million. The jury ruled the company was liable because it purchased 10-inch steel `` blanks'' from suppliers in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The blanks were milled, hardened and tempered in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Rulings in the case indicated that it would not have been a violation of the act had Gloucester-based Rule Industries purchased sheets or coils of steel from foreign suppliers and cut the blanks from them. `` The act is really being interpreted in a bizarre fashion,'' <PERSON> Facher </PERSON> said. `` It's a very complex and old piece of legislation that dates back to the Depression and has never really been definitively interpreted by a court.'' The case is believed to be the first jury trial in the enforcement of the 55-year-old act, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said. <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> had filed a civil lawsuit in 1985 against Rule Industries, a diversified manufacturer of marine and hardware products; its president, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Anastos </PERSON>, and its vice president, <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Sable </PERSON>. Each was charged with violating the act. The jury said the defendants falsely represented that domestic steel was used to fulfill four contracts with the <ORGANIZATION> GSA </ORGANIZATION>, the main contracting arm of the federal government. Rule Industries officials had said when the suit was filed the <ORGANIZATION> GSA </ORGANIZATION> was well aware of its steel-purchasing practices. During the trial, several former employees testified that <ORGANIZATION> Rule </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> executives hid the source of the steel by destroying containers shipped from overseas, blackening out foreign markings and removing shipping labels from packages. `` There were a number of very honest employees who got offended when their company lied to the government,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON>, a first assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney.
