<FIRST>r f BC-Ford-Deductibles     03-31 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ford-Deductibles,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says Ford Must Give Back $100 Deductibles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> illegally charged $ 100 deductibles to perform some automobile repairs it should have done in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> for free under the state's lemon law, a mid-level state appeals court ruled. The Appellate Division of the state's <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decided Thursday that <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> was `` unjustly enriched'' by charging <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> consumers the deductibles and must make restitution. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> State Attorney General <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> contended in court that the state's 1983 lemon law, designed to provide New Yorkers with replacement vehicles or money back if their new cars exhibit irreparable flaws, did not allow <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> to impose the deductibles. According to court papers, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> paid the cost of all repairs for its new cars during the first 12 months or 12,000 miles. But under an extended limited warranty, the automaker charged $ 100 each time it made repairs to the power train and other major components of cars with 12,000 to 18,000 miles or between one and two years old. <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> argued in court that the state's lemon law prohibits automakers from imposing a deductible for repairs on new cars during their first 18,000 miles or two years. A state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justice in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, ruled in December 1986 that the lemon law prohibits <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> from imposing the deductibles, but he did not order the automaker to provide restitution. In the 5-0 ruling by the appellate division Thursday, however, Presiding Justice <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> said he and his colleagues `` choose to exercise our discretion'' by ordering <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> to give the money back. <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> rejected arguments by <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> attorneys that <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s lemon law is unconstitutional and that it violates interstate commerce laws <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> conceded that while <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> may not have detailed records of all customers it improperly charged for repairs, `` it would not be impracticable to give purchasers during the relevant time period a general notice and a time period to come forward.'' <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> sent the matter back to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> level to devise an `` appropriate restitution procedure'' for <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> to follow. He was joined in his decision by state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justices </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kane </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Mercure </PERSON>. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Connell </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>, said the attorney general's office has no accurate total of how many New Yorkers were improperly charged the deductibles. But she said it's believed refunds could total `` in the millions of dollars.'' <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacovara </PERSON>, a Washington-based attorney who represented <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> in the case, did not immediately return a telephone call seeking comment. The ruling could be appealed to the state's highest court, the Court of Appeals.
</TEXT>
