<HEAD>Bonds Sold To Finance Kohlberg's Buyout of Jim Walter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In what is being billed as one of the largest non-government issues in history, $ 1.45 billion in bonds have been sold to help <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> pay off bank loans from its buyout of <ORGANIZATION> Jim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kohlberg </PERSON> <PERSON> Kravis </PERSON> took <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> private last year for about $ 2.4 billion, about $ 2 billion of which was financed by bank loans Since then the New York-based investment firm has been selling selected <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>'s assets to help finance the deal. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>, which has its headquarters in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, is a diversified building materials and natural resources company that operates primarily in the South and <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>. It also is one of the country's largest home builders, specializing in inexpensive, partially finished `` shell'' houses. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> had 74,000 single-family mortgages in 22 states totaling $ 1.74 billion that were packaged together to back the bond issue. `` KKR realized they had a very unusual asset in these mortgages,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoey </PERSON>, senior vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assurance </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hoey </PERSON> said the bond issue was `` totally sold out to a blue-chip list'' comprised of large pension funds, life insurance companies and banks from around the world. The mortgages were sold to a special trust and used to back the bond issue, which Financial Security guaranteed with a triple-A rating. Homeowners pay their morgtages into the trust, which has a cushion to protect against any defaults by homeowners. That cash flow will pay the interest on the bonds, which were sold in five different maturities, each carrying a different interest rate. `` The purpose was not to take weak credit and make it triple-A and take on risk, but to take complex and unusual collateral that the marketplace has difficulty understanding'' and package it to sell, <PERSON> Hoey </PERSON> said. The average buyer of a <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> home requires a low-cost mortgage and therefore is not a typical homebuyer. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> does not provide the land on which its houses are built, which cuts down on the price of the homes. In addition, the company leaves its houses as much as 30 percent incomplete, making them affordable to blue-collar, first-time homebuyers, <PERSON> Hoey </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kohlberg </PERSON> <PERSON> Kravis </PERSON> has spearheaded a number of major leveraged buyouts, including the $ 6.2 billion buyout of <ORGANIZATION> Beatrice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos </ORGANIZATION>. The company said this week that it is seeking permission to acquire up to 15 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>.
