<HEAD>Resorts Stock Falls as Trump Ends Bid, Vows to Block Griffin Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The price of <ORGANIZATION> Resorts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> stock slumped Thursday as investor <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, who holds 88 percent of the company's voting power, withdrew his bid to take the hotel-casino operator private and indicated he would block a higher, rival offer by entertainer <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>. Resorts' Class A stock fell by $ 1.62 -LCB- per share to $ 28.87 -LCB- in trading on the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s bid, which was revised Wednesday for the second time, was an attempt to make an end run around <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s repeated objections and force Resorts' outside directors to vote on the plan free of <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s influence. `` The <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> courts have consistently ruled that a corporation's outside directors are charged with the duty to conduct a fair bidding contest,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Griffin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. `` Outside directors have been authorized by the courts to take all reasonable steps, including diluting a major shareholder, in order to obtain the best deal for the public shareholders.'' However, some analysts were skeptical of whether <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> could succeed. `` Because <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s offer is conditional, they -LRB- Resorts' outside directors -RRB- have an out. They can simply refuse to consider it on grounds that it is unlikely it would be able to succeed,'' said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Isgur </PERSON>, a leisure-time industry analyst with <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Resorts' board, composed of <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> and two of his nominees plus three outside directors, is scheduled to meet Monday. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> is chairman of Resorts. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s latest proposal dropped two previous conditions _ that <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> agree to sell his stock and terminate a lucrative five-year contract to operate Resorts properties in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>. Instead, <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> imposed a new contingency _ that Resorts agree to sell him 1.2 million new shares of Class B stock, which carries 100 votes per share and would give <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> more votes that <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> owns nearly all of the company's current 572,000 Class B shares. He was offering $ 22 per share for the company's 5.7 million Class A shares, which carry only one vote per share and hence only 12 percent of the company's voting strentgh. But he said the offer was allowed to expire at 12:01 a.m. Friday and all tendered shares will be returned to their owners. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> is offering $ 36 per share for the Class A stock, and the same price for the 1.2 million new Class B shares he is seeking. Attorney <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Applebauam </PERSON>, who represents the independent directors, indicated that he feels all Resorts directors including those nominated by <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> have the right to vote on <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s merger proposal. But he said that the question of whether only outside directors should vote on the proposal to issue new Class B stock to <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> `` is a matter for further research.'' <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Nusbaum </PERSON>, reiterated that he feels the full board should take up <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s offer.
