<HEAD>Two Countries Prepare to Sign New Five-Year Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have reached substantial agreement on a new five-year pact to expand their scientific and technical cooperation, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. The new agreement, to be concluded in about three months, seeks incentives to boost the flow of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> students, researchers and scientific workers to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, said officials of both countries who declined to be named. They said more than 10 times as many Japanese are currently in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> classrooms, laboratories and factories as Americans studying or working in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The 1980 U.S.-Japanese scientific exchange agreement, extended several times since its expiration in 1985, was extended for another three months `` to allow for legal editing of the new document, and signing at a high level,'' the department said. It will be considerably more detailed than the existing pact on the two countries' scientific and technological relationship and also provide a new management structure to oversee that relationship, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. It will provide for protection of patents and other intellectual property rights while calling for the widest dissemination of information resulting from joint research, the announcement said. Both countries were concerned about the need to increase the flow of Americans to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, said the sources. They said the new agreement provides steps to be taken by both sides to make <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> more attractive for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> scientists and easier for them to go there. It envisions more funding for Japanese language study and fellowships by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, one said. The estimate that there are 10 times as many Japanese students and scientists currently in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> as Americans in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is a rough minimum estimate, because in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> it is difficult to count students of science separately from those of other subjects or even from tourists, one official said.
