<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reached an agreement Thursday with rival bidder <ORGANIZATION> Whirlpool </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, allowing it to proceed unopposed with a $ 507.6 million offer to acquire <ORGANIZATION> Roper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. GE spokesman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Jamison </PERSON> said the Connecticut-based company's offer of $ 54 per share would be extended until 5 p.m. <ORGANIZATION> Whirlpool </ORGANIZATION> simultaneously announced it was terminating its $ 50-per-share offer. The battle to acquire <PERSON> Roper </PERSON>, an appliance and lawn equipment manufacturer based in <LOCATION> Augusta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, began last November. Earlier Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Whirlpool </ORGANIZATION> said they were negotiating to resolve their dispute over the proposed acquisition. `` For <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION>, the <PERSON> Roper </PERSON> factories and <PERSON> Roper </PERSON>'s strong Sears relationship makes this an important niche acquisition that will significantly strengthen our appliance business in an increasingly competitive global market,'' said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schipke </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> senior vice president in charge of the company's appliance business. <PERSON> Roper </PERSON> had recommended Tuesday that its shareholders accept <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION>'s latest tender offer, rather than the $ 470 million bid from <ORGANIZATION> Whirlpool </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Whirlpool </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> agreed Tuesday in <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> that there would be no open market purchases of <PERSON> Roper </PERSON> stock until a judge ruled on a <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> request for a temporary restraining order. The companies said Thursday that agreement was being continued while they negotiated, and eventually the two came to an accord. <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> sought an order to prevent <ORGANIZATION> Whirlpool </ORGANIZATION> from making a `` street sweep'' of <LOCATION> Roper </LOCATION> stock through market professionals rather than from public shareholders. The reqest came in a hearing on a GE application for a preliminary injunction to block a <ORGANIZATION> Whirlpool </ORGANIZATION> acquisition of <PERSON> Roper </PERSON>. The terms of the agreement between <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Whirlpool </ORGANIZATION> allow <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> to acquire <PERSON> Roper </PERSON> and its manufacturing capacity for kitchen ranges and lawn equipment. <ORGANIZATION> Whirlpool </ORGANIZATION>, in return, will get rights to the <PERSON> Roper </PERSON> name for major appliances. GE will supply <ORGANIZATION> Whirlpool </ORGANIZATION> with Roper-brand electric and gas ranges at competitive prices for at least two years, according to a press release from the companies. The parties also agreed to other commercial relationships whereby GE would sell to <ORGANIZATION> Whirlpool </ORGANIZATION> certain industrial components and materials. Lawsuits filed by both companies will be withdrawn upon completion of <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION>'s tender offer, the companies said.
