<FIRST>u f AM-Trade 2ndLd-Writethru   03-31 0937</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0963</SECOND>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts 2 grafs after 17th graf bgng: The House ... to add
background on windfall profits. Picks up 18th graf pvs bgng: Farm
lawmakers ...</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Also moved on general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators reached tentative agreement Thursday night on a sweeping trade bill designed to open foreign markets, but only after loading it with provisions that lawmakers said could invite a veto. Repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies, tough trade sanctions against <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and millions of dollars in new subsidies designed to boost <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain exports were tentatively included. `` We're going to need a trade policy in the next couple of years and I think this is as good as anything that's going to come across the president's desk,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, worked out the details of the central agreement in private in the final hours of negotiations over different versions of the bill passed last year by both houses. The measure erased a provision for driving down unwarranted foreign trade surpluses that had been sponsored by erstwhile Democratic presidential hopeful <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version prevailed and I think that's unfortunate and I'm against the bill,'' the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> congressman told reporters. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration veto threats hovered over the legislation, and some members of the <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION> were disatisified with the bargain worked out between <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>. `` My chairman has reached an agreement with Sen. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and has laid it at the feet of the conferees with only a sort of very general discussion and is now winging his way to <LOCATION> Istanbul </LOCATION>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Minn </LOCATION>. He said that it was uncertain that <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> would be able to sell the package to other <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members of a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> trade conference committee. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials had been threatening a veto over provisions requiring employers to provide workers with notice of plant closings and the <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> sanctions. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo., said in a statement Thursday night that the plant closing provision and another relating to foreign investment `` clearly would sink the legislation unless they were removed. Thursday afternoon, however, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> appeared to back off a bit, saying that the administration was not trying to signal a veto and still hoped to receive a trade bill that it could sign. <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> told reporters before leaving on a congressional fact-finding trip to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> that he hoped to get sufficient members of the conference committee to sign the final product. `` When you get down to the serious negotiating, something has to lose sometimes and I understand that the administration is disappointed in some of this legislation,'' he said. Final arrangement began to fall into place Thursday morning when one of 17 separate groups of conferees adopted the trade sanctions against <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> and a subsidiary for selling computerized machinery to the Soviets for the silencing of submarine propellers. The measure would ban <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government purchases of <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> equipment for three years. It would bar import of products of the <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary for three years. In the future, such violations would be punishble by import bans of two to five years. The House had held out for leaving retaliation up to the president but Sen. <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Garn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, refused to accept that proposal and won out in the end. Another group of conferees broke up without taking action on a proposal by Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, to require registration of foreign property ownership in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. They said they would wrap up the issue in one final meeting after the spring break. Repeal of the windfall profits tax was a major goal of <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, who is running for reelection this year in a state hammered hard by low oil prices. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approved the tax in 1979 to when oil prices were soaring. But the collapse of <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> sent them plunging in 1985 and dried up revenues from the tax. Critics say they want repeal because the tax means costly paperwork. Farm lawmakers, meeting separately, said they were close to agreement on a provision that would put in place export subsidies of up to $ 500 million in 1990 unless negotiators reach agreement by then on phasing out agricultural subsidies under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. The so-called triggered marketing loan would benefit producers of wheat, feed grains, soybeans and other oilseed crops. Farm lawmakers also agreed on boosting by $ 1 billion the <ORGANIZATION> Export </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enhancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION>, which furnishes grain companies and others with surplus government crops to induce them to ship American grain overseas. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s plan would have required the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative to roll back `` excess and unwarranted'' foreign trade surpluses by 10 percent annualluy if negotiations failed to do the job. In its place, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> adopted a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> proposal that would require the trade representative to list foreign unfair trade practices and if necessary take action to force trading partners to end them. The agreement between the two also transferred authority to impose retaliatory import curbs from the president to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative _ a step that the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had vigorously opposed and which <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> had sought. But it provided authority to waive such retaliation if the cost `` would be substantially out of proportion to the benefits of action.'' The president would retain his authority to decide whether to grant import relief to industries that were hard hit by surges in imports.
